(24, 1, 'King Kong', '', 0, 1, 6, 25.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An <em>Audie Award </em>Finalist.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>King Kong</em> His very name inspires awe, horror, and for some of the greatest masters of contemporary <em>Science Fiction</em>, a strong affection.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005<em> Universal Pictures</em> launched a remake of the classic version (set in the original film&rsquo;s 1933 contemporary setting) under the <em>Academy</em> award-winning New Zealand director<em> Peter Jackson</em>, best known for directing the <em>The Lord of the Rings </em>film trilogy.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this special Collector&rsquo;s Edition of the original 1932 novelization of&nbsp; Cooper and Wallace&rsquo;s movie, 8 masters of Science Fiction -- <em>Ray Bradbury, Ray Harryhausen, Orson Scott Card, Harlan Ellison, Larry Niven, Catherine Asaro, Jack Williamson</em>, and <em>Marc Zicree</em> --tell what was it about the movie that inspired them.<br /><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SFFAudio.com:</strong> &ldquo;This audiobook is certainly special&hellip;.Not only does it gives fond memories of an absolutely iconic fantasy film, it also dispenses deeply insightful criticism and sharp commentary from those who were influenced by the film.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "Indeed this is perhaps the finest collection of commentary on <em>King Kong</em> ever collected&mdash;and that it could be recorded in the commentators&rsquo; own words, and in their own voices (except for Williamson), makes this a true treasure for the ages. Kudos to<em> Blackstone Audio</em>!&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Jack Williamson, Author of The Humanoids:</strong> &ldquo;King Kong still holds the force of its raw simplicity. More myth than monster, Kong suffers the fate of the classic tragic hero, destroyed by his own nobility. High-tech civilization overwhelms his primitive power. Beauty kills the beast.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AudioFile:</strong> "Stefan Rudnicki treats this pulpy novelization of the original Kong film with respect, allowing listeners to appreciate on its own terms the familiar story....Rudnicki&rsquo;s deep, craggy voice and seriousness help one past the campy or dated parts...."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Publishers Weekly:</strong> &ldquo;Rudnicki provides his melodious baritone... He keeps his characterizations diverse but restrained&hellip; and provides a fine, laid-back performance. Even more enjoyable are the commentaries found at the end...&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(25, 1, 'King Solomon''s Mines', '', 0, 1, 5, 25.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A brilliant work of adventure romance that has gripped readers for generations.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A bold elephant hunter journeys to an unknown land in Africa in search of a fabled lost treasure. But terrible dangers threaten anyone who approaches the wonderful diamond mines of King Solomon.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adventure alone was not enough for <em>Haggard</em>: &ldquo;The thing must have a heart.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So the book is filled with qualities close to the human heart: the spirit of adventure and discovery, the desire for immortality, primal terror, and the search for the primitive.&nbsp; And beyond all this lies a feeling for the supernatural.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Few knew the Dark Continent as <em>Haggard </em>did; his experience of savage life and wild lands lends a visceral credibility that makes us believe the impossible.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This great African adventure novel is an enduring favorite among those who love excitement and romance.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On board a ship bound for Natal, adventurer <em>Allan Quatermain</em> meets <em>Sir Henry Curtis </em>and <em>Captain John Good</em>. His new friends have set out to find <em>Sir Henry&rsquo;s</em> younger brother, who vanished while seeking King Solomon&rsquo;s legendary diamond mines in the African interior.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By strange chance, Quatermain has a map to the mines, drawn in blood, and agrees to join the others on their perilous journey.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The travelers face many dangers on their quest&mdash;the baking desert heat, freezing mountains, the hostile lost tribe they discover, and the evil &ldquo;<em>wise woman</em>&rdquo; who holds the secret of the diamond mines.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Graham Greene, New York Times bestselling author: </strong><em>&ldquo;Enchantment is just what Rider Haggard exercised&hellip;his books live today with undiminished vitality.&rdquo;</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Saturday Review:</strong> <em>&ldquo;Since Treasure Island we have seen no such healthily exciting volume.&rdquo;</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Andrew Lang:</strong> <em>&ldquo;A peculiarly thrilling and vigorous tale of adventure.&rdquo; Robert Sandels, Armchair Detective contributor: &ldquo; has an appeal and durability which leads one to wonder if it isn&rsquo;t more than just a well-told tale.&rdquo;</em><br /><br />The story continues on the sequel <em>Allan Quartermain</em>&hellip; also available here at <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(26, 1, 'Let''s Face It', '', 0, 1, 6, 26.95, 1, '', '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kirk Douglas</em> is a born storyteller, and in this engrossing memoir, he offers wonderful tales, favorite jokes, and hard-won insights.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As he explores the mixed blessings of growing older, <em>Kirk Douglas</em> looks back at his youth and his storied, glamorous life in Hollywood.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He tells delightful stories of the making of such films as <em>Spartacus</em> and includes anecdotes about such friends as <em>Frank Sinatra, Lauren Bacall, Ronald Reagan, Fred Astaire, John Wayne</em>, and<em> </em><em>Johnny Cash</em><strong><em>.<br /></em></strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Douglas reveals the secrets that have kept him happily married for more than five decades, and talks fondly of times spent with his sons and grandchildren.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He reflects upon his Jewish faith and offers strong opinions on everything from racism to corporate greed to the war in Iraq and the situation in Israel.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He writes about the need to care more about the world and less about ourselves, as he shares a lifetime&rsquo;s accumulation of wit and wisdom.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;Douglas <em>makes another splendid foray into his life, and Jason Alexander </em><em>excels in its narration. Alexander&rsquo;s voice is friendly and inclusive, and his speech patterns are well suited for Douglas&rsquo;s many remembrances....Alexander transforms the iconic movie star into the decent, humane man fans never knew&mdash;&rsquo;til now.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em><strong>Publishers Weekly:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Jason Alexander...speaks in a sage-like tone and pitch that capture the spirit and essence of Douglas....Alexander treats the material with grace and dignity....fans looking to savor a connection with a living legend will not be disappointed.&rdquo;</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(27, 1, 'Lost Boys', '', 0, 1, 16, 27.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From the bestselling storyteller<em> Orson Scott Card</em> comes a gripping story of terror within a small town. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Step Fletcher, his pregnant wife DeAnne, and their three children move to Steuben, North Carolina with high hopes. But Step&rsquo;s new job with a software company turns out to be a snake pit, and eight-year-old Stevie&rsquo;s school is worse. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As Stevie retreats into himself, focusing more and more on a mysterious computer game and a growing troop of imaginary friends, the Fletchers&rsquo; concern turns to terror. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Young boys, whose names match a list of Stevie&rsquo;s nonexistent friends, have mysteriously vanished from Steuben. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As evil strikes out from the most trusted corners, it&rsquo;s suddenly clear that Stevie is next on the list.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong><em> "....Rudnicki<strong> </strong></em><em>capturing the personalities of the children as well as the adults </em><em>draws on the intensity of the characters&rsquo; emotions, adding a compelling edge to the suspense."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Library Journal:</strong> <em>&ldquo;For Stephen King fans and those who like their suspense mixed with the supernatural.&rdquo;</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(28, 1, 'Lost on Planet China', '', 0, 1, 11, 20.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitled:</strong> <em>Traveling teaches you to appreciate the beauty and uniqueness of all the wonders encountered... like eating live squid</em>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hilarious!!!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Troost</em> charmed listeners with his humorous tales of wandering the remote islands of the South Pacific in <em>The Sex Lives of Cannibals and Getting Stoned with Savages.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em>When the travel bug bit again, he took on the world&rsquo;s most populous and intriguing nation.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Now Troost relates his gonzo adventure through China&mdash;dodging deadly drivers in Shanghai, eating yak in Tibet, deciphering restaurant menus (offering local favorites such as cattle penis with garlic), and visiting with Chairman Mao (still dead),<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He reveals a vast, complex country on the brink of transformation that will shape the way we all work, live, and think.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This insightful and hilarious narrative brings China to life as you&rsquo;ve never seen (or imagined it) before.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Library Journal:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Troost</em> <em>tackles modern China with his trademark wit and unstinting honesty. A genuine pleasure to read&hellip;. continued entertainment for the reader.&rdquo;</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Troost<strong> </strong>is refreshingly upbeat, without a hint of ugly American elitism....readers interested in a warts-and-all look at this complicated, evolving country will find this a rich education.&rdquo;</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(29, 1, 'Nightmare at 20,000 Feet', '', 0, 1, 11, 24.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>Horror Stories by Richard Matheson<br /><br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The imagined horror can be worst than the real.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Find out why <em>Stephen King</em> (who writes the introduction) has called <em>Matheson</em> one of his favorite writers.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Many of these stories have already entered into popular culture, including the title story, which became a landmark episode of <em>The Twilight Zone, </em>and <em>"Duel"</em>, the nail-biting tale of man versus machines that inspired <em>Steven Spielberg</em>&rsquo;s first film.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other stories include <em>&ldquo;First Anniversary,&rdquo; &ldquo;Dress of White Silk,&rdquo; &ldquo;Witch War,&rdquo; &ldquo;Dance of the Dead,&rdquo; &ldquo;Mad House,&rdquo; &ldquo;Prey,&rdquo; &ldquo;Blood Son,&rdquo; &ldquo;Crickets,&rdquo; &ldquo;Wet Straw,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Children of Noah,&rdquo; &ldquo;Through Channels,&rdquo; &ldquo;Old Haunts,&rdquo; &ldquo;Disappearing Act,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Holiday Man,&rdquo; &ldquo;Legion of Plotters,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Distributor,&rdquo; &ldquo;Long Distance Call,&rdquo; &ldquo;Slaughter House,&rdquo;</em> and <strong><em>&ldquo;</em></strong><em>The Likeness of Julie.&rdquo; </em><strong><em><br /></em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stephen King:</strong> "<em>Be warned: You are in the hands of a writer who asks no quarter and gives none. He will wring you dry... and when you finish he will leave you with the greatest gift a writer can give: He will leave you wanting more</em>."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Spanning almost half a century, the influential contents are as much a roadmap to the direction horror fiction has taken since the 1950s as to Matheson&rsquo;s own legacy of spare, scary chillers. In lieu of pedantic priers into the Unknown, he offers sympathetic everymen&hellip;.Matheson</em><em> strips away horror&rsquo;s traditional gothic clutter to expose ordinary landscapes that perfectly take the imprint of his characters&rsquo; paranoid fixations&hellip; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;The well-known title tale about a nervous air traveler is a showcase for the author&rsquo;s trademark less-is-more prose style, which suspenseful delineates a psychological tug-of-war between man and a monster that may be purely imagined. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "Timeless in their simplicity, stories are also relentless in their approach to basic fears.&rdquo;</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(30, 1, 'One is the Sun', '', 0, 1, 24, 34.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; The American "<em>Old West</em>" from a non-white perspective.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Based on a true story of indian mysticism that took 10 years of research and writing.<em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; One Is the Sun</em> is a historical novel about <em>Earth Thunder</em>, a great woman chief who lived in the mid-1800s in the US Northwest, and the six Germans who traveled from Bavaria on a "noble and dangerous quest" to find "the learned peoples . . . who loved the Goddess as well as the God.": knowledge stamped out in Europe by the Christian supremacy.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Surviving a massacre of wise Mayan priestesses, <em>Earth Thunder</em> flees her temple and journeys north to teach those who wish to know <em>Mother Earth</em> and Her great circles of life.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Meanwhile, a European noblewoman sends her family across the ocean to renew a spiritual link with native America.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Natives and travelers meet and build a new temple of learning in the <em>Deer Lodge</em> valley of Montana territory. There they live by the old wisdom of life: one is the Sun, two is the Earth&hellip;five is human self.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When enemies threaten to destroy them all, the <em>Deer Lodge</em> people will fight bravely and leave their mark in time.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A MUST for anyone interested in the history of what may have really happened in the American conquered West.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Francisco Chronicle:</strong> <em>&ldquo;Taps into both the current frenzy for goddess lore and renewed interest in American Indians...illuminating....&rdquo;</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Raver</em> <em>reads with a sense of empowerment and importance, giving each complicated character their own identity through a large arrangement of voices and tones. A memorable listening experience and powerful denouncement await those willing to give this story the time and respect it deserves.&rdquo;</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(31, 1, 'Paris Stories', '', 0, 1, 17, 27.95, 1, '', '<p>An <strong>Audie Award</strong> Nominee.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mysterious, funny, insightful, and heartbreaking, these are tales of expatriates and exiles, wise children and straying saints.<em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>Mavis Gallant</em> is a contemporary legend, a frequent contributor to <em>The New Yorker </em>for close to 50 years, and undisputed master of the short story whose peerless prose captures the range of human experience while evoking time and place with unequaled skill.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This collection of&nbsp;15 of <em>Gallant&rsquo;s</em> stories, edited and with an introduction by best-selling author Michael Ondaatje, gathers the best of her many stories set all over Europe.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All written in Paris where <em>Gallant<strong> </strong></em>has long lived. Together they compose a secret history, at once intimate and panoramic, of modern times.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Gallant&rsquo;s stories are filled with insights and wonderfully crafted sentences</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly:</strong> "<em>Mavis Gallant&rsquo;s finely honed prose captures the small details that illuminate a life</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Globe and Mail:</strong> "<em>Mavis Gallant </em><em>writes some of the most superbly crafted and perceptive stories of our time</em>.&rdquo;<strong><em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New York Times Book Review:</em></strong> &ldquo;<em>Ms</em>.<em> Gallant</em>...<em>has dared to drift in a disorienting century, always trusting her own imaginative compass. Her fiction, never fooled into trying to keep up with history, will last a long time</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(32, 1, 'Prentice Alvin', '', 0, 1, 14, 24.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em><strong>Book 3</strong> of The Tales of Alvin Maker <br /><br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A fictionalized American frontier life full of folk magic is even more engaging than the real one...<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; The saga of <em>Alvin Maker</em>, set in an alternative version of the American frontier country, continues in a tale full of folklore and magic <em>Orson Scott Card&rsquo;s </em><em>Tales of Alvin Maker </em>have created a moving fantasy world from the dream of America and the simple magic of the people who settled her.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Here is a world where folk magic is as much a part of life as hard work and religion, and where the red man and the white still have hope for living in peace with the land and each other.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A fantasy unique to literature. In this book young<em> Alvin</em> returns to the town of his birth and begins his apprenticeship with Makepeace Smith, committing seven years of his life in exchange for the skills and knowledge of a blacksmith.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But <em>Alvin</em> must also learn to control and use his own talent, that of a Maker, else his destiny will be unfulfilled.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Booklist:</strong> <em>&ldquo;With his tales of Alvin Maker series, Card</em><em>&rsquo;s alternative frontier America epic continues to be a significant event in fantasy publishing.&rdquo;<br /></em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly:</strong> <em>"A beguiling book. . .robust but reflective blend of folktale, history, parable and personal testimony, pioneer narrative. The series promises to be a story of deep delight."</em></p>\r\n<p>You can listen to other tiles of the series here on <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(33, 1, 'Prophecy be Damned', '', 0, 1, 12, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Book One</strong> in the <em>Tales of the Penitent Trilogy<strong><br /><br /></strong></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Not the usual fare of fairies, goblins and elves. The characters are unique and vary from ordinary peasants to magicians reminiscent of Merlin and a brave knight willing to die to keep his word.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Long ago, the youngest of the gods fell into the clutches of an ambitious mortal, a vain usurper who almost destroyed the world. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Elderkin, the old gods, imprisoned the mortal in the heart of a mountain and took away the young god&rsquo;s beauty, name, and tears. Then they fled the Earth, leaving man godless.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But they left a prophecy behind: that if the Nameless God&rsquo;s birthright is returned to him before the mortal breaks free, the Elderkin will return. Now, the burden of this prophecy rests on the shoulders of a reluctant boy called Sam. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a Scribe for the Guardians, the group of men and women dedicated to restoring the gods, by whom Sam has been mistreated, ordered about, and mind-scrambled. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yet, he has to fulfill the prophecy? The boy would much rather damn it than do it. But the choice may not be his to make. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The surprise ending will leave you eager for more.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(34, 1, 'Robinson Crusoe', '', 1, 1, 11, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Let your imagination carry you to the exotic coast of Brazil as you listen to <em>Robinson Crusoe&rsquo;s </em>adventures coping&nbsp; with survival, cannibals and pirates from whom he recaptures a mutinous ship to return to England.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Daily life in our 21rst century life is never this exciting!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Revisit the old time favorite which inspired the new <em>TV series &ldquo;Crusoe&rdquo; </em>and <em>Tom Hank&rsquo;</em><strong>s</strong> movie &ldquo;<em>Cast Away</em>&rdquo;.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Shipwrecked and cast ashore onto an uninhabited island,<em><strong> </strong>Robinson Crusoe</em> ingeniously carves out a solitary, primitive existence for twenty-four years.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eventually, he meets a young native, Friday, whom he saves from death at the hands of cannibals and makes him his companion and servant.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Crusoe and Friday share in a variety of adventures, including a fierce battle with cannibals and culminating with the heroes recapturing a mutinous ship and returning to England.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Based partly on the real-life experiences of Scottish sailor Alexander Selkirk, Defoe&rsquo;s novel of human endurance in an exotic, faraway land exerts a timeless appeal and has taken its rightful place among the great works of Western civilization.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Audio File:</strong> &ldquo;<em>John Lee&rsquo;s</em> <em>performance provides an excellent reason to listen to this classic of English literature. His deep voice recounts the memories of a sailor stranded alone on an island off the coast of Brazil. The story also gives Lee the opportunity to show his skill with the many accents of foreign sailors, adding a delightful authenticity to the yarn. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;Some narrators founder miserably in the sea of peculiar words used aboard sailing ships of the seventeenth century, but Lee handles them as though he has been aboard a ship all his life. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "Don&rsquo;t mistake this survival story as being intended solely for children, for it has all the complexities of language, suspense, and action adults love in great books</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(35, 1, 'Salambo', '', 0, 1, 12, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>High Priestess of Ancient Carthage</em> <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The eternal dichotomy which has torn men throughout history: religion and passion!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A tale of blood and thunder from the author of <em>Madame Bovary.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beyond the gardens of Hamilcar&rsquo;s palace, beyond the walls of Carthage, the Roman hordes stood waiting to annihilate the noblest city of ancient Africa. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After the First Punic War, Carthage is unable to fulfil promises made to its army of mercenaries, and finds itself under attack. The fictional title character, <em>Salambo</em>, a priestess and exquisite daughter of Hamilcar Barca, an aristocratic Carthaginian general, is the object of the obsessive lust of Matho, a leader of the mercenaries. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Within the city, all was madness: the houses were filled with the screams of women and the streets teemed with terrified men because he veil of the goddess Tanit, sacred to Carthage, had fallen into Matho&rsquo;s hands. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But when <em>Salambo</em> rides into the Roman camp, into Matho&rsquo;s tent, to exchange her beauty for the veil of Carthage&mdash;he stands ready to throw away victory and forsake his army, his nation, and his soul for the price of her body. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the midst of this historical struggle between Rome and Carthage, Flaubert&rsquo;s novel offers a richly detailed portrait of the lives and rites of two ancient kingdoms moved by their allegiances to very different gods.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(36, 1, 'Sarah', '', 1, 1, 13, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><em><strong>The Women of Genesis Series <br /><br /></strong></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The biblical <em>Sarah </em>seen through an exploring of human motives and the role of faith in individual lives.<em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>Sarah</em> takes on vivid reality as a woman desirable to kings, a devoted wife, a faithful follower of the God of Abraham, and chosen to experience an incomparable miracle.<br /><strong><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em></strong><em>Sarah</em> was a child of ten years, wise for her age but not yet a woman, when she first met Abraham.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He appeared before her in her father&rsquo;s house, filthy from the desert, tired and thirsty. But as the dirt of travel was washed from his body, the sight of him filled her heart. When Abraham promises Sarah to return in ten years to take her for his wife, her fate was sealed.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Abraham kept his promise, and Sarah kept hers. They were wed and joined the royal house of Ur with the high priesthood of the Hebrews.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So began a lifetime of great joy together, and greater peril: and with the blessing of their God, a great nation would be built around the core of their love.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Gabrielle de Cuir weaves beauty into the story, giving Sarah a strong personality and voicing her personal doubts</em>.<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly:</strong> &ldquo;<em>What <strong>Card</strong> does best: exploring human motives and relationships&hellip;.this playfully speculative novel succeeds in bringing Sarah&rsquo;s often overlooked character into vivid relief</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(37, 1, 'Scaramouche', '', 0, 1, 12, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><em><strong>Scaramouche</strong></em>...<em>one of the best historical romances of all time</em>.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "He was born with the gift of laughter and a sense that the world was mad..." begins the novel. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is the book that made Sabatini famous worldwide and those words became his epitaph, descriptive of both his leading character and himself. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Called "Scaramouche" by his enemies, a young man of unknown origins, impresses them all with his elegant orations and extraordinary swordsmanship. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With swordfights and romance, adventure and treachery, set against the backdrop of the French Revolution, Andr&eacute;-Louis Moreau starts with good prospects as a young lawyer. But an unfair duel with the ruthlessly cruel Count de La Tour d&rsquo;Azyr leaves Andr&eacute;-Louis&rsquo;s best friend dead and Andr&eacute;-Louis himself a fugitive from the King&rsquo;s justice. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While incognito, he becomes both a wildly popular actor and a firebrand of the Revolution. His vow to avenge his friend&rsquo;s murder leads him deeper into the political intrigues that surround the Revolution, and to a position of power. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But there are secrets to be revealed that will stun all of Paris.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(38, 1, 'Scotts Last Expedition', '', 0, 1, 19, 31.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>The Journals </em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The most famous of all the Polar explorers. This is his personal account, extracted from the journal he kept of their chilling adventure.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In November 1910, the vessel Terra Nova left New Zealand carrying an international team of explorers led by Robert Falcon Scott, an Englishman determined to be the first man to reach the South Pole.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scott kept a detailed journal of his adventures until March 29, 1912, when he and the few remaining members of his team met their ends in a brutal blizzard.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The daily progress of the expedition toward the pole is recorded in an immensely vivid and personal narrative, depicting the beauty of the Antarctic tundra, the harsh living conditions, and Scott&rsquo;s own desperation to beat rival explorers to the pole.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; KLIATT:</strong> &ldquo;<strong><em>Sutherland</em></strong> <em>reads in a matter-of-fact tone befitting a diary. He has a big-man&rsquo;s voice, masculine and robust&hellip;.Chilling authentic adventure written by someone who braved the worst nature could offer but never forgot that he and his fellows were gentlemen</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(39, 1, 'Seventh Son', '', 0, 1, 9, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>Tales of Alvin Maker</em>, <strong>Book 1 <br /><br /></strong>Named an <strong>American Library Association Best Book for Young Adults <br /><br /></strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From the best-selling author of the award-winning <em>Ender&rsquo;s Game</em> comes the unforgettable story of young <em>Alvin Maker</em>, the seventh son of a seventh son.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born into an alternative frontier America where life is hard and folk magic is real.<em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Alvin</em> is gifted with power, but he must learn to use his gift wisely. Dark forces are arrayed against <em>Alvin</em>, and only a young girl with second sight can protect him.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Library Journal:</strong> &ldquo;<em>A tribute to the art of storytelling</em>.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Booklist:</strong> &ldquo;<em>A consistently gripping tale featuring solid historical research and a keen understanding of religious experience. Another major effort by a world-class talent. Highly recommended</em>.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>KLIATT:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Truly marvelous and beautiful</em>.&rdquo; &ldquo;<em>Washington Post Book World:Seventh Son begins what may be a significant recasting in fantasy terms of the tall tale of America</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chicago Sun Times:</strong> &ldquo;<em>The most important work of American fantasy since Stephen Donaldson&rsquo;s Thomas Covenant Trilogy</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Locus magazine:</strong> &ldquo;<em>In Seventh Son Card</em> <em>achieves the near miracle of bringing something new to fantasy</em>.&rdquo;<br /><br />You can listen to other tiles of the series here on <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(40, 1, 'Shattered Air', '', 0, 1, 8, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>A True Account of Catastrophe and Courage on Yosemite&rsquo;s Half Dome<br /><br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On the evening of July 27, 1985, 5 hikers made a fateful choice to climb Yosemite&rsquo;s fabled Half Dome even as the sky darkened and thunder rolled.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By night&rsquo;s end, 2 would be dead from a lightning strike. The remaining 3, gravely injured, sparked the onset of a harrowing midnight helicopter rescue effort.<strong><em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em></strong><em>Shattered Air</em> is a haunting account of recklessness, tragedy, courage and rescue.&nbsp; A book whose depiction of Nature&rsquo;s power is tempered by unforgettable portraits of human courage and the will to survive.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A terrifying tale serves as a warning for others seeking to experience the extreme.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em><strong>Anthony Heald&rsquo;s</strong> slightly husky voice is perfect for this outdoor horror story. He adds foreshadowing when describing the gathering clouds, quickens the pace during the storm, and injects personality into the follow-up interviews. Listen and be educated, entertained and cautioned</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Francisco Chronicle:</strong> &ldquo;<em>If you&rsquo;ve ever felt cavalier about dealing with mountain thunderstorms, this drama about lightning and death should fix it.</em>&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Outdoor Guide:</strong> &ldquo;<em>A sobering and compelling story....Brilliant</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(41, 1, 'Shibumi', '', 0, 1, 16, 24.95, 1, '', '<p>An <strong>Audie&reg; Award</strong> Finalist<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Genius, mystic, master of language and culture, The protagonist&rsquo;s secret is his determination to attain a rare kind of personal excellence, a state of effortless perfection&mdash;<em>Shibumi.<br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nicholai Hel, born in the ravages of World War I China to an aristocratic Russian mother and a mysterious German father, raised in the spiritual gardens of a Japanese Go master, survives the destruction of Hiroshima to emerge as the world&rsquo;s most artful lover and its most accomplished and highly paid assassin.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Now living in an isolated mountain fortress with his magnificent Eurasian mistress, Hel faces his most sinister enemy, a super-monolith of espionage and monopoly.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The battle lines are drawn: ruthless power and corruption on one side and on the other, <em>Shibumi.<br /><br /></em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Los Angeles Times:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Novels about international intrigue demand intricate plotting. Shibumi delivers</em>.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>St. Louis Post-Dispatch:</strong> &ldquo;<em>A master of international intrigue</em>.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Trevanian&rsquo;s</em><em> seventies-era storytelling loses nothing in this audio treatment&hellip;Reader Joe Barrett embodies the author&rsquo;s voice ably, whether he&rsquo;s enigmatic assassin Nicholai Hel, narcissistic agency head Mr. Diamond, or a laughable Basque sidekick</em>.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Milwaukee Journal:</strong> &ldquo;<em>It&rsquo;s hard to imagine a more nearly perfect spy story.</em>&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; KLIATT:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Barrett, with his pleasing low-toned voice, narrates with skill, taking the time to develop Hel&rsquo;s personality along with his concubine, his deep-voiced Basque friends, the nasty Americans, and other multinational types. An intriguing listening experience with more depth than most books of this genre</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(42, 1, 'Songmaster', '', 0, 1, 12, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The story of the<em> Songmaster<strong> </strong></em>occurs in a future human empire where Ansset, a beautiful young boy whose perfect singing voice has the power of amplifying people&rsquo;s emotions, can be both a potential healer and destroyer.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kidnapped at an early age, Ansset has been raised in isolation at a mystical retreat called the <em>Songhouse</em>. His life is filled with music, and having only songs for companions, he develops a voice that is unlike any other.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When it is discovered that his is the voice that the Emperor has waited decades for, Ansset is summoned to the Imperial Palace on Old Earth.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Many fates rest in Ansset&rsquo;s hands, and his songs will soon be put to the test: either to salve the troubled conscience of a conqueror or drive him, and the universe, into mad chaos.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As with many of Card&rsquo;s works, this story is more about the interplay of people, and their moral issues, than it is about technology, although the Empire clearly has advanced technology.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Stefan Rudnicki narrates this novel with the power that the prose demands....Rudnicki, when called upon to do so, sings lines with an understated grace that effectively suggests the great abilities of the characters doing the singing</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SFFAudio.com:</strong> &ldquo;<em>The audiobook is narrated beautifully by Stefan Rudnicki. </em><em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;Mr. Rudnicki </em><em>conveys an introspective and measured performance that suits the novel perfectly....The recording is up to the usually high standards that we expect of a Blackstone audiobook</em>."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Science Fiction Site Review:</strong> &rdquo;This is a book full of depth and insight, and a cracking good story besides. It is a rare event when these two things coincide in a book, and a work can both enlighten and entertain at the same time. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;<em>Orson Scott Card</em> is a fine writer with great insight, great idealism, and love.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(43, 1, 'South', '', 0, 1, 13, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>A Memoir of the Endurance Voyage</em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Among history&rsquo;s greatest adventures... an astonishing story that explores the limits of human courage and determination.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This gripping first-hand account follows Shackleton and his men on their harrowing journey back to civilization: over 600 miles of unstable ice floes, on foot, 850 miles of the worst seas in an open twenty-two-foot boat, and then twenty miles of mountainous terrain to reach the nearest outpost of civilization.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An astonishing story<em> Shackleton&rsquo;s South</em> ranks among history&rsquo;s greatest adventures.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> "<em>Geoffrey Howard&rsquo;s splendid rendition conveys the genuine drama of the story without succumbing to false dramatics. His Shackleton has a deep-voiced charm; he is witty, calm and, most important, masterly in a crisis. In short, Howard&rsquo;s </em><em>Shackleton sounds exactly as we imagine an explorer should sound</em>."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>KLIATT:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Howard&rsquo;</em>s reading conveys both the urgency and the hope as Shackleton makes decisions on cutting rations and killing dogs, where to camp and when to press on.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(44, 1, 'South Sea Tales', '', 0, 1, 7, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eight tales of adventure, bravery, death, even humor portraying life in the South Seas in the days of tall ships &ndash; a century ago and extracted from the author&rsquo;s own experiences and exotic travels.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A rare pearl is fought over during a hurricane on a South Sea island.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; --- A zealous missionary sets out to spread the Gospel in a land of cannibals.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; --- The son of a Polynesian chief becomes the slave of a white man.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; These stories and others portray life in the South Seas in the days of tall ships a century ago.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In powerful and compelling language that seems not the least bit dated, <em>Jack London </em>tells eight tales of high daring and great savagery, of bravery and death, even of occasional humor, that could only take place in the exotic South Sea islands. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Based around themes<em> London </em>considered important&mdash;race, culture, justice, and heroism&mdash;the stories derive their intensity from the author&rsquo;s own far-flung adventures, conveying an impassioned, unsparing vision borne only of experience.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Lloyd James reads wonderfully, turning a one-man reading into a lyrical presentation that feels like a full-cast production. Not only does James handle half a dozen accents easily, he shifts pace to capture the cadence of London&rsquo;s vivid passages of extended description and allows London&rsquo;s near-poetry to ring out powerfully</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br /><br />Index of Contents:</strong><br /><br />1. &ldquo;<em>The House of Mapuhi</em>&rdquo; <br />2. &ldquo;<em>The Whale Tooth</em>&rdquo; <br />3. &ldquo;<em>Mauki</em>&rdquo; <br />4. &ldquo;<em>Yah! Yah! Yah</em>!&rdquo; <br />5. &ldquo;<em>The Heathen</em>&rdquo; <br />6. &ldquo;<em>The Terrible Solomons</em>&rdquo; <br />7. &ldquo;<em>The Inevitable White Man</em>&rdquo; <br />8. &ldquo;<em>The Seed of McCoy</em>&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(45, 1, 'Striking Back', '', 0, 1, 8, 25.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>The 1972 Munich Olympics Massacre and Israel&rsquo;s Deadly Response</em><br /><br />An <strong>Audie Award</strong> Nominee. <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A journalistic account of the events that inspired <em>Speilberg&rsquo;s</em> motion picture <em>Munich</em> about the massacre of the Israeli Olympic team by Palestine terrorists.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By the end of the 1972 ordeal at Munich&rsquo;s Olympic Village, the terrorist group had killed 11 Israeli athletes and coaches, and one West German police officer.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Five of the 8 members of <em>Black September</em> were killed by police officers during an abortive rescue attempt. The three surviving terrorists were captured but had to be released later in West Germany following the hijacking by <em>Black September</em> of a Lufthansa airliner.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Back in Israel, <em>Prime Minister Golda Meir vowed to track down those responsible and, in Menachem Begin&rsquo;s</em> words: &ldquo;Run these criminals and murderers off the face of the Earth.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A secret <em>Mossad</em> unit is mobilized, a list of targets drawn up. Thus begins the Israeli response, a mission that unfolds not over months but over decades.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>Mossad</em> never spoke about this operation. No one knew the real story, until &ldquo;<em>Strike Back&rdquo;</em>. In this riveting account, Aaron Klein peels back layers of myth and misinformation about the &ldquo;<em>shadow War</em>&rdquo; against <em>Black September</em> and other terrorist groups.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Gut-wrenching&hellip;Rudnicki reads with palpable revulsion at the bungling and indifference of the German government&hellip;his voice percolates with outrage and disbelief when Klein reveals how Israel&rsquo;s longstanding campaign for revenge has at times resulted in the deaths of innocent people</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(46, 1, 'The Adventures of Tom Sawyer', '', 0, 1, 7, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Just what did boys do in a small town during the mid-1800s, a time when there were no televisions, no arcades, and no videos?<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They whitewashed fences, floated down rivers, traded marbles, formed secret societies, smoked pipes, and, on occasion, managed to attend their own funerals.<br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Adventures of Tom Sawyer</em> is a humorous and nostalgic book depicting the carefree days of boyhood in a small Midwestern town during the mid-1800s. The characters are based on <em>Twain&rsquo;s </em>schoolmates and the town, Hannibal, Missouri, is where Twain grew up.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As Narrator,<em> Grover Gardner </em>excels at pacing T<em>wain&rsquo;s</em> story to deliver maximum drama, while creating memorable characters through accent and tone.Gardner&rsquo;s ability to capture a specific sense of time and place while also conveying<em> Twain&rsquo;s </em>timeless insights about human nature make this production one the author himself could happily approve.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em><strong>Grover Gardner</strong></em> <em>slips inside the humor and drama of this classic, casting a spell that vividly creates </em>Twain&rsquo;s<em> nineteenth-century setting for listeners. Whether dramatizing the exchange between two boys about to fight or that of clever Tom outwitting goodhearted Aunt Polly, Gardner highlights all the virtues of Twain&rsquo;s prose: that sly sense of humor, those deep insights into the human heart, whether glimpsed at a church funeral, a schoolyard, or a picnic gone wrong.</em>&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Booklist:</strong> "Gardner&rsquo;<em>s reading of Twain&rsquo;s classic convinces us why certain titles remain in the pantheon of must-reads (and must-listens). </em>Gardner&rsquo;s <em>resonant tones roll over the rich, extensive vocabulary, almost as if </em>Twain<em> himself were telling the story. He reads the varying country dialects in a natural manner, conveying Tom&rsquo;s spunkiness and quick wit. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;He uses higher pitches for the female characters, imparting an innocent breathiness into Becky Thatcher&rsquo;s dialogue and a solid, forthrightness into Aunt Polly&rsquo;s. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "Although the nineteenth-century language and syntax may seem a bit arcane, this delightful audio production makes it possible to enjoy this compelling tale, which might seem a bit daunting in book form</em>."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>KLIATT:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Twain intended his novel not just as a book for the young, but as a piece of nostalgia for the young at heart&hellip;.Gardner&rsquo;s performance is designed to realize </em>Twain&rsquo;s<em> intent&hellip;.He makes listeners pay attention to the words as well as the action. It&rsquo;s a relatively quiet reading&mdash;homey&mdash;as if told in retrospect by one&rsquo;s grandfather&hellip;.His forte is interpretation</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
