(47, 1, 'The Art of Being', '', 0, 1, 5, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To HAVE&hellip; or to BE&hellip; that is the question!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A subtitle to this book could be: &ldquo;<em>The art of trying to function in this life as a whole, real person in this consumer driven world</em>&rdquo; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The "a<em>verage man today</em>", Fromm observes, thinks very little for himself, and his capacity to concentrate has become "<em>a rarity</em>". <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He accuses modern man or living in a social milieu of mass communications which stunts his own thinking. Where political, ideological and religious clich&eacute;s are adopted in accordance with the social and economic class of each individual. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thus he makes a call to man to rediscover his own being by consciously breaking away from the consumer/property structure of our existence. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By learning to be centered in the self, the individual is less swayed by the endless pressures and dissatisfactions of the culture of consumerism. <strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Erich Fromm:</strong> <em>&ldquo;The situation of mankind is too serious to permit us to listen to the demagogues - least of all demagogues who are attracted to destruction - or even to the leaders who use only their brains and whose hearts have hardened. Critical and radical thought will only bear fruit when it is blended with the most precious quality man is endowed with - the love of life.&rdquo; <br /></em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(48, 1, 'The Canterville Ghost', '', 0, 1, 5, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A popular short story by Oscar Wilde, widely adapted for the screen, TV and stage.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The eternal clash of American and British cultures... set in a gothic haunted house and spiced with Wilde-wit!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The story takes place in an old English country house, Canterville Chase, which has all the&nbsp; of a traditional haunted house.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Typical of the style of the English Decadents, the gothic atmosphere reveals the author&rsquo;s fascination with the macabre. But he mixes the macabre with comedy, juxtaposing devices from traditional English ghost stories such as creaking floorboards, clanking chains, and ancient prophecies with symbols of modern American consumerism.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Silde&rsquo;s Gothic setting helps emphasize the contrast between the American and British cultures, underscoring the "modern" thinking of the house&rsquo;s mismatched residents.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After the refined Lord Canterville warns the practical American, Mr. Otis, about the ghost, Mr. Otis replies: &ldquo;But there is no such thing as a ghost, sir, and I guess the laws of Nature are not going to be suspended for the British aristocracy.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This audio production also includes a handful of his shorter works that demonstrate his range, versatility, and skill as a storyteller, too often overshadowed by his reputation as a dramatist, critical theorist and novelist.<br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; Wilde shows his wit in the social parodies &ldquo;<em>The Canterville Ghost,&rdquo; &ldquo;Lord Arthur Savile&rsquo;s Crime,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Sphinx without a Secret&rdquo;<strong> </strong></em>and &ldquo;<em>The Model Millionare&rdquo;.<br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In <em>&ldquo;</em><em>The </em><em>Portrait of Mr. W.H.</em><strong><em>&rdquo;</em></strong> he identifies the mysterious dedicatee of Shakespeare&rsquo;s Sonnets.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finally, the collection is rounded out by a selection of well known fairy tales, including &ldquo;<em>The Happy Prince,&rdquo; &ldquo;The Nightingale and the Rose&rdquo; &ldquo;The Selfish Giant&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Devoted Friend&rdquo;</em>.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ralph Keyes, Author of The Wit and Wisdom of Oscar Wilde:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Oscar Wilde&rsquo;s </em><em>writing remains fresh, alive, electric. His words stride off the page to grab us by the lapels and demand that we pay attention. &lsquo;You&rsquo;ve got to listen to what I&rsquo;m about to tell you,&rsquo; they insist. And we do, gladly.</em>&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Booklist:</strong> &ldquo;<em>A classic of Wildean wit and Victorian sentimentality....a delight</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(49, 1, 'The Count of Monte Cristo', '', 0, 1, 47, 49.95, 1, '', '<p>Winner of the <strong>AudioFile Earphones Award</strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Filled with thrilling episodes of betrayal, romance, and revenge&hellip; one of the greatest adventure stories ever written.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Let your imagination take you to be an absorbed witness of landscape of the world of intrigue, fated unrelenting love, opulence, misery and deprivation which Alexandre Dumas weaves in exquisite detail.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dashing young Edmond Dant&egrave;s has everything: a fine reputation, an appointment as captain of a ship, and the heart of a beautiful woman.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But his perfect life is shattered when three jealous friends conspire to destroy him. Falsely accused of a political crime, Dant&egrave;s is locked away for life in the infamous Chateau d&rsquo;If prison.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But it is there that Dant&egrave;s learns of a vast hidden treasure. After fourteen years of hopeless imprisonment, Dant&egrave;s makes his daring escape and follows his secret map to untold fortune.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disguised now as the mysterious and powerful Count of Monte Cristo, Dant&egrave;s seeks out his enemies, and nothing will stand in the way of his just revenge.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>John Lee </em><em>imbues this classic with exactly the right balance of solemnity and compassion. His light accents for characters of various nationalities give them individual personalities without overdoing them in the slightest.<strong> </strong>Lee<strong> </strong>works with Dumas&rsquo;</em><em> text to give each character complexity and emotion. The listener regrets the story&rsquo;s end, wishing to live with Edmund and his adventures just a little longer</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(50, 1, 'The Dragon''s Doom', '', 0, 1, 16, 27.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Book 4</strong> <em>in the Band of Four Series</em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Following the events of <em>A Dragon&rsquo;s Ascension</em>, <em>Hawkril</em> the mighty warrior, <em>Embra</em> the beautiful sorceress, and <em>Craer</em> the crafty thief, mourn their lost companion.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But now they must forge new alliances in their roles as Overdukes of Aglirta, a land that has been torn asunder by double-crossing royals, savage warlords, and sinister high priests.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Now, the kingdom is threatened by a mystical berserker plague that is promoting anarchy among the citizenry. Meanwhile, serpentine acolytes move in the shadows to try and resurrect a new Serpent.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Will a new Dragon rise to vanquish it?<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; The fate of Aglirta lies in balance in this triumphant conclusion of the <em>Band of Four </em>cycles.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Publisher&rsquo;s Weekly:</strong> "<em><strong>Greenwood</strong> continues to give his audience exactly what they want: fast, furious read</em>."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Booklist:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Every bit as good as its predecessors&hellip; The book&rsquo;s many conflicts and their resolutions are never simple-minded, and altogether this is a most respectable wrap-up to a highly readable saga.</em>&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dragon:</strong> "<em>Amazing and indescribable...thrilling action...fantastic magic...fast paced with an enormous barrage of pyrotechnics...all the genius of Greenwood action with all the genius of </em>Greenwood <em>characterization.</em>"</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(51, 1, 'The Fall of Che Guevara', '', 0, 1, 8, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How much was the US and the CIA got involved in the execution of Che in Bolivia?<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This book tells the dramatic story of the United States government&rsquo;s response to Guevara&rsquo;s ill-starred insurgency in Bolivia in 1967.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Historian Henry Butterfield Ryan argues that Guevara&rsquo;s life must be re-evaluated in light of secret documents released by the CIA, the State Department, the Pentagon and the National Security Council.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This dramatic account of the last days of Che Guevara is sure to appeal to scholars and students of United States foreign policy, Latin American history, military history, and to all others interested in this modern revolutionary&rsquo;s remarkable life.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Miami Herald:</strong> "<em>As a behind-the-scenes look into the issues and personalities that shaped U.S. foreign policy for Latin America... is fascinating.&rdquo;<br /></em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Journal of Military History:</strong> "Th<em>is work is well researched, utilizing Cuban, U.S., and Bolivian sources, and is a cracking good read</em>."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Washington Monthly:</strong> "<em>Ryan offers a thoughtful critique of both the operational and intelligence-gathering aspects of the U.S. intervention against the Cuban intervention in Bolivia... He enlivens his narrative with vivid portraits of the two American officials who played key parts in the hunt for Guevara... This is a welcome addition to the literature on both Che Guevara and U.S. intervention in Latin America</em>."</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(52, 1, 'The Hunchback of Notre Dame', '', 0, 1, 19, 31.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The original Beauty/Beast romance of 1831&hellip; set during Par&iacute;s&rsquo; Gothic era of extremes of architecture, passion, religion and politics, and written with a profound sense of tragic irony, Victor Hugo&rsquo;s powerful historical romance remains one of the most thrilling stories of all times<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From Walt Disney Productions to Peter Jackson&rsquo;s <em>King Kong</em>, it is the same story of fated crossed love between grossly unequal characters which has captivated the imagination of writers, poets, music composers, film, radio and TV producers during almost 2 centuries.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Victor Hugo&rsquo;s&nbsp; "<em>Hunchback of Notre Dame</em>&rdquo; has been the object of more than 14 film and TV adaptations in the XX century. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The consummated author of <em>Les Miserables</em>, employes the fated love of the underpriviledged creature to communicate his concerns about social justice and religious fanaticism... man&rsquo;s eternal conflicts equally relevant for us in the XXI century. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is the story of Quasimodo, the deformed bell-ringer of the Notre Dame Cathedral, who falls in love with the beautiful gypsy Esmeralda. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Esmeralda is condemned as a witch by the powerful and tormented Archdeacon who lusts after her, Quasimodo attempts to save her giving her sanctuary within the momental cathedral; but his intentions are tragically thwarted. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Strikingly, Hugo shifts his focus between characters, and assigns the roles of hero and villain to different characters at different points in the novel.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(53, 1, 'The Invisible Man', '', 0, 1, 6, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 1933 <em>Universal Pictures</em> produced the first version of <em>The Invisible Man</em>, considered to be one of the studio&rsquo;s great horror films of the 1930s. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chevy Chase starred on a 1992 comedy version, Memoirs of an Invisible Man, and in 2000 Hollywood released another film adaptation starring Kevin Bacon, Hollow Man.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the tradition of Mary Shelley&rsquo;s Frankenstein comes another undisputed classic of science fiction and horror to stir the imagination and conscience of the listeners. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; H.G. Wells created a gripping masterpiece about the destructive effects the invisibility has on the scientist and the insane and murderous chaos left in his malicious wake. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On a freezing February day in a small village of West Sussex, England, a stranger emerges from out of the gray to request a room at a local provincial inn. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Who is this out-of-season traveler? More confounding is the thick mask of bandages obscuring his face. Why does he disguise himself in this manner and keep himself hidden away in his room? <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aroused by trepidation and curiosity, the local villagers bring it upon themselves to find the answers. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What they discover is a man trapped in a terror of his own creation, and a chilling reflection of the unsolvable mysteries of their own souls.<br /><br /><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SFFAudio.com:</strong> &ldquo;<em>The psychological rigor that Wells brings to the novel makes The Invisible Man </em><em>quite possibly the first and last straight science-fiction story worthy of our attentions</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(54, 1, 'The Memory of Earth', '', 0, 1, 11, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Book 1</strong> in the <em>Homecoming Series</em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; High above the planet Harmony, the Oversoul watches.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Its task, programmed so many millennia ago, is to guard the human settlement on this planet, to protect this fragile remnant of Earth from all threats. To protect them, most of all, from themselves.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Oversoul has done its job well. There is no war on Harmony. There are no weapons of mass destruction. There is no technology that could lead to weapons of war. By control of the data banks and subtle interference in the very thoughts of the people, the artificial intelligence has fulfilled its mission.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But now there is a problem.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In orbit, the Oversoul realizes that it has lost access to some of its memory banks, and some of its power systems are failing. And on the planet, men are beginning to think about power, wealth, and conquest.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New York Times Book Review:</strong> &ldquo;<em>As always, Mr. Card</em><em> writes with energy and conviction</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Library Journal:</strong> "<em>One of the Science Fiction&rsquo;s most convincing storytellers.</em>"<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Seattle Times:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Card is a master storyteller</em>.&rdquo;<br /><br />You can find other titles of the series here on <strong>www.MundoHablado.com <br /></strong></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(55, 1, 'The Phantom of the Opera', '', 0, 1, 8, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>An <strong>Audie Award</strong> Finalist<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Love&hellip; obsession&hellip; tragedy...&nbsp; this story has it all!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The musical by <em>Andrew Lloyd Webber</em> based on this title has turned into the longest running Broadway show in history and one of the most lucrative entertainment enterprises of all time.&nbsp; More than 80 million people around the world have seen it during the last two decades.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Relive the passion and the characters in the haunting of the Opera.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A shadow of unease; a quickening pulse; an unnamed fear breathing on the collar of those who sit alone in their dressing rooms at the great Paris Opera.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An unbearable compulsion to glance quickly over a shoulder in the dark corridors to the stage would sometimes reveal a figure in evening clothes moving softly in the shadows&mdash;a figure no one could name.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nothing is done, however, until the disappearance of Christine Daa&eacute; during her triumphant performance.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With an increasing pattern of fear and violence, the Phantom of the Opera begins to strike but always with a beautiful young performer at the center of his deadly desires.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This production by <em>Blackstone Audio</em> and <em>Ralph Coshman</em> as the Narrator will keep your imagination captive for hours.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>New York Times Book Review:</strong> &ldquo;<em>The wildest and most fantastic of tales</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Ralph Cosham&nbsp;shines at moving the story briskly, effortlessly keeping it involving.&rdquo; </em>Ingram: &ldquo;A superb suspense story and dark tale of obsession.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Nation:</strong> &ldquo;<em>Ingenious&hellip;breathless suspense</em>.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(56, 1, 'The Picture of Dorian Gray', '', 0, 1, 8, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Picture of Dorian Gray </em>is the only published novel by<em> Oscar Wilde, </em>appearing as the lead story in Lippincott&rsquo;s Monthly Magazine on 20 June 1890.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The novel tells of a young man named Dorian Gray, the subject of a painting by artist Basil Hallward. Basil is impressed by Dorian&rsquo;s beauty and becomes infatuated with him, believing his beauty is responsible for a new mode in his art.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Talking in Basil&rsquo;s garden, Dorian meets Lord Henry Wotton, a friend of Basil&rsquo;s, and becomes enthralled by Lord Henry&rsquo;s world view. Espousing a new hedonism, Lord Henry suggests the only things worth pursuing in life are beauty and fulfillment of the senses.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Realizing that one day his beauty will fade, Dorian cries out, expressing his desire to sell his soul to ensure the portrait Basil has painted would age rather than himself.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dorian&rsquo;s wish is fulfilled and realizing that he will appear fresh and unspoiled no matter what kind of life he lives, Dorian becomes increasingly corrupt, unchecked by public opinion. Only the portrait grows degenerate and ugly, a powerful symbol of Dorian&rsquo;s internal ruin him into debauched acts.<br /><em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong></em>The Picture of Dorian Gray is considered one of the last works of classic gothic horror fiction with a strong Faustian theme. It deals with the artistic movement of the Decadents and homosexuality, both of which caused controversy when the book was published.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, in recent times, the book has been regarded as one of the modern classics of Western literature.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wilde&rsquo;s dreamlike exploration of life without limits scandalized its late-Victorian audience and has haunted readers&rsquo; imaginations for more than a hundred years.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AudioFile:</strong> "<em>Simon Vance&rsquo;<strong>s</strong> portrayal of each character is spot-on. His Lord Henry is casual, dismissive, and haughty. His Basil Hallward, the artist infatuated with Dorian, comes across as timid and pitiful but always endearing. Best of all, Vance&rsquo;s Dorian Gray exudes youth and impetuousness at the beginning, but quickly darkens once the character&rsquo;s madness takes hold...."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(57, 1, 'The Prestige', '', 0, 1, 13, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>Winner of <strong>AudioFile Earphones Award and the World Fantasy Award</strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hugh Jackman, Michael Caine, Christian Bale and David Bowie starred in the latest movie adaptation of <em>The Prestige.<br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>&nbsp; The Prestige</em> is one of Priest&rsquo;s most acclaimed novels, being winner of both the <em>World Fantasy Award </em>and the J<em>ames Tait Black Memorial Prize for Fiction.</em><span><span style="font-size: 16px;"><em></em></span></span><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 1878, two young stage magicians clash in the dark during the course of a fraudulent s&eacute;ance. From this moment on, their lives become webs of deceit and revelation as they vie to outwit and expose each other. Their rivalry will take them to the peaks of their careers&mdash;but with terrible consequences.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the course of pursuing each other&rsquo;s ruin, they will deploy all the deception their magician&rsquo;s craft can command, the highest misdirection and the darkest science. Blood will be spilled, but it will not be enough. In the end, their legacy will pass on for generations to descendants who must, for their sanity&rsquo;s sake, untangle their puzzle.<br /><br /><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> "<em>Priest&rsquo;s remarkable novel has been produced as an audiobook every bit as remarkable....Hearing Vance mellifluously pronounce words like &lsquo;prestidigitator&rsquo; as if they were part of his normal speech makes the book worth the time, but there is so much more....Vance expertly portrays these two men as their lives (and their tricks) are slowly revealed</em>."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SFFAudio.com:</strong> "<em>It&rsquo;s difficult to say how long it&rsquo;s been since I&rsquo;ve been so enthralled with an audiobook.... performance was stellar. Because of his subtle care, the surprises of the novel were enhanced....The result is an intricate web that is slowly unraveled throughout the book. It&rsquo;s an audiobook that merits a second listen</em>."</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(58, 1, 'The Savage Detectives', '', 0, 1, 27, 34.95, 1, '', '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Savage Detectives</em> is an exuberant, wildly inventive and ambitious novel from one of the greatest Latin American authors of our age. The late Chilean writer Roberto Bola&ntilde;o has been called the Garc&iacute;a Marquez of his generation.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this dazzling novel, the book that established his international reputation, Bola&ntilde;o tells the story of two modern-day Quixotes &mdash; the last survivors of an underground literary movement, perhaps of literature itself &mdash; on a tragicomic quest through a darkening, entropic universe.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Brilliantly rendered into English by Natasha Wimmer, the acclaimed translator of Bola&ntilde;o&rsquo;s other great masterwork,<em> 2666</em>. (also available here at <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>)<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>New York Times:</strong> <em>"Wildly enjoyable....Bola&ntilde;o beautifully manages to keep his comedy and his pathos in the same family."<br /></em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly:</strong> <em>"This novel will allow English speaking readers to discover a truly great writer... There are copious, and acidly hilarious, references to the Latin American literary scene, and one needn&rsquo;t be an insider to get the jokes... Bola&ntilde;o fashions an engrossing lost world of youth and utopian ambition, as particular and vivid as it is sad and uncontainable."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em><strong>Bookmarks Magazine:</strong> <em>"By turns humorous and sad, this literary mystery also affirms the value of literature and serves as a modern history of the Latin American literary scene... inventive and entertaining."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em><strong>Vogue:</strong> <em>"Roberto Bola&ntilde;o&rsquo;s masterwork...confirms this Chilean&rsquo;s status as Latin America&rsquo;s literary enfant terrible."</em><br /><br />You can also listen to Bola&ntilde;o&rsquo;s posthumous work, <em><strong>2666</strong></em>, here at <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(59, 1, 'The Sherlock Holmes Theatre', '', 0, 1, 5, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Blackstone Audio</em> is pleased to present the first ever audio recordings of the only two Holmes plays written by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle. This specially commissioned production by the <em>Hollywood Theater of the Ear </em>is a unique, must-have audio for all Sherlockians.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In <em>Sherlock Holmes: Professor Moriarity, the Napoleon of crime</em>, plots with would-be blackmailers to have Holmes killed. And the normally love-proof Holmes falls for an exceptional woman.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In The Speckled Band: What is the secret of the shocking death of poor Enid&rsquo;s sister, whose dying words were, "the speckled band"? Only Holmes can find the answer and save a helpless girl from certain death.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In Famed Detective&rsquo;s Flat: When Holmes retired, it created a financial crisis for his friend Watson, who owes money to mobsters who want either their cash or his blood.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The surprising upshot is: Ghastly Double Murder, a one-act comedy by Producer-Director <em>Yuri Rasovsky</em>. First time as an audiobook.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ForeWord magazine:</strong> <em>"Harkening back to the Golden Days of radio, these three audio presentations are outstanding. They are superbly produced, and the voice work by the performers is spot on..."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> <em>"Rasovsky combines a talented cast, spot-on sound effects and a rich musical score to achieve a stunning audio production. Every character, every cast member, every special effect, and every note of music merits applause."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Leisurebooks.com:</strong> <em>"An excellent Holmes radio production...with excellent performances by Martin Jarvis, Kristoffer Tabori, and a full cast. The sound and music are top notch, and over all there is so much to like about this performance.... takes you back to the days of gaslight and great detective stories!"</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(60, 1, 'The Story of the Red Cross', '', 0, 1, 4, 19.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The account of the founding years of one of the most important humanitarian organizations in the world, told by the woman who spearheaded the accomplishment. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With the emergence of the U.S. Civil War, <em>Clara Barton</em> dedicated herself to aiding soldiers on the front. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Never before had women been allowed in hospitals, camps or on battlefields. Initially, military and civil officials declined her help but, eventually, she gained the trust of these officials and began receiving supplies from all over the country. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result of her untiring work, she became known as the "<em>Angel of the Battlefield</em>". <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 1877 Clara Barton wrote a founder of the <em>International Red Cross, </em>offering to lead an American branch of the organization. Thus, at 56 she began a new career. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She founded the <em>American Red Cross </em>to help the unfortunate victims of wars and disasters. She served as its President from 1882, until 1904, at 83 years of age. <br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Red Cross </em>today stands as a living memorial to the lifelong efforts of this valiant lady.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(61, 1, 'The Sun and the Moon', '', 0, 1, 13, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>The Remarkable True Account of Hoaxers, Showmen, Dueling Journalists, and Lunar Man-Bats in Nineteenth-century New York</em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The legendary gullibility of population in the Big Apple is once more chronicled!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Orson Wells generated a mass exodus from the city of New York when he announced in a radio drama : "<em>The Martians are coming</em>!".<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the 1830s the rag newspaper, <em>The Sun</em>, convinced the urban dwellers that the moon was inhabited. This is a surprisingly true story.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Purporting to reveal the discoveries of a famous British astronomer, the series described such moon life as unicorns, beavers that walked upright, and four-foot-tall flying man-bats.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Not so surprisingly, the Sun&rsquo;s moon series quickly became the most widely circulated newspaper story of the era!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Told in richly novelistic detail, <em>The Sun and the Moon</em> brings the raucous world of 1830s New York City vividly to life, overflowing with larger-than-life characters such as Richard Adams Locke, author of the moon series, who never intended it to be a hoax at all; a fledgling showman named P.T. Barnum, who had just brought his own hoax to New York (his circus, <em>The Greatest Show on Earth</em>!); and the young writer Edgar Allan Poe, who was convinced that the moon series was a plagiarism of his own work.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kirkus Reviews:</strong> "<em>A delightful recounting of &lsquo;the most successful hoax in the history of American journalism&rsquo;....Goodman consistently entertains with his tale of press manipulation, hucksterism and the seemingly bottomless capacity for people to believe the most outrageous things. Absolutely charming</em>."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sky &amp; Telescope:</strong> "<em>A fascinating story about life in 19th-century New York, the savagely competitive newspaper business, and public entrancement with new sciences</em>."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Edwin G. Burrows, co-author of Gotham:</strong> "<em>The Sun and the Moon</em> <em>is flat-out fascinating&mdash;not only for its brilliant reconstruction of one of the great newspaper hoaxes of the nineteenth century, but also for the Dickensian characters who populate its pages, each more outlandish and outrageous than the other. Hats off to Goodman for one of the most entertaining books about New York City in quite some time.</em>"</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(62, 1, 'The Three Musketeers', '', 0, 1, 23, 31.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The greatest cloak-and-sword story ever written&hellip; now is being told!&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Enjoy&nbsp; once more the swashbuckling adventures of <em>The Three Musketeers.&nbsp; With the </em>Award winning Narrator, Simon Vance the immortal classic, never sounded better!<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>D&Aacute;rtagnon, Athos, Porthos</em> and <em>Aramis</em>, the heroes who loyally served the French Kings Louis XIII &amp; XIV,&nbsp;are back. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When the dashing young D&rsquo;Artagnon arrives in Paris from Gascony, he becomes embroiled in three duels with the three musketeers. But when he proves himself by fighting with, not against them, he forges the legendary friendship with the three who later become his comrades in arms when he is inducted into the Royal Guard and becomes a Musketeer himself. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The daring escapades of the four pit them against the devious master of intrigue, Cardinal Richelieu, and the quintessential wicked woman, Lady de Winter. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>The Three Musketeers</em> was first published in serial form in the magazine Le Si&egrave;cle between March and July 1844. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dumas&rsquo; characters have also inspired innumerable film versions, cartoons and video games.  listening to their antics through the voice of <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; You can also listen to the Musketeers&rsquo; sequel, <em>Twenty Years Later</em>, here at <strong>www.MundoHablado.com<br /></strong></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(63, 1, 'The Tortilla Curtain', '', 0, 1, 12, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><em> Audie&reg; Award</em> for Best Narration by the Author<br />Winner of the <em>Prix Medicis Entranger</em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The price of the American Dream... two parallel worlds collide in tragic-comic social satire.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Topanga Canyon is home to two couples unwillingly enrolled on a crash course about values what is really important in life.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Los Angeles liberals Delaney and Kyra Mossbacker lead an ordered sushi-and-recycling existence in a newly gated hilltop community: he is a sensitive nature writer, she an obsessive realtor.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mexican illegals Candido and Am&eacute;rica Rincon desperately cling to their vision of the American Dream as they fight off starvation in a makeshift camp deep in the ravine.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From the moment a freak accident brings C&aacute;ndido and Delany into intimate contact, these four and their opposing worlds gradually intersect in what becomes a tragicomedy of error and misunderstanding.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Booklist:</strong> <em>"This highly engaging story subtly plays on our consciences, forcing us to form, confirm, or dispute social, political, and moral viewpoints....Boyle manages to address these issues in a nonjudgmental fashion, depicting the vast inequity in the characters&rsquo; parallel existences."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Times Literary Supplement:</strong><em> "Boyle&rsquo;s style is punctuated with fire-cracker metaphors, a showy extravagance with obscurities of language and an easy mediation between hard fact and invention."<br /></em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Newsweek:</strong> <em>&ldquo;A rich and moving novel about the price of the American dream by America&rsquo;s most imaginative contemporary novelist.&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em><strong>AudioFile:</strong> <em>"T. C. Boyle&rsquo;s intimate connection to this story provides the precise character interpretation necessary for a high-energy and entertaining performance. His inclination for sarcasm, humor, and a wide range of emotions illuminates the turmoil behind the complicated national immigration issue."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(64, 1, 'The Vacant Throne', '', 0, 1, 15, 24.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Book 2</strong> in the "<em>Band of Four</em>" Series<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The master of fantasy adventure world building (<em>Dungeons &amp; Dragons</em>) returns with his magic and wizardry.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>Kingless Land</em> is kingless no more, for the <em>Sleeping King</em> of legend, King Kelgrael, has been awakened by the efforts of the "<em>Band of Four</em>": <em>Hawkril</em>, a bold and brave warrior gifted with great strength and fortitude; <em>Craer</em>, the crafty and clever thief; <em>Sarasper</em>, the learned and wise healer; and, last but not least, <em>Lady Embra Silvertree</em>, the mystical Lady of Jewels, a powerful sorceress.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With the aid of the magical powers of the <em>Dwaerindim Stones,</em> the King&rsquo;s curse has been lifted. But it will take more than the power of a single Dwaerindim to allow him to occupy the long-vacant throne of the land, for there are ambitious and devious barons ready to challenge him for his royal dominion.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While inhuman and dark forces lurk, the "<em>Band of Four</em>" must set out again on an arduous quest for the secret that will allow the kingdom to return to the safety and prosperity of its former glory.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Romantic Times:</strong> <em>"Packed with action, quirky twists of fate, magic, blood, and gore, Mr. Greenwood delivers a rollicking adventure story with complex characterization that is as enjoyable as it is entangled."<br /></em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AudioFile:</strong> <em>"Langton&rsquo;s narrative voice is strong, and he helps to bring both characters and story alive."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(65, 1, 'The Women', '', 0, 1, 19, 22.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The life of <em>Frank Lloyd Wright,</em> as told through the experiences of the four women who loved him, blazes with <em>T. C. Boyle&rsquo;<strong>s</strong></em> trademark wit and invention.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; World reknown architect<em> Frank Lloyd Wright</em>&rsquo;s life was one long, howling struggle against the bonds of convention, whether aesthetic, social, moral, or romantic.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Despite the overblown scandals surrounding his amours and the financial disarray that dogged him, he never let anything get in the way of his larger-than-life appetites and visions.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Yet, Wright&rsquo;s triumphs and defeats were always tied to the women he loved: the Montenegrin beauty.<em> Olgivanna Milanoff;</em> the passionate Southern belle Maud Miriam Noel; the spirited <em>Mamah Cheney</em>, tragically killed; and his young first wife, <em>Kitty Tobin</em>.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New York Times Book Review:</strong> <em>&ldquo;A mesmerizing story of women who invested everything, at great risk, in that mysterious &lsquo;bank of feeling&rsquo; named Frank Lloyd Wright</em>.&rdquo;<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; BookPage:</strong> "<em>Boyle</em><strong>&rsquo;</strong>s <em>exuberance, a good match for Wright&rsquo;s</em><em>, and his skillful blending of history and invention animate this extraordinary fictional portrait of Wright and his women</em>."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Washington Post Book World:</strong> "<em>A strangely riveting novel....Call it a thinking man&rsquo;s soap opera....It&rsquo;s the writing that pulls you through, and it&rsquo;s the writing that will reward you in the last scene of this...(sometimes deliciously) overwrought novel. <strong>Boyle</strong> is a marvel at descriptive prose....</em>"<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers Weekly Audio:</strong> "<em>Rising and falling in steady rhythm, soothing even when the story unsettles and surprises, </em>Grover Gardner&rsquo;s voice is a fine instrument. He delivers a stellar rendition nimbly skipping from character to character of Boyle&rsquo;s reimagining of Frank Lloyd Wright&rsquo;s<em> tortured relationships with his wives and lovers. Readers will be entirely immersed in the hothouse world of the architect and his women."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(66, 1, 'Worst Journey in the World', '', 0, 1, 21, 31.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A drama documentary, also entitled <em>The Worst Journey In The World</em>, was broadcast on<em> BBC Four</em> in April 2007. Also there was a 2-part radio drama produced by the <em>BBC </em>in 2008.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A true story of the toughest expedition to the South Pole where the effort and tireless fortitude of the men involved was truly epic.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At its conclusion one is left by the sense of deep admiration for those who reached beyond their normal selves, against overwhelming odds to achieve the impossible, not for riches, nor fame, but for the sake of universal human knowledge and achievement.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is&nbsp;an account of Robert Falcon Scott&rsquo;s last fateful expedition to the Antarctic, as told by surviving expedition member Apsley Cherry-Garrard full of human warmth for the men who undertook the journey.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cherry-Garrard tells of the journey from England to South Africa and southward to the ice floes, where began the unforgettable polar journey across a forbidding and inhospitable region.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It took 3 years of back-breaking, teeth-shattering work, to get five people to the tip of the world. The fact that it was all carried out in sub-zero temperatures, gale-force winds and six months of perpetual darkness demonstrates that these men were a breed apart.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On November 12, 1912, in arctic temperatures, Cherry-Garrard, in a search party, found the bodies of Scott and his companions, along with their poignant last notebook entries. Those final entries of his dying comrades are included in this book and make the telling truly heart rendering.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Garrad&rsquo;s background in the arts and humanities makes The Worst Journey in the World stand out as a literary accomplishment as well as a classic in the annals of exploration.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; National Geographic&rsquo;s Adventure magazine: </strong><em>"The <strong>#1</strong> adventure book of all time</em>"<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New York Times:</strong> "<em>A great book of Antarctic exploration."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Paul Theroux:</strong> "<em>A masterpiece....It is about courage, misery, starvation, heroism, exploration, discovery, and friendship. It vividly illustrates the demands of science and the rigours of travel. It is a record of the coldest darkest days that can be found on our planet. It is written beautifully but not obviously, with a subtle artistry....It is rare to find a person who is at once a great traveller, recounting an overwhelming experience, and who is also such an accomplished writer...."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(67, 1, 'The Worthing Saga', '', 0, 1, 19, 27.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It was a miracle of science that permitted human beings to live, if not forever then for a long, long time... those who could afford the luxury, anyway.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It allowed great plans to be put into motion, interstellar empires to be built, but it&nbsp;came near to destroying humanity.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The rich, the powerful... lived their lives at the rate of one year every ten. Some created two societies: that of people who lived out their normal span and died, and those who slept away the decades, skipping over the intervening years and events.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After a long, long time of decadence and stagnation, a few seed ships were sent out to save our species. Each carried human embryos and supplies, teaching robots and one men.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>The Worthing Saga </em>is the story of one of these men, Jason Worthing, and the world he found for the seed he carried. <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>SFFAudio:</strong> "<em>A gripping story...Even though the book is decades old, it could pass for being written this year. Technology advances, but relationships and moral dilemmas are timeless, and both are Mr. Card&rsquo;s stock in trade."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em><strong>KLIATT:</strong> <em>"Scott Brick maintains his interest and enthusiasm throughout in his narration."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(68, 1, 'Titanic', '', 0, 1, 7, 22.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subtitle:</strong> <em>A Survivor&rsquo;s Story</em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Archibald Gracie was probably among the last to leave the sinking Titanic.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this unique account, he describes his personal experiences and remarkable escape from death in the icy waters of the Atlantic, painting a vivid picture of what it was like on board the  on that cold April night in 1912, one of the most traumatic events in maritime history. Titanic in its final hours.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But not content with his own recollections he tracked down other survivors to collect their stories and attended court hearings to obtain the official records. All of that documentation is part of this non-romantic eye-witness retelling of their gruesome experiences during the fated voyage in spite of the illness to which he finally succumbed, 8 months later in 1912.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His early death was largely due to the effects of his ordeal and exposure to the frigid waters of the Atlantic when the Titanic sank.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His book was published in 1913 to universal acclaim and remains one of the most vivid and first-hand accounts of the disaster.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Library Journal:</strong> "<em>This very elegantly written narrative by a man who actually did sink with the ship (he was later hauled into a lifeboat) is often riveting....Titanic buffs will love this on-the-spot reporting; others will also find much to enjoy and ponder."<br /></em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Philadelphia Enquirer:</strong> <em>"Sometimes amazingly priggish, at others unwittingly funny, the Colonel </em><em>was also possessed of a fierce tenacity, a sturdy kind of dignity, and a feeling of controlled outrage at what he thought was gross negligence."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(69, 1, 'Twenty Thousand Leagues', '', 0, 1, 12, 20.95, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This Jule Verne&rsquo;s most famous novel, earned him the title of <em>"Father of Science Fiction". </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Through unforeseen dangers and exotic settings, this epic adventure is a tour-de-force of imagination and narrative grandeur.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em> "The year 1866 was signalized by a remarkable incident, a mysterious and puzzling phenomenon, which doubtless no one has yet forgotten....For some time past, vessels had been met by &lsquo;an enormous thing,&rsquo; a long object, spindle-shaped, occasionally phosphorescent, and infinitely larger and more rapid in its movements than a whale." </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When Professor Aronnax agrees to investigate a series of attacks by a mysterious sea monster, he begins an incredible underwater journey that leads him from Atlantis to the South Pole.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jules Verne was remarkably successful in foretelling the wonders science held for the future, like the submarine, television and space travel. <br /><br /><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; School Library Journal:</strong> <em>"Jules Verne&rsquo;s classic offers a perfect blend of suspense, adventure, and excitement that will entice even the most reluctant readers."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
