(177, 1, 'Dark Dude', '', 0, 2, 8, 19.95, 1, '', '<p><strong>Pulitzer Price Author<br />ALA Best Books for Young Adults <br />International  Latino Book Award<br />Los Angeles Times Book Prize Nominee<br /><br /></strong><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Rico Fuentes</em> is a &ldquo;<em>fish-out-of-water</em>&rdquo; because his skin is  too light for the New York ghetto and his Latin roots are too loud for  the prejudices in rural America.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From<em> Pulitzer Prize-winning  novelist Oscar Hijuelos </em>comes an unforgettable journey about  identity, choices, and the way in which we all struggle to accept our  true selves.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In gritty, clear prose,<em> Dark Dude</em> captures  New York City in the 1960s&mdash;violent, decaying, slouching away from the  American dream&mdash;and brings to life a character who has no choice but to  head out west in search of something better.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In an effort to  escape the violence and decay New York City in the 1960s, at the ripe  old age of 15, Rico Fuentes heads out West looking for the American  Dream.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the Midwest, Rico could blend in, his light hair and  lighter skin disguising his background. He would no longer be the "dark  dude", the punching bag for the whole neighborhood.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Trading  Harlem for Wisconsin, though, means giving up on a big part of his  identity. And when Rico no longer has to prove that he&rsquo;s Latino, he  almost stops being one.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; But the light hair Cuban-American  youngster, and his multi-colored skin friends, soon find that the white  picket-fenced rural Wisconsin community can be as cruel and judgmental  as the one he fled from in the eastern city ghetto because there are  some things that can&rsquo;t be left behind, things that will follow you a  thousand miles away.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Then he is forced to swallow an  uncomfortable truth: no longer an outsider by his appearance, Rico is  still an outsider. It is a vibrant, gritty and funny rite of passage  account.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The prized author <em>Oscar Hijuelos</em> explores the  universal theme of self identity demonstrating through <em>Rico&rsquo;</em>s  ordeals that who you are has nothing to do with where you are or how you  look. Rico&rsquo;s journey of self acceptance is not unlike the one embarked  on by the millions of Latins who live in the United States.<strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  AudioFile:</strong> <em>"With parallels to Huck Finn&rsquo;s journey, Rico&rsquo;s story  of self-discovery is skillfully chronicled by Armando Dur&aacute;n, whose ease  with accents is noteworthy. He seamlessly delivers the many Spanish  phrases interspersed throughout the text and conveys Rico&rsquo;s sense of  alienation and bewilderment when he experiences injustice and random  violence in the rural Midwestern community."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publishers  Weekly (starred review):</strong> <em>"... themes are classic&mdash;alienation, the  search for identity&mdash;but his approach is pure Hijuelos</em><em>:  Cuban-American, musical and very, very funny...he inevitability of the  conclusion doesn&rsquo;t matter: it&rsquo;s the smooth, jazzy flow of the narration,  the slides between Rico&rsquo;s rootlessness and the book&rsquo;s strong sense of  place that count."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em><strong>Booklist (starred review):</strong><em> "Hijuelos<strong> </strong>proves himself to be a powerful, adept storyteller for  teens...Frank, gritty, vibrant, and wholly absorbing, Rico&rsquo;s story will  hold teens with its celebration of friendship and its fundamental  questions about life purpose, family responsibility, and the profound  ways that experience shapes identity."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; KLIATT:</strong><em> "High school readers will appreciate the struggles and the humor of  being a fish out of water."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(178, 1, 'Marian McPartland''s Jazz World', '', 0, 2, 7, 24.99, 1, '', '<p><em><strong>Subtitle: </strong>All in Good Time</em><em><br /><br /></em>A <strong>MUST Collector&rsquo;s Edition</strong> for all  Jazz lovers.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This recording is a veritable "<em>Who&rsquo;s Who"</em> of the best and greatest in Jazz.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this collection of musical  portraits, jazz pianist and radio host <em>Marian McPartland </em>pays  sparkling tribute to such beloved and legendary figures as <em>Benny  Goodman, Bill Evans, Joe Morello, Paul Desmond, Alec Wilder, Mary Lou  Williams,</em> and others.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In a preface to this new  edition&mdash;published originally as <em>All in Good Time&mdash;McPartland</em> extends her commentary to include details of her long-running <em>National  Public Radio show Marian McPartland&rsquo;s Piano Jazz</em> and memories of  her late husband, famed Chicago trumpeter<em> Jimmy McPartland.Bonus  Feature!</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This recording includes special excerpts from  Marian&rsquo;s highly successful program, <em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; Marian McPartland  Piano Jazz,</em> featuring interviews with <em>Rosemary Clooney, Bill  Evans, Oscar Peterson, and Mary Lou Williams.</em><strong><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  AudioFile:</strong> "This is an audio treasure, whether you&rsquo;re a current fan  of this beloved jazz pianist and her long-running public radio program  or you&rsquo;re new to her work. It&rsquo;s clear that it&rsquo;s been a joyful life as  McPartland reads essays and remembrances over the decades&mdash;her joie de  vivre and true immersion in jazz and its great artists come through loud  and clear. Her soft London-influenced voice has made a friendly truce  with an American accent&mdash;the overall effect is like being invited to tea  or bourbon with a savvy, kind, and talented lady of the arts. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  "The bonus CD with excerpts of McPartland&rsquo;s interviews with such jazz  greats as Bill Evans and Oscar Peterson is the topper."<strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New  York Times:</strong> <em>"She has done her studying from the inside: as one of  the few working jazz musicians to write about the music with any  frequency, she offers a perspective on the men and women who play jazz  for a living that seldom finds its way into print."</em><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San  Diego Union Tribune:</strong> <em>"Marian McPartland </em><em>is that rare  combination, a first rank jazz musician who also can write about her  music, its milieu and musicians... writes with wit, acumen, and  vivacity."</em><strong><br /><br />Contents of the Special Bonus features:</strong> <br /><br />Foreword  by <em>James T. Maher</em> <br />--- You&rsquo;ve Come a Long Way<br />--- Baby  Halcyon Days: Remembering the Hickory House <br />--- The Fabulous <em>Joe  Morello </em><strong><em><br /></em></strong><em>---&nbsp; Joe Morello:</em> With a Light  Touch <br />--- Perils of Paul: A Portrait of Desperate Desmond <br />---  Into the Sun: An Affectionate Sketch of <em>Mary Lou Williams</em><strong><em><br /></em></strong>---  Just Swinging: <em>Jake Hanna </em><strong><em><br /></em></strong>--- Benny Goodman:  From the Inside&mdash;the Sideman&rsquo;s View <br /><em>--- Bill Evans,</em> Genius <br />---  Looking to the Future:<em> Ron McClure</em> and <em>Eddie Gomez</em> <br /><em>---  Dudley Moore:</em> Serious Music from a Colossus of Comedy <br />--- The  Untold Story of the International Sweethearts of Rhythm <br /><em>--- Alec  Wilder</em>: The Compleat Composer <br />--- Conversation with <em>Rosemary  Clooney</em> <br />--- "My Shining Hour" Duet <br />--- Conversation with <em>Oscar  Peterson</em> <br />--- "Emily" Solo <br />--- "Space Playing Blues" <br />---  Conversation with <em>Mary Lou Williams</em> <br />--- Conversation with <em>Bill  Evans</em> <br />--- "The Touch of Your Lips" Duet</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(179, 1, 'The Picture of Dorian Gray', '', 0, 2, 8, 19.95, 1, '', '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Picture of Dorian Gray </em>is the only published novel by<em> Oscar Wilde, </em>appearing as the lead story in Lippincott&rsquo;s Monthly  Magazine on 20 June 1890.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The novel tells of a young man named  Dorian Gray, the subject of a painting by artist Basil Hallward. Basil  is impressed by Dorian&rsquo;s beauty and becomes infatuated with him,  believing his beauty is responsible for a new mode in his art.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Talking in Basil&rsquo;s garden, Dorian meets Lord Henry Wotton, a friend of  Basil&rsquo;s, and becomes enthralled by Lord Henry&rsquo;s world view. Espousing a  new hedonism, Lord Henry suggests the only things worth pursuing in life  are beauty and fulfillment of the senses.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Realizing that one  day his beauty will fade, Dorian cries out, expressing his desire to  sell his soul to ensure the portrait Basil has painted would age rather  than himself.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dorian&rsquo;s wish is fulfilled and realizing that he  will appear fresh and unspoiled no matter what kind of life he lives,  Dorian becomes increasingly corrupt, unchecked by public opinion. Only  the portrait grows degenerate and ugly, a powerful symbol of Dorian&rsquo;s  internal ruin him into debauched acts.<br /><em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong></em>The Picture  of Dorian Gray is considered one of the last works of classic gothic  horror fiction with a strong Faustian theme. It deals with the artistic  movement of the Decadents and homosexuality, both of which caused  controversy when the book was published.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; However, in recent  times, the book has been regarded as one of the modern classics of  Western literature.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wilde&rsquo;s dreamlike exploration of life  without limits scandalized its late-Victorian audience and has haunted  readers&rsquo; imaginations for more than a hundred years.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>AudioFile:</strong> "<em>Simon Vance&rsquo;<strong>s</strong> portrayal of each character is spot-on. His  Lord Henry is casual, dismissive, and haughty. His Basil Hallward, the  artist infatuated with Dorian, comes across as timid and pitiful but  always endearing. Best of all, Vance&rsquo;s Dorian Gray exudes youth and  impetuousness at the beginning, but quickly darkens once the character&rsquo;s  madness takes hold...."</em></p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(180, 2, 'Solo el miedo muere', '', 0, 2, 0, 24.99, 1, '', '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; S&oacute;lo el miedo muere</em> es una de las obras m&aacute;s importantes de este prestigioso autorl.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A trav&eacute;s de sus ocho ensayos nos transmite ense&ntilde;anzas b&aacute;sicas en relaci&oacute;n al modo en que dentro de nosotros se crea la infelicidad y qu&eacute; hacer para apartarnos de ella. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Describiendo el proceso espiritual que denomina &ldquo;morir por la vida&rdquo;, nos muestra:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &bull; C&oacute;mo escapar a las limitaciones impuestas por la personalidad.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &bull; C&oacute;mo aportar mayor verdad a nuestras vidas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &bull; C&oacute;mo el virus de la infelicidad corrompe nuestra civilizaci&oacute;n.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &bull; Las consecuencias k&aacute;rmicas que nos persiguen a trav&eacute;s de la vida e incluso despu&eacute;s de la muerte.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &bull;Lo que cada uno de nosotros puede hacer para liberarse de la infelicidad con el fin de poder disfrutar plenamente de la vida. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; S&oacute;lo el miedo muere es un acertado llamamiento a redescubrir la libertad y la felicidad que nos asiste como seres humanos. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sobre todo, Barry Long desea que sepamos que es posible y pr&aacute;ctico llevar una vida apacible. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Podemos ser libres ahora y para siempre...&nbsp; s&oacute;lo si el miedo muere.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(181, 2, 'Rosas negras', '', 0, 2, 9, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En su narrativa, tanto en novela como en cuento, Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua transgrede las reglas del mundo cotidiano para intentar, a trav&eacute;s de personajes que a veces llegan del "m&aacute;s all&aacute;", comprender mejor el "m&aacute;s ac&aacute;".<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Esta es la historia de Bernab&eacute; G&oacute;ngora, una "luminaria" del pueblo  de San Cipriano, que mientras come con su esposa y amigos siente un  dolor repentino en el cuerpo causado, se sospecha, por un cintur&oacute;n de  metal que le lleg&oacute; de Estados Unidos y que se ha puesto para mejorar sus  habilidades en la cama. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bernab&eacute; G&oacute;ngora , apacible y hedonista mueblero portifiriano, muere pero en vez de pasar a mejor vida, simplemente pasa a ser testigo, desde el candil del restaruante donde muri&oacute;, de todas las intrigas que hormiguean en la peque&ntilde;a ciudad provinciana de San Cipriano.&nbsp; Intrigas entre las que se encuentran los intentos de unos cuantos por conquistar a su viuda, los afanes de ella por comunicarse con &eacute;l mediante el espiritismo y el estupor del presidente municipal ante la misteriosa bomba pestilente que alguien ha lanzado a su casa augurando una posible revoluci&oacute;n&hellip; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Enemiga declarada de toda seriedad, Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua vuelve a crear una provincia imaginaria para entregarnos una comedia metaf&iacute;sica de enredos en la que el espiritismo, la electricidad con sus poderes y las fantasmagor&iacute;as entretejen una meditaci&oacute;n sobre la naturaleza del cuerpo.<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (La segunda novela de Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua, <em>P&uacute;rpura</em>, tambi&eacute;n puede escucharse aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablaod.com</strong>)</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(182, 2, 'Purpura', '', 0, 2, 8, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Con un humor incisivo y refrescante, y una&nbsp; prosa elegante y par&oacute;dica, Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua explora los entrepisos y los mecanismos de la sociedad mexicana a trav&eacute;s de las peripecias, andanzas, aventuras, y desventuras, amores y desamores de un joven provinciano que llega a la ciudad de M&eacute;xico.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La autora hace entrega de un detallado cuadro de &eacute;poca que hacia 1940 modernizaba usos y costumbres de una sociedad ansiosa de elegancia y cosmopolitismo donde el joven Artemio compaginar&aacute; las sorpresas diarias de la gran ciudad con sus ambiciones de superarse y de llegar a formar parte de la alta sociedad de un M&eacute;xico por cuyas calles circulaban los Packards norteamericanos y un general presid&iacute;a los designios del pa&iacute;s. <br />&nbsp;<em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; P&uacute;rpura </em>es una novela de iniciaci&oacute;n a la vida en la que Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua, con una prosa precisa y contundente, nos invita a dar un paseo por los encantos de la frivolidad y el descubrimiento de los placeres. <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em> P&uacute;rpura</em>, es la segunda novela de Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua.&nbsp; (La primera,<em> Rosas Negras</em>, tambi&eacute;n puede escucharse aqui en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>)</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(183, 2, 'Parece que va a llover', '', 0, 2, 9, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Parece que va a llover es una particular y mordaz visi&oacute;n del mundo contempor&aacute;neo donde la sin raz&oacute;n y la incomunicaci&oacute;n son el pan de cada d&iacute;a de nosotros, los mortales que vivimos en la &ldquo;posmodernidad&rdquo;.&nbsp;&nbsp; Uno de los grandes problemas a los que nos vemos abocados como seres modernos es &ldquo;el juicio&rdquo;. Enjuiciar es tomar posici&oacute;n, es arriesgarse a hablar, a acertar (o no).<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Juana Villegas, un mujer de 29 a&ntilde;os que se ha quedado sin madre, sin empleo, sin dinero y va camino al consultorio donde va a interrumpir su primer embarazo porque se resiste a ser la madre de alg&uacute;n hijo de su futuro esposo y se niega a que la gente que la ha visto como un ejemplo se entere de que ha ca&iacute;do en la desdicha m&aacute;s com&uacute;n entre adolescentes. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Todo sucede ese d&iacute;a en que ella va a abortar &hellip; en unos cuantos minutos.&nbsp; Pero, como el mundo se niega a detenerse ante su desdicha y confusi&oacute;n, los hechos, las preguntas, las conjeturas comienzan a perderse en su propia cabeza. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entretejidas, las an&eacute;cdotas, las situaciones, las miradas, las relaciones humanas avanzan, amasando una personalidad, y poblando una ciudad bajo un cielo amenazante. Momentos notables de intimidad entre la protagonista y el lector, en los que parece que los dos compartieran un solo paraguas, sobre el mundo y bajo la amenaza del tiempo. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Personajes que ceden su voz a nuestras preguntas, hacen suyos nuestros miedos e incertidumbres; preguntas que sirven de respuesta a nuestra desconocida y apenas presentida identidad. Personajes cuya suerte parece la nuestra.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Y en definitiva, un solo d&iacute;a puede prefigurar el universo, y un solo ser humano ser reflejo de lo com&uacute;n que hay en todos nosotros: bestia y &aacute;ngel.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La novela se ha basa en esos criterios sociales del mundo &ldquo;moderno&rdquo; para ilustrarnos&nbsp; una sociedad que ans&iacute;a nuevos &oacute;rdenes de pensamiento para poder lograr una existencia m&aacute;s vivible.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tendr&iacute;a que llover, para que todo fuera peor de lo que es&hellip; pero finalmente no llueve.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(184, 2, 'Tic', '', 0, 2, 8, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sebasti&aacute;n Bernal es un abogado de &eacute;xito: est&aacute; casado, tiene dos hijos y sus cejas se levantan con un tic tan sexy que las mujeres le encuentran irresistible. Todas las que se dejan fascinar por ese gesto involuntario corren el riesgo de caer en la red de este c&iacute;nico ser humano. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gabriel Castillo es un acreditado pediatra que dedica su vida a sus pacientes, a sus amigos y a su familia. No existe persona m&aacute;s amable. Lee diariamente el peri&oacute;dico, hace todos los crucigramas y adora las canciones tristes y el blues. Su vida s&oacute;lo tiene algo imperfecto y fuera de control: est&aacute; enamorado de la esposa de Sebasti&aacute;n. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Una ma&ntilde;ana el abogado despierta y se da cuenta de que est&aacute; en el cuerpo de otra persona. Trata desesperadamente de volver al suyo y hacerle ver a la gente que alguien est&aacute; usurpando su existencia. Pero su otro yo ha empezado a cambiar su vida y es posible que nadie quiera al verdadero Sebasti&aacute;n de vuelta. Mientras, debe acomodarse a un cuerpo enfermo y darse unas vacaciones obligadas de su propia vida.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>&nbsp; Tic</em> es una divertida y perturbadora novela donde las casualidades muestran lo absurdo de muchas actitudes y lo falso que subyace en las buenas costumbres. Disfrutarla a fondo es saber re&iacute;rse de uno mismo, dejar de escuchar la divertida historia es tan dif&iacute;cil como librarse de un tic.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(185, 2, 'Relato de Navidad en la Gran Via', '', 0, 2, 9, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El protagonista, Pablo Uribe, un hombre solitario, desafortunado y amargado, primero se lleva por equivocaci&oacute;n, porque es igual al suyo, el auto de la familia Silva que vive en la gran V&iacute;a.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Al percatarse del error lleva el auto a la casa de sus due&ntilde;os, ingresa al departamento de los Silva que est&aacute; vac&iacute;o porque est&aacute;n de vacaciones&hellip;. y se dedica a plasmar en el computador que encuentra all&iacute; el texto de esta novela con sus m&aacute;s oscuros secretos, y se va... pero, no sin antes llegar a la conclusi&oacute;n que el mundo ser&iacute;a mejor si no sali&eacute;ramos tanto de nuestras casas.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La raz&oacute;n del ejercicio literario de Uribe, en el computador secuestrado, es plasmar memorias obscenas para despotricar contra una familia, un pa&iacute;s y un mundo que, aparte de existir, en realidad no le han hecho nada malo a &eacute;l.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cuando Ricardo Silva regresa a su casa encuentra el archivo en el computador, intrigado y entusiasmado con lo que lee, se dedica a a&ntilde;adir notas al pie de p&aacute;gina al texto original para,&nbsp; con gran humor e iron&iacute;a, hacer p&uacute;blica la novela de una antigua y juvenil visi&oacute;n del mundo proyectada desde una soledad irredimible durante la &eacute;poca navide&ntilde;a. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El verdadero autor colombiano, Ricardo Silva Romero, lleva toda su vida en un edificio en Bogot&aacute; llamado La Gran V&iacute;a, y a pesar que &eacute;l s&oacute;lo se adjudica el papel de &lsquo;editor y comentarista&rsquo; de la novela, se sospecha que en realidad se trata de una extra&ntilde;a autobiograf&iacute;a&hellip; &iexcl;una &uacute;ltima prueba de la existencia de un hombre!</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(186, 2, 'Ni chicha,  ni limonada', '', 0, 2, 5, 25.50, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Los trece relatos que conforman este libro est&aacute;n entretejidos de manera tan ajustada que pueden ser le&iacute;dos como los cap&iacute;tulos de una novela. Los mismos personajes entran y salen, sufren y discuten, se redimen o condenan en un escenario doble que abarca por partes iguales a Guatemala y Estados Unidos, pero que de alguna manera existe menos en la geograf&iacute;a del mundo que en la de las relaciones humanas, cada vez m&aacute;s palpables a medida que leemos. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Utilizando una prosa clara y dejando que el libro fluya desde la ni&ntilde;ez a la madurez, David Unger logra que una parte de la historia reciente de Latinoam&eacute;rica &mdash;la de los golpes de estado, el antisemitismo, el exilio y los sentimientos ambiguos en relaci&oacute;n a EEUU&mdash; encuentre un eco en la vida privada de una familia guatemalteca que decide probar suerte en el gran pa&iacute;s del norte.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La religi&oacute;n, el sexo, el trabajo, las relaciones familiares y la b&uacute;squeda de una vocaci&oacute;n son algunos de los temas que atraviesan el libro, que cobra fuerza en su segunda mitad, cuando la vida ha dado vuelta su p&aacute;gina y los adultos del principio se han debilitado o borroneado hasta transformarse en fantasmas, dejando en su&nbsp; lugar a una nueva generaci&oacute;n que intenta no caer en las mismas trampas.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>&ldquo;Ni chicha ni limonada&rdquo;</em> parece ser la etiqueta aplicable a ese vasto grupo de exiliados que creci&oacute; haciendo equilibrio entre una cultura y otra, y que tuvo que esforzarse por poner en foco su lugar en el mundo.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El lenguaje del libro repite dichos ya idos de Guatemala, una  jerga que se fue alrededor de los setenta y se llev&oacute; a los &uacute;ltimos que  hablaron de sus sue&ntilde;os en cantinas de las que apenas quedan dos o tres,  afamadas y mantenidas con historias fantasmales de un lapso del que  nadie escap&oacute;. Ni chicha ni limonada&hellip; ni lo uno ni lo otro.&nbsp; La frase  abre de lleno la brecha de la inconsistencia de la identidad.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Guatemala y Am&eacute;rica Latina se hunden, y sabemos que no somos ni  chicha, ni li&not;&not;&not;monada, sino lo que el momento determine sin menci&oacute;n del  futuro. En este libro de Unger la religi&oacute;n suena igual que la  Doc&not;&not;trina Monroe. Describe al que no puede hablar porque est&aacute; fuera de  contexto en un pa&iacute;s y una cultura extra&ntilde;a.&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n &ldquo;fueron ni chicha,  ni limonada&rdquo; todos los que sab&iacute;an lo que pasaba en Guatemala en los 60s y  70s: que se estaba cambiando la libertad de un pueblo por unos peque&ntilde;os  intereses econ&oacute;micos.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lo que se infiere en la obra es que Guatemala (as&iacute; como el resto de  Am&eacute;rica Latina) en alg&uacute;n momento tendr&aacute;n que decidir entra la chicha y  la limonada.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(187, 2, 'No hay principe', '', 0, 2, 9, 25.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Por supuesto que las pel&iacute;culas de Disney han contribuido con la fantas&iacute;a del pr&iacute;ncipe azul que bajar&aacute; del caballo blanco, pero tambi&eacute;n nuestras madres han hecho su trabajo. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el libro, se resumen una gran cantidad de pensamientos transmitidos de generaci&oacute;n en generaci&oacute;n, de madres a hijas. <br /><br />Por ejemplo:<br />&bull; Tu madre nunca te dijo que tienes la posibilidad de cambiar tus expectativas.<br />&bull; Tu madre nunca te dijo que la forma de ser de tu padre y el modo en que te trataba ejercer&iacute;a un gran efecto sobre ti y tus relaciones. <br />&bull; Tu madre nunca te dijo que optar por cosas nuevas significa darle la espalda a lo que ya no necesitas. <br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Y ahora, &iquest;c&oacute;mo seguir adelante sin un pr&iacute;ncipe a quien buscar?<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La respuesta es que no hay pr&iacute;ncipe... &iexcl;pero hay una multitud de hombres maravillosos a la espera de una mujer como t&uacute;!<br /><br />Si alguna vez ...<br />- te has enamorado de alguien que no era lo mejor para ti;<br />- te has conformado con un hombre porque no quer&iacute;as estar sola;<br />- intentaste cambiar a alguien para que fuera lo que t&uacute; deseabas;<br />- mantuviste una relaci&oacute;n negativa durante demasiado tiempo;<br />- has estado con una persona que no quer&iacute;a lo mismo que t&uacute;;<br />- has ignorado las se&ntilde;ales que indicaban que la relaci&oacute;n no funcionar&iacute;a;<br />- has dicho que "s&iacute;" cuando quer&iacute;as decir "no", o no pensaste en ti misma en el contexto de una relaci&oacute;n...<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ... entonces sabes lo doloroso que resulta encontrarte en una situaci&oacute;n equivocada con el hombre inadecuado. Y quiz&aacute;, tras tantos desenga&ntilde;os amorosos, la sola idea de empezar de nuevo te parezca absurda o demasiado complicada.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Basado en el famoso taller de Life Works, te ayudar&aacute; a hallar lo que  para ti es verdadero y de qu&eacute; forma mantener la relaci&oacute;n que realmente  est&aacute;s esperando. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sea cual fuere tu situaci&oacute;n, si a&uacute;n anhelas tener un hombre bueno en tu vida, las autoras nos ofrecen una gu&iacute;a c&aacute;lida y sumamente clara que aborda con ternura y amor c&oacute;mo mantener la relaci&oacute;n que deseas con un hombre. Ayud&aacute;ndote primero a amarte a ti misma, te animan y ense&ntilde;an a mirar a tu alrededor para que descubras la gran cantidad de hombres adecuados que desean amarte y ofrecerte lo que t&uacute; deseas.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(188, 2, 'Mil y una muertes', '', 0, 2, 10, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La obra comienza con un relato en primera persona en la cual que el autor cuenta que en su viaje a Varsovia en 1987 dio, de forma accidental, con una exposici&oacute;n fotogr&aacute;fica titulada <em>El fot&oacute;grafo Castell&oacute;n</em> en Varsovia, en la que hab&iacute;a fotos dispares como la casa&nbsp; natal de Chopin en Zelazowa Wola, as&iacute; como de escenas de fusilamientos cometidos por la Gestapo. De ah&iacute; nace el inter&eacute;s del autor por conocer qui&eacute;n era ese fot&oacute;grafo de apellido Castell&oacute;n.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pero las voces en este relato son m&uacute;ltiples.&nbsp; No se limitan a las de Ram&iacute;rez- narrador y la de Castell&oacute;n. Tambi&eacute;n hacen su aparici&oacute;n&nbsp; un sin numero de personajes de la historia universal con los que tiene alg&uacute;n contacto el fot&oacute;grafo Castell&oacute;n, tales como el mercenario Walter, Napole&oacute;n el peque&ntilde;o, Flaubert y George Sand, chopin y Rub&eacute;n Dar&iacute;o&hellip; incluso la reina Victoria y personajes como Wenceslao Vivorny y el archiduque Luis Salvador.&nbsp; Entre todos se ir&aacute; tejiendo la narrativa hasta conformar el juego literario que es toda la obra.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es un complejo estudio fotogr&aacute;fico, es una suerte de collage de im&aacute;genes tomadas por un lente imaginativo y reveladas en el cuarto oscuro de la memoria&hellip; un atrapante ambular por pasajes hist&oacute;ricos que muestran adem&aacute;s el surgimiento y ca&iacute;da de ideales, sue&ntilde;os y grandes empresas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Por &uacute;ltimo, el resultado es un fotograma compuesto de palabras que en s&iacute; mismo es un repaso de an&eacute;cdotas, relatos y episodios fotografiados por un nicarag&uuml;ense rescatado del olvido.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El autor, Sergio Ram&iacute;rez insiste en hacernos creer que &eacute;l es quien busca al personaje, pero en realidad Castell&oacute;n es quien persigue a lo largo de varios a&ntilde;os a Ram&iacute;rez, hasta encontrarlo y obligarlo a escribir su historia porque lo apasiona la manera en que Castell&oacute;n logra captar la historia y el destino de la humanidad, con fotograf&iacute;as o escritos&hellip; inventando a partir de hechos y personajes de la vida real.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &iquest;Cu&aacute;nto hay de cierto en todo lo que se relata? &iquest;Cu&aacute;nto es ficci&oacute;n? <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; No importa.&nbsp; As&iacute; como los libros de historia contienen m&aacute;s de una falsedad, las novelas pueden poblarse con mentiras que terminan por ser verdades.&nbsp; Como en otras legendarias profesiones, lo importante es que la mentira se manifieste de manera cre&iacute;ble y placentera.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(189, 2, 'Nicolas', '', 0, 2, 12, 29.99, 1, '', '<p><strong>Libro 3</strong> de la serie <em>&ldquo;Dejados atr&aacute;s&rdquo;</em><br /><br /><strong>Bestseller #1</strong> del New York Times, USA Toda y Publisher&rsquo;s Weekly<br />M&aacute;s de <strong>65 millones</strong> de ejemplares vendidos a nivel mundial<br /><br /><strong>Subt&iacute;tulo:</strong> <em>El surgimiento del anti-cristo</em><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Basada en las profec&iacute;as que aparecen en los libros de la Biblia Revelaciones, Daniel, Isaia y Ezekiel para el fin de los tiempos, todos estos libros se han ubicado en el #1 de las listas de Bestsellers del New York Times, USA Today y Publisher&rsquo;s Weekly. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Los cuatro primeros libros de la serie se mantuvieron simult&aacute;neamente en los cuatro primeros lugares de la lista de los m&aacute;s vendidos del New York Times.&nbsp; Las ventas totales de la serie han superado 65 millones de ejemplares a nivel internacional.<br />Las dos pel&iacute;culas fueron &eacute;xitos taquilleros, la segunda siendo s&oacute;lo superada cuando se lanz&oacute; por El hombre ara&ntilde;a y en Amazon fue la #1 en ventas del DVE.&nbsp; Seg&uacute;n el New York Times la popularidad de la serie se debe a que est&aacute; escrita con el mismo tipo de acci&oacute;n y dinamismo que caracteriza las obras de Tom Clancy o Stephen King, <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El<strong> tercer libro</strong> enfoca la atenci&oacute;n en Nicol&aacute;s Carpatia, el anti-cristo, seg&uacute;n va consolidando su poder al unificar y controlar la pol&iacute;tica, econom&iacute;a, religi&oacute;n y medios de comunicaci&oacute;n&nbsp; en una comunidad global.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mientras, ante el asedio de las fuerzas militares, el Comando Tribulaci&oacute;n del pueblo contin&uacute;a su lucha por sobrevivir y proteger sus familias en medio de guerras y destrucci&oacute;n global. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Resulta aparente que el caos creado por Nicol&aacute;s corresponde a las profec&iacute;as de Juan de los siete sellos en el libro de Revelaciones.&nbsp; Y ahora ya se enfrentan al sexto sello, un terremoto de proporciones mayores a menudo designado como la &ldquo;la ira del cordero&rdquo;. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &iquest;Qui&eacute;n sobrevivir&aacute;?&nbsp; &iquest;Cu&aacute;les son los planes finales de Nicol&aacute;s para el mundo?</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(190, 2, 'Un Dios para Cordelia', '', 0, 2, 6, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La trama toma prestado detalles de la realidad del abuso sexual al que se ven sujetas las estrellas en la televisi&oacute;n latina.&nbsp; El libro es un s&aacute;tiro an&aacute;lisis de la mentalidad anti-feminista de la mujer latina y los nefastos efectos que tienen en sus vidas creencias religiosas y patriarcales.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Una novela que ofrece todo un crisol de &aacute;nimos, desventuras y pesares, de una generaci&oacute;n que hoy vive y padece la impredecible, pero a&uacute;n fascinante, aventura de la existencia. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es una historia sobre dos mujeres: una famosa cantante, Cordelia, incapaz siquiera de entonar, y su doble, Iris, quienes habitan un mundo en donde a los dioses los crean los hombres; nunca al rev&eacute;s.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estos dioses existen en un mundo que invade un dios Impostor&mdash;arribista y sibilino&mdash; quien reinventa el cielo a imagen y semejanza del infierno&mdash;y ah&iacute; es donde viven los hombres.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El primer d&iacute;a el dios crea el pavimento, el segundo los embotellamientos luego&nbsp; la contaminaci&oacute;n, etc&eacute;tera.&nbsp; El producto final es algo muy similar al ca&oacute;tico y corrupto mundo de una ciudad como la de M&eacute;xico. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Este dios Impostor acaba con la fascinaci&oacute;n en que viv&iacute;an los otros dioses; provoca luchas internas y acaba por dar forma humana a todos los habitantes del antiguo pante&oacute;n. Los dioses pierden sus caracter&iacute;sticas originales y acaban por permitir&mdash;como los hombres&mdash;que un tirano imb&eacute;cil, carente de imaginaci&oacute;n, los manipule. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Luego, un dios del tiempo&mdash;en tr&aacute;nsito hacia su inevitable humanizaci&oacute;n&mdash;deviene narrador y con paciencia dolorosa teje la urdimbre donde las historias de Cordelia e Iris, y la suya propia, se insertan en ese &ldquo;mundo de los hombres&rdquo;, sobrepoblado e ingobernable, apocal&iacute;ptico. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Narrado por la propia autora, este audiolibro le garantiza una experiencia memorable.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(192, 3, 'Un regalo de graduaci&oacute;n', '', 0, 2, 4, 24.50, 1, '', '<p><strong>Subt&iacute;tulo:</strong> Lo que sab&iacute;a de ni&ntilde;a y olvid&eacute; en la carrera de la vida&hellip;<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Escrito para su hija y toda la generaci&oacute;n, aborda ense&ntilde;anzas que estos j&oacute;venes que han crecido en medio de la revoluci&oacute;n tecnol&oacute;gica, nunca recibieron en sus en sus recintos universitarios.&nbsp; Sin embargo, el mensaje es v&aacute;lido a cualquier edad para refrescar lo que adultos tambi&eacute;n pueden haber olvidado de la magia de ser ni&ntilde;os.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;El libro busca fomentar la exploraci&oacute;n del&nbsp; potencial del hombre.&nbsp; Ilustrando complejos conceptos con&nbsp; ejemplos simples y an&eacute;cdotas personales, la autora busca ayudar a revivir esos poderes innatos con los que&nbsp; todos&nbsp; nacemos para que, de adultos, puedan ser a&uacute;n m&aacute;s efectivos que de ni&ntilde;os activando la magia a voluntad, conscientes de lo que hacen, c&oacute;mo y por qu&eacute;. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Su mensaje es que la vida no tiene que se dura, el mundo no va hacia su destrucci&oacute;n y en la vida no hay que aprender a golpes.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Todo lo contrario, que hoy nos encontramos&nbsp; en el umbral de un nuevo mundo donde nada ser&aacute; imposible; donde todo lo que se necesitar&aacute; para conseguir algo es desearki; donde todos&nbsp; estar&aacute;n en total control de sus destinos; donde las palabras &ldquo;por favor&rdquo; y &ldquo;gracias&rdquo; recuperar&aacute;n&nbsp; su magia;&nbsp; donde toda b&uacute;squeda por conocimiento ser&aacute; una fascinante aventura;&nbsp; donde habr&aacute;n juguetes (y abundancia) para todos&hellip; y entenderemos que somos seres multidimensionales.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Tal como se lamenta la autora al revelar lo que ha ido aprendiendo en su trayectoria por la vida,&nbsp; sus logros&nbsp; le habr&iacute;an resultado mucho m&aacute;s f&aacute;ciles si s&oacute;lo alguien le hubiera dicho en su juventud lo que ella ahora comparte con todos.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(194, 2, 'Vivir con diabetes', '', 0, 2, 9, 24.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unas 40,000 personas mueren de diabetes en Latinoam&eacute;rica anualmente.&nbsp; La incidencia de la enfermedad sigue en aumento y afecta m&aacute;s las poblaciones urbanas y personas mayores.&nbsp; De modo que es importante entender qu&eacute; puede hacer la persona para afrontarla llevando una vida saludable y feliz a pesar de la condici&oacute;n. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La educaci&oacute;n sanitaria y la actitud del paciente diab&eacute;tico constituyen una parte esencial del tratamiento de esta enfermedad.&nbsp; Es, por ello, sumamente importante que las personas diab&eacute;ticas conozcan, con fundamento y exactitud, qu&eacute; es la diabetes y cu&aacute;l es su tratamiento. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es &eacute;ste un libro para que tanto los pacientes como sus familiares conozcan bien la diabetes, para mantener una actitud positiva ante esta enfermedad que les acompa&ntilde;ar&aacute; siempre, para llevar un buen control metab&oacute;lico y para alcanzar una vida sana y feliz. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es una gu&iacute;a que proporciona toda la informaci&oacute;n que precisan los enfermos y quienes con ellos se relacionan (familiares y cuidadores). Su cualidad fundamental es que est&aacute; escrita desde la &oacute;ptica del paciente. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Por ello, adem&aacute;s de tratar extensamente la faceta m&eacute;dica, tambi&eacute;n incorpora ese lado humano que ni el m&eacute;dico ni la medicina contemplan, como por ejemplo: c&oacute;mo afrontar el proceso psicol&oacute;gico y emocional de la enfermedad, alteraciones del car&aacute;cter, experiencias compartidas por los enfermos, el significado profundo de la enfermedad o c&oacute;mo cuidar y apoyar al diab&eacute;tico.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Incluye, tambi&eacute;n, una importante secci&oacute;n dedicada a los padres de ni&ntilde;os diab&eacute;ticos.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(195, 2, 'Vivir en el maldito tr&oacute;pico', '', 0, 2, 14, 29.99, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Son los a&ntilde;os ochenta, vientos dif&iacute;ciles azotan Centroam&eacute;rica y tambi&eacute;n a la familia Eltalef; los hermanos David, Marcos y Aar&oacute;n est&aacute;n decididos a no permitir que su familia y sus negocios sean arrasados por la compleja realidad que vive la regi&oacute;n.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Uno de los almacenes que conforman la empresa de los Eltalef sufre un atentado; Aar&oacute;n, cansado de la situaci&oacute;n que vive el pa&iacute;s, decide hacer algo.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Varios acontecimientos inusuales terminar&aacute;n por desnudar la verdad tras la mancuerna formada por el coronel Mendoza, una especie de cacique local, y Aar&oacute;n Eltalef, quienes pretenden formar una organizaci&oacute;n para desestabilizar Guatemala,<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;<em>Vivir en el maldito tr&oacute;pico</em>&rdquo; recrea el cruce cultural de la tradici&oacute;n jud&iacute;a y centroamericana, al tiempo que consigue atrapar entre sus p&aacute;ginas, gracias a la excelente traducci&oacute;n y narraci&oacute;n de Walter Krochmal, la naturalidad&nbsp; de la expresi&oacute;n del&nbsp; pueblo&nbsp; en Guatemala, un pa&iacute;s que obliga a sus personajes a debatirse ante un crudo presente y un futuro que se niega a cambiar.</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(196, 3, 'La fidelidad presunta de las partes', '', 0, 2, 8, 35.50, 1, '', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Se desatan la paranoia y el miedo, en un mundo en apariencia bien constituido, pero donde toda fidelidad &mdash;pol&iacute;tica, sexual, o simplemente humana&mdash; queda al borde del abismo.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El protagonista, Diego Lombardi, es un escritor chileno que enfrenta el desplome de su vida conyugal y no est&aacute; seguro de su papel en el mundo de la literatura, o de la pol&iacute;tica.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Igual que toda una generaci&oacute;n en Chile que en su juventud vivieron la ca&iacute;da de Allende y la dictadura de Pinochet, Lombardi encarna la ambivalencia pol&iacute;tica de los que hoy se encuentran entre las esferas de los "privilegiados" en la sociedad, pero sin tener una idea clara en el mundo actual d&oacute;nde radican sus afinidades y fidelidades pol&iacute;ticas.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En una comedia de malentendidos Lombardi termina sin mujer y sin amante, vanagloriado por un libro que no escribi&oacute; mientras sus propias obras se comentan, pero no se leen... y en forma dram&aacute;tica todo desencadena en una acci&oacute;n tr&aacute;gica a ra&iacute;z de la decisi&oacute;n que toma una mujer frustrada y amargada en una posici&oacute;n de poder.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estos acontecimientos aue engendran un torbellino de emociones en la vida del protagonista, con c&iacute;nica perspectiva todo desencadena en su profunda necesidad de evaluar sus propias afiliaciones y lealtades, que lo llevaron a obrar en su pasado y ahora podr&iacute;an llevarlo hacia un nuevo enfoque en su vida... una vez descubre cu&aacute;les son fidelidades meramente presuntas en la sociedad y cu&aacute;les son aut&eacute;nticas en la consciencia de un individuo. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Una novela escrita con brillantez y sentido de humor, que hurga en las profundidades psicol&oacute;gicas para descubrir el cariz tragic&oacute;mico de nuestra existencia.<br /><strong><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The New York Times Review: </strong>"El autor chileno James Collyer es psic&oacute;logo por capacitaci&oacute;n &hellip; pero un autor innato&hellip; El Sr. Collyer escribe historias que se centran en un incidente impactante, un inesperado desenlace de eventos o las peremnes peculiaridades de la naturaleza humana... Su inteligencia supremamente civilizada, con tendencia a instar a la imaginaci&oacute;n, queda en evidencia, pero ocasionalmente surge un aspecto m&aacute;s emotivo.&rdquo;</p>', '', '', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 1, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
INSERT INTO `audiobooks_authors` (`audiobook_id`, `author_id`, `main`, `bio`, `image`) VALUES
(6, 43, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Writer and journalist based in Brooklyn, New York. He is known for his explorations of the seamy side of urban life, both here and abroad, and for his offbeat and witty take on popular culture. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is a Contributing Editor at <em>New York Magazine</em> and<em> Rolling Stone</em>. <br />Also a frequent contributor to <em>The Village Voice, National Geographic, Natural History Magazine, Men&rsquo;s Journal, Esquire </em>and other publications. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jacobson&rsquo;s articles have been adapted into the classic TV series, &ldquo;Taxi&rdquo; and the feature film <em>American Ganster</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jacobson was awarded the 2001 <em>Humanitas Prize</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(7, 80, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Author or co-Author of 29 books, including the <em>New York Times #1 Bestseller, American Soldier</em>, with Gen. Tommy Franks. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; McConnell lives in Queenstown, MD.</p>', ''),
(9, 61, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Renowned for his<em> Callahan&rsquo;s Place</em> series of best-selling novels. With his wife, Jeanne, he has written the <em>Hugo</em> and <em>Nebula Award </em>winning &ldquo;Stardance&rdquo;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Winner of three  series. <em>Hugo Awards</em>, a <em>John W. Campbell Award </em>and a <em>Nebula Award</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He currently resides on an island near Vancouver, British Columbia, and writes a regular editorial column, &ldquo;<em>Future Tense</em>", for the <em>Globe and Mail.<br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is a favorite guest at sci-fi conventions across the United States and Canada.</p>', '.png'),
(10, 38, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He began working as a reporter in 1979 for the <em>Lima Times</em> in Peru.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During the 1980s he covered Central America first for the syndicated columnist <em>Jack Anderson</em> and later for<em> Time</em> magazine.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has also written for the<em> New York Times, Nation, Harper&rsquo;s, Life</em>, and <em>The Nation </em>and is the author of<em> Guerillas: Journeys in the Insurgent World</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(13, 8, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Author of several books, including the <em>New York Times </em>bestseller <em>Nickel and Dimed. <br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A frequent contributor to the <em>New York Times, Progressive</em>, and <em>Harpers</em>, and a contributing writer to <em>Time</em> magazine. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She lives in Florida.</p>', '.png'),
(14, 48, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An astrophysicist with the <em>American Museum of Natural History</em>, where he serves as Director of its world-famous <em>Hayden Planetarium</em> at the <em>American Museum of Natural History</em> in Manhattan. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is an award-winning author and a columnist for <em>Natural History</em>. A charismatic television personality, he has, since 2006, hosted <em>PBS</em>&rsquo;s educational television show<em> NOVA</em> and <em>NOVA scienceNOW</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has been a frequent guest on <em>The Daily Show, The Colbert Report</em>, and <em>Jeopardy</em>. Awarded the <em>NASA</em> <em>Distinguished Public Service Medal</em>, the highest civilian honor bestowed by <em>NASA</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(15, 49, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>New York Times </em>best-selling author of <em>Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several <em>Hugo<strong> </strong></em>and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(17, 57, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Called "<em>the dean of Canadian Science Fiction</em>" by the <em>Ottwa Citizen</em> and ""just about the best Science-Fiction writer out there"" by the <em>Denver Rocky Muntain News&nbsp;</em>-- is one of&nbsp;7 authors in history to win all three of the Science-Fiction field&rsquo;s highest honors for best novel of the year: the <em>Hugo Award </em>(which he won for <em>Hominids</em>), the <em>Nebula Award </em>(which he won for<em> The Terminal Experiment</em>); and the <em>John W. Campbell Memorial Award</em> (which he won for <em>Mindscan</em>). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has written 18 novels and his short fiction has been published in numerous magazines and anthologies. He has won 41 national and international awards. <br /><em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; Sawyer</em> is the President of the <em>Science Fiction Writers of America.</em></p>', '.png'),
(19, 36, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A newspaper reporter, magazine writer, and daily columnist for the <em>Los Angeles Times</em> (1916-1996). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For 37 years he chronicled or poked fun at Los Angeles, his family and himself in a witty style that became a defining voice for the booming city. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His columns were distributed to almost 600 newspapers worldwide by the <em>Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He published 10 books, many of them based on his columns, and won the Los Angeles chapter of the <em>Society of Professional Journalists&rsquo; Distinguished Journalist Award.</em></p>', '.png'),
(20, 63, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>Macavity Award</em>-winning author of <em>Stealing the Dragon</em>.<br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tim Maleeny</em> was born in New Jersey, and graduated from <em>Dartmouth College</em> with a Computer Science degree. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Afterwards attended <em>Columbia Business School</em> and spent several years pursuing a career in advertising. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His on-going series with detective <em>Cape Weathers</em> and his deadly Asian sidekick, Sally, are eagerly awaited by his growing audience worldwide. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After a lot of traveling around the world, he now lives in San Francisco.</p>', '.png'),
(21, 11, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An award-winning British writer and broadcaster. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Previously a writer and host for<em> BBC TV</em> and <em>BBC Radio</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is also a frequent contributor to <em>National Public Radio&rsquo;s </em>shows <em>Marketplace</em> and <em>The Savvy Traveler</em>, where his <em>Bad Taste Tours</em> have been heard regularly since 2000, as well as a regular panelist on the<em> KUOW</em> talk show Rewind.</p>', '.png'),
(22, 20, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An American novelist,short story writer and designer (1862-1937).<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 1921 she was awared the <em>Pulitzer Price for Literature</em> for her novel <em>The Age of Innocence</em>, making her the first woman ever to win the prestigious award. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She combined her insider&rsquo;s view of America&rsquo;s privileged classes with a brilliant, natural wit to write humorous and incisive novels and short stories.</p>', '.png'),
(23, 81, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A successful <em>Hollywood</em> screenwriter.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A native of Alabama, moved to North Carolina as a teen where he began to &ldquo;produce&rdquo;&nbsp; home movies.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Graduated from<em> Bringham Young University</em> in Utah and in 2003 moved to Los Angeles to work as as Producer/Writer Taleswapper Inc., a production company headed by Bestselling author <em>Orson Scott Card</em> and <em>Oscar-winner</em> film director <em>Peter Johnson</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He now lives with his wife and two sons in Greenville, South Carolina, working as a copywriter for an advertising agency.</p>', '.png'),
(24, 82, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A&nbsp;Director, Screenwriter and Producer (1893-1973). <br /><em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; Cooper</em> started his film career with documentaries for <em>Paramount PicturesRKO Radio Pictures</em> and afterwards led movie production for  before and after World War II. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The now classic 1933 <em>King Kong</em> film, which he co-wrote, co-directed, and appeared in, was a breakthrough in technical innovations. <br /><strong><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em></strong><em>Cooper</em> helped pave the way for such ground-breaking technologies as <em>Technicolor </em>and the widescreen process<em> Cinerama.</em></p>', '.png'),
(25, 30, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Norfolk, England (1856-1925). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After failing the Army entrance exam, he went to Natal in 1875, as secretary to Sir Henry Bulwer, and the next year went to the Transvaal. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He returned to England in 1881, married, and settled down to a literary life. His first novel,<em> King Solomon&rsquo;s Mines</em>, was published in 1885. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He published 34 adventure novels during his lifetime. He was knighted in 1912.</p>', '.png'),
(26, 41, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A born storyteller.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this engrossing memoir, he offers wonderful tales, favorite jokes, and hard-won insights.</p>', '.png'),
(27, 49, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>New York Times</em> best-selling author of <em>Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several <em>Hugo and Nebula Awards</em> and  for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina."</p>', '.png'),
(28, 34, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Author of three travel books about his experiences in the Pacific Islands in <em>The Sex Lives of Cannibals and Getting Stoned with Savages</em>, and a 3-month trip to China in <em>Lost on Planet China. <br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His travel essays have appeared in the Atlantic Monthly, Washington Post, and other publications.</p>', '.png'),
(35, 28, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; French novelist (1821-1880) and one of the masters of nineteenth-century fiction, was born in Rouen the second son of a noted physician. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beset by ill health and personal misfortune, he led a solitary life of rigid discipline, which was reflected in his writing by his obsession with finding <em>le mot juste</em> (exactly the right word). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His first published novel was <em>Madame Bovary</em> (1857). When certain passages in<em> Madame Bovary </em>were judged to be offensive to public morals, Flaubert, his publisher, and his printer were tried, but acquitted.</p>', '.png'),
(36, 49, 1, '<p><em>The New York Times</em> best-selling author of<em> Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several <em>Hugo </em>and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(38, 56, 0, '', ''),
(39, 49, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The New York Times</em> best-selling author of <em>Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several Hugo and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(40, 10, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An Amherst College graduate in 1960, moved to California to attend Stanford and obtain a teaching degree. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Taught American History in the Bay Area High Schools in the 60&rsquo;s and later returned to Stanford for a PhD in Education. Became principal of Los Altos High School in 1976 and later Assistant Superintendent for the District.&nbsp;He retired in the early 90&rsquo;s. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Author of two books about fly fishing: <em>Pursuing Wild Trout</em> and <em>A Guide to California&rsquo;s Freshwater Fishes</em>. Also a contributing Editor at <em>California Fly Fisher</em> magazine.</p>', '.png'),
(41, 65, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An American film scholar and writer who wrote several successful novels under the pen name <em>Trevanian</em> ( 1931-2005). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Whitaker also published works as <em>Nicholas Seare, Be&ntilde;at Le Cagot</em> and <em>Edoard Moran</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He published the non-fiction <em>The Language of Film</em> under his own name.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Whitaker wrote in a wide variety of genres, achieved best-seller status, and published under several names, but was best known as <em>Trevanian</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Between 1972 to 1983, five of his novels sold more than a million copies each. He was described as "<em>the only writer of airport paperbacks to be compared to Zola, Ian Fleming, Poe and Chaucer.</em>" <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He revealed his real name in an interview with the <em>New York Times</em> in 1979. His books have been translated into more than&nbsp;14 languages.</p>', ''),
(42, 49, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The New York Times </em>best-selling author of <em>Ender&rsquo;s Game,</em> has won several <em>HugoNebula</em> and  Awards for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(43, 22, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A&nbsp;British explorer born in Ireland (1874-1922). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He made his first expedition to Antarctica under Robert F. Scott. In 1907 he commanded a south polar expedition in which the south magnetic pole was located, with vast scientific results. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The journey of the <em>Endurance</em> was his final expedition.</p>', '.png'),
(45, 3, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Time</em> magazine&rsquo;s military and intelligence affairs correspondent in the Jerusalem Bureau. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He received the <em>2002 Henry Luce Award</em> and has been a consultant for <em>CNN</em>. Klein was the military-security correspondent and analyst for Hadashot and Al-Hamishmar, two of Israel&rsquo;s leading national newspapers. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He teaches at Hebrew University and is a Captain in the <em>Israeli Defense Forces&rsquo; Intelligence.</em></p>', ''),
(46, 44, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mark Twain was a pseudonym of Samuel L. Clemens (1835-1910), born in Florida, Missouri. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A printer and later a Mississippi riverboat pilot, he adopted his pen name from riverboat lingo meaning water two fathoms deep. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His masterpieces, <em>The Adventures of Tom Sawyer</em> (1876) and <em>The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn</em> (1884), are not only classics of humorous writing but also a graphic picture of nineteenth-century America.</p>', '.png'),
(50, 19, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in 1959, Greenwood is a Canadian writer and editor who created the Forgotten Realms Dungeons &amp; Dragons campaign setting. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He retains certain rights of his setting, but is essentially a freelance author. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives in Colborne, Ontario, and works full-time as a librarian. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is an active freelance game designer and has written several best-selling novels in the Forgotten Realms fantasy setting he created.</p>', '.png'),
(51, 32, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A retired <em>United States Foreign Service</em> officer and a professional historian. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is the author of <em>The Vision of Anglo-America </em>(1987) as well as numerous articles and studies concerning diplomatic history and government affairs.</p>', '.png'),
(55, 25, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; French novelist (1868-1927), was born in Paris. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He earned a Law degree in 1889 but turned to journalism in his mid twenties and later sailed the world as a Correspondent, reporting on the Russian Revolution of 1905. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the early 1900s, he began writing novels and became best known for <em>The Phantom of the Opera </em>(1910). His novel <em>The Mystery in the Yellow Room</em> sparked the development of detective fiction as a genre.</p>', '.png'),
(56, 50, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Dublin in 1854, he won scholarships to both <em>Trinity College</em> (Dublin) and <em>Magdalen College</em> (Oxford), where he was heavily influenced by the radical aesthetics of Walter Pater. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Flamboyant wit and man-about-town, Wilde had a reputation that preceded him, especially in his early career. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After publishing two volumes of short stories between 1887 and 1891, his social-comedy plays such as <em>Lady Windermere&rsquo;s Fan </em>and<em> The Importance of Being Earnest </em>established his critical and commercial success.</p>', '.png'),
(61, 45, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Received an <em>M.F.A</em>. from <em>Vermont College</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His writing has appeared in the <em>Harvard Review, Georgia Review, New England Review, American Scholar,</em> and <em>Utne Reader. <br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A former fellow at the MacDowall and Yaddo colonies, he lives in New York City with his wife and children.</p>', ''),
(63, 62, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Received his Ph.D in English literature from the University of Iowa and has taught creative writing at the University of Southern California since 1977.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His novels include <em>World&rsquo;s End</em> -- winner of the <em>PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction</em>, and <em>Water Music</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His short fiction regularly appears in such major magazines as<em> Harper&rsquo;s </em>and the <em>New Yorker</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Much of the appeal of Boyle&rsquo;s novels and stories is his creation of outrageous characters, bizarre situations and deliberately inflated comparisons.</p>', '.png'),
(64, 19, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in 1959, Greenwood is a Canadian Writer and Editor who created the <em>Forgotten Realms Dungeons &amp; Dragons</em> campaign setting.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He retains certain rights of his setting, but is essentially a Freelance Author.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives in Colborne, Ontario, and works full-time as a librarian.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is an active freelance game designer and has written several best-selling novels in the <em>Forgotten Realms</em> fantasy setting he created.</p>', '.png'),
(67, 49, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The New York Times</em> best-selling author of<em> Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several<em> Hugo</em> and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(65, 62, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Received his Ph.D in English Literature from the University of Iowa and has taught creative writing at the University of Southern California since 1977. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His novels include <em>World&rsquo;s End</em> -- winner of the <em>PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction,</em> and <em>Water Music</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His short fiction regularly appears in such major magazines as <em>Harper&rsquo;s</em> and <em>The New Yorker</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Much of the appeal of Boyle&rsquo;s novels and stories is his creation of outrageous characters, bizarre situations and deliberately inflated comparisons.</p>', '.png'),
(66, 6, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in England and educated at Oxford (1886-1959). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At 24 he was one of the youngest members of <em>Scott&rsquo;s British Antarctic Expedition. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He served in the </em><em>First World War until being invalided out of the Navy in 1915 and during his convalescence started to write The Worst Journey in the World.</em></p>', '.png'),
(68, 16, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born 1859, in Mobile, Alabama. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A member of the wealthy Gracie family of New York state, one of Gracie&rsquo;s ancestors had built<em> Gracie Mansion</em> which became the official residence of the mayor of New York City in 1942. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gracie was a graduate of St. Paul&rsquo;s Academy in Concord, New Hampshire and of West Point Military Academy. Later becoming a Colonel in the Seventh Regiment, United States Army. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Colonel Gracie wrote an account of the tragedy that was published as "<em>The Truth About The Titanic</em>" in 1913.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He never finished proofing the manuscript as he died on&nbsp;December 4,&nbsp;1912 at his ancestral home in New York, N.Y., having never fully recovered from the trauma of that night.</p>', '.png'),
(69, 39, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (1828-1905) -- Considered by many the<em> Father of Science Fiction</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Nantes, France, he studied Law but turned to writing opera libretti until the 1863 publication of his first Voyages extraordinaires&mdash;<em>Cinq Semaines en ballon (Five Weeks in a Balloon).</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Its success encouraged him to produce a number of classic and prophetic science-fiction novels, including <em>A Journey to the Center of the Earth </em>and <em>Twenty Thousand Leagues under the Sea</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Verne&rsquo;s stories foresaw many scientific and technological developments, including the submarine, television, and space travel.</p>', '.png'),
(70, 4, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; French novelist and playwright (1802-1870), was born in France, the son of an innkeeper&rsquo;s daughter and one of Napoleon&rsquo;s generals.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He moved to Paris in 1823 to make his fortune in the theater, and at twenty-eight he was one of the leading literary figures of his day. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His complete works were eventually to fill <em>over 300 volumes,</em> and his stories made him the best-known Frenchman of his age.</p>', '.png'),
(71, 9, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A six-time Winner of <em>Science Fiction&rsquo;s Hugo Award</em>, is the author of over <em>100 works</em> of science fact and fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A former Editor of <em>Analog</em> and former Fiction Editor of <em>Omn</em>i, he is also a past <em>President of the National Space Society</em> and the <em>Science-Fiction Writers of America. <br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives in Naples, Florida.</p>', '.png'),
(72, 9, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A six-time Winner of <em>Science Fiction&rsquo;s Hugo Award</em>, is the author of over <em>100 </em>works of science fact and fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A former Editor of<em> Analog</em> and former Fiction Editor of <em>Omni</em>, he is also a past President of the National Space Society and the<em> Science-Fiction Writers of America. </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives in Naples, Florida.</p>', '.png'),
(73, 9, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A six-time Winner of <em>Science Fiction&rsquo;s Hugo Award</em>, is the author of over <em>100 </em>works of science fact and fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A former Editor of <em>Analog</em> and former Fiction Editor of <em>Omni,</em> he is also a past <em>President of the National Space Society</em> and the <em>Science-Fiction Writers of America. </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives in Naples, Florida.</p>', '.png'),
(74, 55, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The New York Times</em> best-selling author of such novels as <em>I Am Legend, Hell House, Somewhere in Time, The Incredible Shrinking Man</em>, and <em>A Stir of Echoes. </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Named a <em>Grand Master of Horror</em> and winner of the<em> Bram Stoker Award for Lifetime Achievement</em>, he has also won the<em> Edgar,</em> the <em>Hugo</em>, the <em>Spur</em>, and the <em>Writer&rsquo;s Guild</em> awards.</p>', '.png'),
(78, 72, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born Samuel L. Clemens (1835-1910) in the town of Florida, Missouri. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One of the most popular and influential authors our nation has ever produced, his keen wit and incisive satire earned him praise from both critics and peers. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has been called not only the<em> Greatest Humorist of his Age</em> but the <em>Father of American Literature</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(75, 2, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The son of a Scottish schoolmaster(1882-1956), Milne won a scholarship to Westminster School and later read Mathematics at <em>Cambridge</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His real interest was in light-hearted writing; he edited the undergraduate magazine <em>Granta</em> and at 24 he became Assistant Editor of <em>Punch</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After serving as a signals officer in World War I he won additional acclaim as a playwright. His great success, however, came as a writer of children&rsquo;s literature after publishing a series of verses about his young son Christopher Robin (<em>When We Were Very Young</em> and<em> Now We Are Six</em>). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Following the acclaim received for the <em>Winnie-the-Pooh </em>books, Milne published several novels as well as an autobiography, <em>It&rsquo;s Too Late Now </em>(1939). His last triumph was a stage adaptation of&nbsp;<em> </em>Kenneth Grahame&rsquo;s <em>The Wind in the Willows </em>called <em>Toad of Toad Hall</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(76, 49, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The New York Times</em> best-selling author of<em> Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several <em>Hugo</em> and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(77, 62, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El autor ive con su familia cerca de Santa Barbara, California. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recibi&oacute; su doctorado en literatura inglesa de la University of Iowa y ha ense&ntilde;ado escritura creativa en la University of Southern California desde 1977. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus obras se distinguen por su humor c&iacute;nico y negro, personajes inolvidables y profunda cr&iacute;tica social.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus exitosas novelas incluyen <em>World&rsquo;s End</em> (ganador del premio <em>PEN/Faulkner</em>&nbsp;de ficci&oacute;n) y <em>Water Music.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus novelas cortas aparecen regularmente en revistas de prestigio como <em>Harper&rsquo;s,</em> <em>The New Yorker </em>y desde 1978 ense&ntilde;a en la Universidad de Southern California.</p>', '.png'),
(79, 40, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A Cum-Laude graduate of Yale University and Rhodes Scholar at Oxford University, was a Marine in Vietnam, where he was awarded the Navy Cross, the Bronze Star, two Navy Commendation Medals for valor, two Purple Hearts, and ten air medals.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; He has lived and traveled all over the world and now writes full time.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He and his wife, Anne, have five children and live on a small lake in Washington state.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Author&rsquo;s Comments About the Book:</strong> <em>"It&rsquo;s a story about growing up and learning compassion in a very difficult situation. I tried to be as true to the experience of what it&rsquo;s like to be 19 or 20 years old in combat.</em><em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "The generation that did live through the Vietnam era&mdash;the Baby Boomers&mdash;is now at an age when they&rsquo;re trying to reflect on things. It was an enormously divisive time in America, the place looked like it was going up in smoke. Now we&rsquo;re reflecting on that."<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em><strong>Author&rsquo;s Comments About the Audiobook</strong><em>: "The recent releaseof the audiobook, narrated by actor Bronson Pinchot (Perfect Strangers), only adds to the urgency and intricacies of the story. He did an incredible job.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "He&rsquo;s really good at bringing characters. Some speak in ways that I didn&rsquo;t imagine, often making me think,: Oh, that&rsquo;s interesting!&rsquo;"</em></p>', '.png'),
(80, 42, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One of the most honored writers in the fields of <em>Science Fiction</em> and <em>Fantasy</em>, having won five <em>Hugo </em>Awards and three <em>Nebula</em> Awards.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her second novel, The Warrior&rsquo;s Apprentice, introduced young Miles Vorkosigan, one of the most popular characters in<em> Science Fiction</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The mother of two, she lives in Minneapolis.</p>', '.png'),
(81, 64, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His diverse background experience includes acting, holding a world record in tango, and being a national Chinese kickboxing champion. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has written for Maxim and the <em>Philadelphia Inquirer</em> and has appeared on <em>MTV</em> and<em> CBS</em> radio.</p>', '.png'),
(82, 7, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Was born in Russia (1905-1982), graduated from the University of Leningrad, and in 1926 came to the United States where she was naturalized. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her first novel, We the Living, was published in 1936. With the publication of <em>The Fountainhead</em> in 1943, she achieved a spectacular and enduring success and her unique philosophy, objectivism, gained a worldwide following.</p>', '.png'),
(83, 37, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lives with her husband and their very spoiled dog in Florida. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Although not a vampire herself, she confesses to having pale skin, wearing a lot of black, and sleeping in late whenever possible. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; And while she can&rsquo;t see ghosts, she loves to walk through old cemeteries. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She also loves poetry and animals, but fears children and hates to cook.</p>', '.png'),
(84, 60, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lived in England for many years after the war. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He married an Englishwoman and lived in the countryside until his death in 2004.</p>', '.png'),
(85, 35, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An American writer and adventurer (1876-1916), was born into poverty and largely self-educated but led an extraordinarily eventful life.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He traveled extensively and was at various times a war correspondent, oyster pirate, seaman, horticulturalist, sealer, hobo, and politician.</p>', '.png'),
(86, 54, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grew up in Berkshire, England, the son of a country doctor. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After an education at Oxford, he spent six years in the Army and then went into the Civil Service. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has written many novels and short stories, including <em>Shardik</em> and <em>The Plague Dog</em>s.</p>', '.png'),
(87, 67, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has had a distinguished career as <em>Foreign Correspondent, News Commentator</em>, and <em>Historian</em> of the contemporary world. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He was a War Correspondent reporting from Berlin on the rise of the Nazis for the<em> Universal News Service</em> and for <em>CBS</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Out of these reports grew his best-sellers, <em>Berlin Diary</em> and <em>The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich</em>, which has sold more copies for the Book-of-the-Month Club than any other book in the club&rsquo;s history.</p>', '.png'),
(92, 74, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Was a New York City cop for twenty years. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He worked and supervised in the DEA, Secret Service Task Force, Special Frauds Squad, Missing Persons Squad, Operation 8, and several other outstanding and prestigious units throughout the city. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He retired from the NYPD in 2003 as a Detective Sergeant. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He now divides his time between television and film work, being a professional fight trainer, and running his Renzo Gracie Brazilian Jiu Jitsu academy with his family.</p>', '.png'),
(93, 49, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A <em>New York Times</em> bestselling author, has won several <em>Hugo</em> and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(88, 1, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The New York Times</em> best-selling author of four international thrillers, including <em>Masquerade</em> and <em>The Coil</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She also co-authored three bestselling novels in the<em> Covert-One Series </em>with Robert Ludlum, including <em>The Hades Factor,</em> which was a <em>CBS</em> miniseries in 2006. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She has been a Newspaper Reporter, a magazine Editor, and a Think-Tank Editor with Top-Secret clearance before turning to writing fiction.<br /><br />She lives in Santa Barbara with her husband, writer Dennis Lynds.</p>', '.png'),
(89, 27, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The author or co-author of seven previous books, including <em>Colored Lights, Dance with Demons, Time Steps, The Shape of Love, The Little Ballerina and Her Dancing Horse,</em> and the <em>New York Times</em> Bestseller <em>Dancing on My Grave</em>&mdash;the last three edited by Jackie Onassis.<em><br /></em></p>', '.png'),
(90, 12, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Worked as a Designer and Editor in publishing before becoming a Director of the literary agency Curtis Brown. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Since 1991 he has worked in television and has been Executive Producer in Drama at ITV since 2000. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Among his productions are<em> The Railway Children</em>, the Oscar-nominated short <em>Syrup</em>, Andrew Davies&rsquo; adaptation of <em>Northanger Abbey</em>, and the recent series <strong>Time of Your Life</strong>.</p>', '.png'),
(91, 5, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grew up in New York. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He currently lives in Vermont and teaches at Bennington College. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a composer, he has produced a large catalog of orchestral, chamber, and piano works, as well as scores for ballet, theater, and film. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He performs frequently as a pianist, and he has written for the <em>Atlantic Monthly</em>, the <em>Times Literary Supplement, The New York Times </em>Magazine, and other publications.</p>', ''),
(92, 83, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A writer whose work has appeared in the <em>Wall Street Journal </em>and the erstwhile <em>New York Sun</em>, among other publications; a guitar player who has performed and recorded with the <em>A-Bones, Hasil Adkins, Action Swingers, Yo La Tengo, </em>and <em>Andre Williams</em>, to name a few; and the writer and director of two award-winning short films, both aired on the <em>Independent Film Channel. <br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A Manhattan native and resident of the Lower East Side for twenty years&mdash;including the period covered in <em>Alphaville</em>&mdash;he now lives and works in Brooklyn.</p>', ''),
(94, 14, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She writes essays and reviews for the <em>New York Times, Vogue, The Nation,</em> and other major publications. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She lives on an island near Seattle.</p>', '.png'),
(95, 31, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A Professor of English at Hope College in Michigan, where she teaches fiction, poetry, and creative nonfiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A recipient of a <em>National Endowment for the Arts Fellowship for Fiction </em>and a<em> Barnes &amp; Noble New Discovery Writers Award. <br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She has published widely in a variety of genres and her books include <em>Georgia Under Water</em>, a collection of linked stories; <em>Drinking Girls and Their Dresses</em>: Poems; <em>Page After Page</em>, a memoir of the writing life; and <em>Spike and Cubby&rsquo;s Ice Cream Island Adventure</em>, a children&rsquo;s book.</p>', '.png'),
(96, 75, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The author has a B.A. in English from the University of Colorado and a Master&rsquo;s degree in Social Work from Adelphi University.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She lives in Olivebridge, New York, and teaches writing at SUNY Ulster and Marist College.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She is also the author of "Saddled" and "Chosen Forever".<br /><br />&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Author&rsquo;s Comments:</strong> "Horses have enriched my life immeasurably, not the least of which was to show me how better to love people."</p>', '.png'),
(97, 76, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For 18 years was the first and only Latino writer ever to win a <em>Pulitzer Prize for Literature.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hijuelos was born in New York City, in Morningside Heights, Manhattan, to Cuban immigrant parents. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His first novel, "<em>Our House in the Last World</em>", was published in 1983 and received the 1985 Rome Prize, awarded by the American Academy in Rome. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His second novel, "<em>The Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love</em>", received the 1990 Pulitzer Prize for Fiction. It was adapted for the film "<em>The Mambo Kings</em>" in 1992 and as a Broadway musical in 2005. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His five previous novels have been translated into twenty-five languages. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hijuelos has taught at Hofstra University and is currently affiliated with Duke University, where he is a member of the faculty of the Department of English.</p>', '.png'),
(99, 78, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born at Dulwich, England (1865-1948). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A graduate of Oxford, he was first a professional actor before becoming a playwright. When he turned to writing fiction, he proved to be a versatile and prolific author, excelling at historical fiction, adventure fiction, social melodrama, and crime fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is perhaps best remembered today for his tales of adventure and detection, often set in exotic locales.</p>', '.png'),
(98, 77, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Widely acknowledged as one of the world&rsquo;s most skilled practitioners of jazz piano. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She has hosted <em>Marian McPartland&rsquo;s Piano Jazz </em>on <em>National Public Radio </em>since 1979 and has many recordings to her credit and continues to perform in the United States.</p>', '.png'),
(100, 19, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in 1959, Greenwood is a Canadian writer and editor who created the <em>Forgotten Realms Dungeons &amp; Dragons</em> campaign setting. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He retains certain rights of his setting, but is essentially a Freelance Author. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives in Colborne, Ontario, and works full-time as a librarian. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is an active Freelance game designer and has written several best-selling novels in the Forgotten Realms fantasy setting he created.</p>', '.png'),
(108, 84, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Doctor en literatura comparada, titulado de la Universidad de Nueva York.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de <em>"El coraz&oacute;n de Voltaire",</em> novela aclamada por la cr&iacute;tica literaria internacional como una de las m&aacute;s originales del siglo XXI, y de Seva, uno de los mayores &eacute;xitos de la literatura caribe&ntilde;a.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; L&oacute;pez Nieves ha ganado el <em>Premio Nacional de Literatura de Puerto Rico </em>en dos ocasiones. Fund&oacute; el primer programa de Maestr&iacute;a en Creaci&oacute;n Literaria de Am&eacute;rica Latina en la Universidad del Sagrado Coraz&oacute;n en Puerto Rico, del cual es actualmente su regente y Escritor Residente. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n es el creador y director de la <em>Biblioteca Digital Ciudad Seva</em> (CiudadSeva.com), uno de los portales ciberliterarios m&aacute;s visitados del mundo. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus obras han sido traducidas al alem&aacute;n, ingl&eacute;s, island&eacute;s, neerland&eacute;s, polaco e italiano.</p>', '.png'),
(3, 17, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in New York and raised in Big Sur, California.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her childhood mentors included Sufis, surfers, single moms, Black Panthers, Ansel Adams, draft dodgers, and striking farm workers.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Today she lives in Berkeley, California, with her husband and two daughters.</p>', '.png'),
(4, 79, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Founder of <em>Story Books</em>, a business committed to helping others preserve their life stories.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She has composed more than seventy-five personal histories in the past twenty years. She lives with her family in Naples, Florida</p>', ''),
(4, 68, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Started his crime career as a bagman for the<strong> </strong>Mafia and graduated to&nbsp; "Master Jewel Thief".<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is now reformed and has written this book about his father as an act of redemption.</p>', '.png'),
(5, 30, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Norfolk, England (1856-1925)&nbsp;. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After failing the Army entrance exam, he went to Natal in 1875, as secretary to Sir Henry Bulwer, and the next year went to the Transvaal. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He returned to England in 1881, married, and settled down to a literary life. His first novel, <em>King Solomon&rsquo;s Mines</em>, was published in 1885. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He published 34 adventure novels during his lifetime. He was knighted in 1912.</p>', '.png'),
(23, 49, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>New York Times</em> best-selling author of<em> Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several <em>Hugo</em> and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(109, 85, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Se gradu&oacute; de la Facultad de Derecho de Boston College y practicaba en una de las principales firmas de Wall Street.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dej&oacute; su vida como abogado en la ciudad de Nueva York para escribir <em>libros de intriga y misterio</em> en su querida isla paradis&iacute;aca griega de<strong> </strong>Mykonos, como s&oacute;lo alguien local pod&iacute;a hacerlo.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su obra es ahora todo un <em>fen&oacute;meno en ventas</em> en Grecia, tanto entre los turistas como la poblaci&oacute;n nativa.</p>', '.png'),
(174, 58, 1, '<p>&nbsp; Born in Santiago, Chile, in 1953. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He grew up in Chile and  Mexico City, where he was a founder of the Infrarealism poetry movement.  <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His first full-length novel, <em>The Savage Detectives</em>,  received the <em>Herralde Prize</em> and the <em>R&oacute;mulo Gallegos Prize</em> when it appeared in 1998. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Roberto Bola&ntilde;o died in Blanes, Spain,  at the age of fifty.</p>', '.png'),
(115, 91, 1, '', '.png'),
(7, 69, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Silverwoods live in California with their four children.</p>', '.png'),
(8, 26, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An award-winning freelance journalist and editor of the<em> Fort Collins Weekly</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His work has appeared in the <em>Christian Science Monitor, San Francisco Chronicle</em>, and the fifth edition of <em>Lonely Planet&rsquo;s West Africa</em> guidebook. Received the <em>American Library Association&rsquo;s Notable Book of the Year</em> award. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He was consultant to the film, <em>Blood Diamonds</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(11, 30, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Norfolk, England (1856-1925). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After failing the Army entrance exam, he went to Natal in 1875, as secretary to Sir Henry Bulwer, and the next year went to the Transvaal. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He returned to England in 1881, married, and settled down to a literary life. His first novel, King Solomon&rsquo;s Mines, was published in 1885. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He published&nbsp;34 adventure novels during his lifetime. He was knighted in 1912.</p>', '.png'),
(111, 87, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pablo De Santis es licenciado en Letras, escritor, periodista y guionista de c&oacute;mics. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su obra ha sido muy bien recibida por el p&uacute;blico lector as&iacute; como por la cr&iacute;tica literaria argentina y la de pa&iacute;ses como Espa&ntilde;a y Francia. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de cinco novelas internacionalmente aclamadas, recibi&oacute; el premio Planeta / Casa de Am&eacute;rica por su obra<em> &ldquo;El enigma de Par&iacute;s&rdquo;.<br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Vive en Buenos Aires.</p>', '.png'),
(196, 88, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chileno</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sic&oacute;logo de formaci&oacute;n, ha trabajado como editor, acad&eacute;mico, traductor y columnista de prensa en Chile y Espa&ntilde;a.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jaime Collyer fue uno de los protagonistas del boom editorial de los a&ntilde;os noventa conocido como la "<em>Nueva narrativa chilena</em>".&nbsp; Collyer se destaca y reconoce en su narrativa por el erotismo, la especulaci&oacute;n bibli&oacute;fila, el escepticismo y la insurrecci&oacute;n.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Desde entonces ha seguido publicando novelas y libros de cuentos con muy buena recepci&oacute;n cr&iacute;tica y resonancia internacional.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entre 1981 y 1990 residi&oacute; en Espa&ntilde;a, donde obtuvo el Premio Jauja de Cuentos y una distinci&oacute;n de la revista Playboy en su concurso de narraciones er&oacute;ticas.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El infiltrado, de 1989, fue galardonada como la mejor novela Latinoamericana traducida al franc&eacute;s y le signific&oacute; un s&oacute;lido comienzo en su trayectoria literaria.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 1993, <em>Gente al acecho</em> (<em>Premio Municipal de Literatura y Premio del Consejo Nacional del Libro y la Lectura</em>; a&ntilde;os m&atilde;s tarde el volumen fue publicado en Estados Unidos como <em>People on the Prowl</em>, con muy buena cr&iacute;tica) fue celebrado un&atilde;nimemente como uno de los vol&uacute;menes de cuentos mejor logrados en muchos a&ntilde;os.</p>', '.png'),
(113, 89, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Escritor chileno.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 1981, tras cursar dos a&ntilde;os de Periodismo y Literatura en la  Universidad de Chile, se traslad&oacute; a Barcelona, donde se  licenci&oacute; en Filolog&iacute;a Hisp&aacute;nica de Universidad Central.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Considerado una de las voces narrativas m&aacute;s personales de la nuevas  generaciones de escritores latinoamericanos. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 1995 apareci&oacute; su primera novela,<em> El Para&iacute;so tres veces al d&iacute;a</em>,  ganadora del<em> Premio del Consejo Nacional del Libro</em> <em>y la Lectura y  del Premio Municipal de Literatura</em> que concede la ciudad de  Santiago.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El volumen de relatos "<em>Nunca fui a Tijuana y otros cuentos</em>",  publicado en Santiago en 1999, obtuvo los mismos reconocimientos en la  categor&iacute;a de cuento. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su segunda novela, "<em>La burla del tiempo",</em> gan&oacute; en Espa&ntilde;a el prestigioso <em>Premio Biblioteca Breve</em> en 2004 y el <em>Premio  del Consejo Nacional del Libro y la Lectura</em> a la mejor novela  chilena publicada en 2004.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su tercera novela "<em>Las islas que van quedando"</em> (Alfaguara,  2009), le vali&oacute; otra vez el <em>Premio del Consejo Nacional del Libro y  la Lectura</em> a la mejor novela chilena in&eacute;dita de 2008. Sus tres  primeras novelas han sido traducidas al franc&eacute;s.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Desde 1987 hasta 2005 residi&oacute; en Par&iacute;s; actualmente vive en Santiago de  Chile donde es profesor de literatura en la Universidad Diego  Portales y columista de la Revista de Libros de El Mercurio.</p>', '.png'),
(116, 92, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el 2000 Lisette comenz&oacute; a trabajar como la asistente personal de Neale Donald Walsch, autor de la exitosa serie de libros de <em>&ldquo;Conversaciones con Dios&rdquo;</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Con su apoyo y &aacute;nimo Lisette accedi&oacute; a comenzar a revelar sus comunicaciones personales con seres cuyo prop&oacute;sito es ayudar a la evoluci&oacute;n del planeta y continuar ampliando el contacto con la poblaci&oacute;n terrestre.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En sus libros sobre este tema: &ldquo;<em>Talking to Extraterrestrials&rdquo;</em> y&nbsp;<em> &ldquo;Calling on Extraterrestrials" </em>en que explica c&oacute;mo estos contactos son parte de la expansi&oacute;n espiritual de humanos que comienzan a aprender a caminar entre mundos y percibir otras dimensiones que nos rodean.</p>', '.png');
INSERT INTO `audiobooks_authors` (`audiobook_id`, `author_id`, `main`, `bio`, `image`) VALUES
(12, 24, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Moscow (1821-1881), the son of a surgeon. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Leaving the study of engineering for literature, he published <em><strong>Poor Folk</strong></em> in 1846. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a member of revolutionary circles in St. Petersburg, he was condemned to death in 1849. A last-minute reprieve sent him to Siberia for hard labor. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Returning to St. Petersburg in 1859, he worked as a journalist and completed his masterpiece, <em>Crime and Punishment</em>, as well as other works, including <em>The Idiot</em> and <em>The Brothers Karamazov</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(117, 93, 1, '', ''),
(118, 94, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor mexicano contempor&aacute;neo, ejerce actualmente como Profesor de la Universidad Iberoamericana y est&aacute; considerado como uno de los m&aacute;ximos exponentes de la llamada <em>Generaci&oacute;n del Crack</em> y en 1996 fue uno de los impulsores de su Manifiesto. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha sido galardonado con media docena de permios nacionales, como el <em>Premio Alfonso Reyes, Premio Juan de la Cabada y Premio Primavera de Novela.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganador del <em>Premio Iberoamericano de Ensayo y Debate</em>- Casa de Am&eacute;rica en el 2010 con su obra <em>"La isla de las tribus perdidas"</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(119, 95, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en Bogot&aacute; (Colombia) en 1950. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Abogado con un posgrado en Econom&iacute;a y Ciencias Pol&iacute;ticas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Se dedica a la literatura desde 1979, a&ntilde;o en que obtuvo el Premio<br />Nacional de Novela Infantil con su obra "<em>Catalino Bocachica</em>". <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su quehacer como escritor est&aacute; ligado a una constante preocupaci&oacute;n<br />por incentivar y promover la lectura en ni&ntilde;os y j&oacute;venes. En este<br />campo ha colaborado como consultor con organismos de fomento<br />a la lectura y con diversos peri&oacute;dicos y revistas de Am&eacute;rica Latina y<br />Espa&ntilde;a.</p>', '.png'),
(121, 96, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Novelista y bi&oacute;grafo estadounidense.&nbsp; Ha escrito m&aacute;s de 150 libros,  pero es m&aacute;s conocido por su co-autor&iacute;am con Tim LaHaye, en la serie  Dejados atr&aacute;s.&nbsp; Debido a esta serie en el 2005, ambos autores se  ubicaron en la&nbsp; novena posici&oacute;n de los 10 autores con&nbsp; mayor n&uacute;mero de  libros vendidos en Amazon desde 1995. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 16 de sus obras se han  ubicado entre los Bestsellers del New York Times (7 en la posici&oacute;n #1).&nbsp;  Tambi&eacute;n han registrado las m&aacute;s altas ventas en las listas de USA Today,  Wall Street Journal y Publisher&rsquo;s Weekly.</p>', '.png'),
(121, 97, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de reconocimiento internacional, se ha destacado en su  carrera literaria como una autoridad en las escrituras y fue quien  desglos&oacute; las profec&iacute;as b&iacute;blicas en las cuales est&aacute; basada toda la trama  de la serie Dejados atr&aacute;s.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n el autor de numerosos  Bestsellers cuyas ventas se acercan a los 10 millones de ejemplares.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Vive en Washington DC.</p>', '.png'),
(122, 98, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nacido en Islandia (1962) estudi&oacute; F&iacute;sica en la Universidad de Brandeis. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue uno de los </em><em>fundadores y Presidente de Sony Interactive Entertainment, donde supervis&oacute; el lanzamiento de la conocida consola de juegos Playstation. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Desde 1999 es</em> <em>Vicepresidente de Time Warner Digital Media en Nueva York, ciudad donde reside habitualmente.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es autor de varias novelas, entre ellas </em><em>Absolution publicada en 1994.</em></p>', '.png'),
(166, 26, 1, '<p>An award-winning freelance journalist and editor of the<em> Fort Collins  Weekly</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His work has appeared in the <em>Christian Science  Monitor, San Francisco Chronicle</em>, and the fifth edition of <em>Lonely  Planet&rsquo;s West Africa</em> guidebook. Received the <em>American Library  Association&rsquo;s Notable Book of the Year</em> award. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He was  consultant to the film, <em>Blood Diamonds</em></p>\r\n<p>.</p>', '.png'),
(167, 38, 1, '<p>He began working as a reporter in 1979 for the <em>Lima Times</em> in  Peru.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During the 1980s he covered Central America first for the  syndicated columnist <em>Jack Anderson</em> and later for<em> Time</em> magazine.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has also written for the<em> New York Times, Nation,  Harper&rsquo;s, Life</em>, and <em>The Nation </em>and is the author of<em> Guerillas: Journeys in the Insurgent World</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(123, 99, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en La Havana en 1960 y se considera como una de las tres autoras de habla hispana de fantas&iacute;a y ciencia ficci&oacute;n m&aacute;s importantes&mdash;la argentina Ang&eacute;lica Gorodischer y la espa&ntilde;oal Elia Barcel&oacute; completan esa trinidad femenina.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 1991 abandona Cuba y se establece en los Estados Unidos.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 1998 logra reconocimiento internacional con el Premio Azor&iacute;n en Espa&ntilde;a por la mejor novela&nbsp; con su obra &ldquo;<em>El hombre, la hembra y el hambre</em>&rdquo;. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el 2004 fue la invitada de honor en la Vigesimoquinta Conferencia Internacional de lo Fant&aacute;stico en las Artes, en EE. UU.&nbsp; Esta fue la primera vez que se le confiere ese honor a un autor de habla hispana.</p>', '.png'),
(16, 33, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He was a noted feature writer for the<em> San Francisco Chronicle,</em> a lecturer, and a regular contributor to national magazines -- 1906-1996.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to <em>Escape from Alcatraz </em>(1963), he also authored <em>The Golden Door: The Irony of Our Immigration Policy </em>(1954).</p>', '.png'),
(124, 100, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nacido en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico el a&ntilde;o de 1952, David Mart&iacute;n del Campo se forj&oacute; inicialmente en el periodismo, carrera que estudi&oacute; en la UNAM; de hecho, fue corresponsal en Madrid y ha incursionado en todos los g&eacute;neros asociados a la labor informativa: art&iacute;culos, ensayos, cr&oacute;nicas y entrevistas publicados en medios de circulaci&oacute;n nacional como La Jornada, Uno m&aacute;s y UnoReforma.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 1973 publica su primera novela, &ldquo;<em>Las rojas son las carretas</em>&rdquo;, y a la fecha cuenta con m&aacute;s de una veintena de t&iacute;tulos de elegancia estil&iacute;stica con historias ins&oacute;litas y cuativantes.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entre sus obras est&aacute;n las cr&oacute;nicas de <em>Los mares de M&eacute;xico</em>, <em>Isla de lobos</em>, (Premio nacional de Novela Jos&eacute; Rub&eacute;n Romero 1987), <em>Dama de noche,</em> <em>Alas de &aacute;ngel </em>(Premio Internacional de Novela Diana-Novedades 1990),el <em>A&ntilde;o del fuego</em>,&nbsp; <em>Las viudas de blanco, Cielito lindo</em> y los cuentos infantiles de<em> El tlacuache lun&aacute;tico.&nbsp;</em></p>', '.png'),
(18, 23, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Was a key figure in international counterterrorism and domestic spycraft.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a member of the <em>State Department&rsquo;s Diplomatic Security Service</em> in the mid 1980s, he was on the front lines of America&rsquo;s first campaign against terror.</p>', '.png'),
(125, 101, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Espa&ntilde;ola {1954-2003 }, escritora galardonada con el </em>Permio de Poes&iacute;a Ciudad de Ir&uacute;n<em> </em>1995 y del Premio Azor&iacute;n<em> 2000 con su obra &ldquo;Cielos de barro</em><em>&rdquo;.&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em>Muri&oacute; de c&aacute;ncer a sus 49 a&ntilde;os y dej&oacute; varias novelas y una obra de teatro. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su &uacute;ltima novela publicada fue "<em>La voz dormida</em>", premiada en la Feria del Libro de Madrid por el Gremio de Libreros de Madrid como Libro del A&ntilde;o<br />2003. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ese mismo a&ntilde;o se convoca en el Ayuntamiento de Brunete, el I Premio Literario de Novela Corta Dulce Chac&oacute;n.</p>', '.png'),
(165, 43, 1, '<p>Writer and journalist based in Brooklyn, New York. He is known for his  explorations of the seamy side of urban life, both here and abroad, and  for his offbeat and witty take on popular culture. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is a  Contributing Editor at <em>New York Magazine</em> and<em> Rolling Stone</em>.  <br />Also a frequent contributor to <em>The Village Voice, National  Geographic, Natural History Magazine, Men&rsquo;s Journal, Esquire </em>and  other publications. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Jacobson&rsquo;s articles have been adapted into  the classic TV series, &ldquo;Taxi&rdquo; and the feature film <em>American Ganster</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Jacobson was awarded the 2001 <em>Humanitas Prize</em></p>\r\n<p>.</p>', '.png'),
(130, 104, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Narrador, poeta y ensayista.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estudi&oacute; periodismo en Costa Rica y hoy es jefe de redacci&oacute;n del  diario La Naci&oacute;n. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue finalista del premio Jaime Sabines de M&eacute;xico con su poemario "<em>Canciones  del prodigioso citarista del r&iacute;o</em>".</p>', '.png'),
(131, 105, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en Chile, en 1958, y se halla comprometida con el despertar de lo m&aacute;s profundo en cada uno de nosotros. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha publicado <em>cuatro vol&uacute;menes</em> de <em>"Cuentos con alma"</em>&nbsp; que, por su gran acogida, cuenta ya con numerosas ediciones.</p>', '.png'),
(132, 106, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Periodista.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de numerosos libros<em><strong> </strong></em>de c<em>recimiento personal,  misterios del mundo y tem&aacute;ticas ins&oacute;litas</em></p>\r\n<p>.</p>', ''),
(132, 107, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Periodista. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Seguidor del movimiento Sufi desde hace m&aacute;s de 20 a&ntilde;os.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha impartido numerosos talleres y seminarios sobre la  magia de los cuentos y sus ense&ntilde;anzas secretas.</p>', '.png'),
(136, 110, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Locutor de radio y pol&iacute;tico mexicano, que se dio a conocer  como divulgador de la historia. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico. Estudi&oacute; en la Escuela Libre de  Derecho obteniendo su t&iacute;tulo profesional de abogado en 1981  con la tesis:<em> El Sistema Jur&iacute;dico del Segundo Imperio Mexicano. </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Desde 1986 es catedr&aacute;tico de la Libre de Derecho con la  materia de Historia del Derecho Patrio as&iacute; como desde 1998 Prosecretario  de la Instituci&oacute;n Educativa.</p>', '.png'),
(135, 109, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nacido en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico en 1969. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es licenciado en Relaciones Internacionales por la UNAM, donde obtuvo su t&iacute;tulo profesional con la tesis hist&oacute;rica: El financiamiento de particulares norteamericanos a la revoluci&oacute;n 1910-1914.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Catedr&aacute;tico en la Facultad de Ciencias Pol&iacute;ticas y Sociales. Actualmente colabora en las revistas DF Traves&iacute;as y Estilo M&eacute;xico. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es colaborador del programa de noticias Monitor. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Desde 1999 es titular de la columna Relicario en la secci&oacute;n Cultura del peri&oacute;dico Reforma.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es asesor de los contenidos hist&oacute;ricos de la p&aacute;gina de Internet de la Presidencia de la Rep&uacute;blica.</p>', '.png'),
(137, 111, 1, '<p>&nbsp; La destacada escritora, es tambi&eacute;n narradora, ensayista y editora;  realiz&oacute; estudios en la Escuela Nacional de Antropolog&iacute;a e Historia y la  licenciatura en Letras Hisp&aacute;nicas en la Universidad Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de  M&eacute;xico.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Parte de su obra ha sido traducida al ingl&eacute;s, al franc&eacute;s y al  alem&aacute;n.<br /> Entres sus textos destacan las novelas: <em>Ascensi&oacute;n Tun </em>(1981),  <em>La  familia vino del norte </em>(1988), <em>Imagen de H&eacute;ctor</em> (1990), <em>El  amor me juraste</em>(1998); los libros de cuentos: <em>Lides de esta&ntilde;o</em> (1984), <em>Dicen que me case yo</em> (1989) y <em>Un hombre cerca</em> (1992). <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n ha escrito ensayos y literatura infantil.</p>', '.png'),
(180, 133, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (1926-2003) fue un maestro espiritual australiano y autor de libros sobre meditaci&oacute;n, auto-conocimiento y la naturaleza espiritual del hombre y del universo.</p>\r\n<!--[if !mso]> <mce:style><!  v\\:* {behavior:url(#default#VML);} o\\:* {behavior:url(#default#VML);} w\\:* {behavior:url(#default#VML);} .shape {behavior:url(#default#VML);} --><!--[endif]-->\r\n<p><strong><span style="font-size: 11pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: "><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype id="_x0000_t75"  coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t" path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe"  filled="f" stroked="f"> <v:stroke joinstyle="miter" /> <v:formulas> <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0" /> <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0" /> <v:f eqn="sum 0 0 @1" /> <v:f eqn="prod @2 1 2" /> <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelWidth" /> <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelHeight" /> <v:f eqn="sum @0 0 1" /> <v:f eqn="prod @6 1 2" /> <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelWidth" /> <v:f eqn="sum @8 21600 0" /> <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelHeight" /> <v:f eqn="sum @10 21600 0" /> </v:formulas> <v:path o:extrusionok="f" gradientshapeok="t" o:connecttype="rect" /> <o:lock v:ext="edit" aspectratio="t" /> </v:shapetype><v:shape id="_x0000_i1025" type="#_x0000_t75" alt="" style="&rsquo;width:195pt;" mce_style="&rsquo;width:195pt;"  height:198pt&rsquo;> <v:imagedata src="file:///C:\\Users\\juan\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\msohtmlclip1\\01\\clip_image001.jpg" mce_src="file:///C:\\Users\\juan\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\msohtmlclip1\\01\\clip_image001.jpg"   o:href="http://www.barrylongweb.com/JPG/bl_sq.jpg" /> </v:shape><![endif]--><!--[if !vml]--><!--[endif]--></span></strong></p>', '.png'),
(138, 112, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Poeta, narrador, ensayista y traductor, naci&oacute; en Coronel Pringles, Buenos Aires, en el seno de una familia de origen hebreo. En 1970 se traslad&oacute; a Jerusal&eacute;n para estudiar Kabbalah y en 1978 se estableci&oacute; en Barcelona, donde se licenci&oacute; en Filolog&iacute;a Hisp&aacute;nica. Hoy combina la realizaci&oacute;n de seminarios sobre Kabbalah con su profesi&oacute;n de escritor. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Incansable viajero, ha recorrido Estados Unidos, buena parte de Sudam&eacute;rica, Europa e Israel.</p>', '.png'),
(139, 113, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Uno de los autores m&aacute;s vers&aacute;tiles y admirados en Estados Unidos.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha escrito m&aacute;s de 35 libros, incluyendo la serie de misterio que protagoniza el personaje principal de este libro, Easy Rawlin. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus obras se han traducido a 21 idiomas .<br />Sus escritos de no-ficci&oacute;n a menudo se publican en The New York Times Magazine y The Nation, entre otros.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganador de un sinn&uacute;mero de premios entre los que se cuentan el <em>O.Henry Award,</em> un <em>Grammy</em> y<em> PEN America&rsquo;s Lifetime Achievement Award</em>.&nbsp;</p>', '.png'),
(140, 114, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Investigador y escritor, experto en tradiciones m&aacute;gicas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de numerosos libros de tem&aacute;ticas ins&oacute;litas.</p>', '.png'),
(147, 120, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en M&eacute;xico, D.F., el 25 de mayo de 1961.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A los 23 a&ntilde;os escribi&oacute; y estren&oacute; en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico su primera obra teatral, "<em>Historia de amor, en s&iacute;ntesis</em>".<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su libro "<em>Crimen sin faltas de ortograf&iacute;a</em>" fue finalista en el <em>Primer Concurso Internacional de Novela Policial Plaza &amp; Jan&eacute;s</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n autora de las novelas "<em>Un cad&aacute;ver llamado Sara</em>"&nbsp; y "<em>Un Dios para Cordelia</em>"(esc&uacute;chela aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>).<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Como guionista, ha escrito "<em>El amor de tu vida S.A</em>." , dirigida por Leticia Venzor (<em>Premio del P&uacute;blico</em> durante la edici&oacute;n 1997 de la <em>Semana de Cine Iberoamericano de Cuba</em>), la serie tragic&oacute;mica "<em>Amor por televisi&oacute;n</em>" y la radionovela "<em>Tirando a matar</em>". <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n es autora de:<em> Los artistas de la t&eacute;cnica</em>: <em>Historias &iacute;ntimas del cine mexicano</em> y<em> Tomo cero del &aacute;lbum de la obscenidad: Cr&oacute;nicas y relatos sobre la vida y la guerra en Nueva York despu&eacute;s del 11 de septiembre de 2001</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(190, 120, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en M&eacute;xico, D.F., el 25 de mayo de 1961.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A los 23 a&ntilde;os escribi&oacute; y estren&oacute; en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico su primera  obra teatral, "Historia de amor, en s&iacute;ntesis".<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su libro "Crimen sin faltas de ortograf&iacute;a" fue finalista en el  Primer Concurso Internacional de Novela Policial Plaza &amp; Jan&eacute;s 1986.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n autora de las novelas "<em>Un cad&aacute;ver llamado Sara</em>"&nbsp; y  "<em>Un Dios para Cordelia</em>".<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Como guionista, ha escrito "<em>El amor de tu vida S.A</em>." ,  dirigida por Leticia Venzor (Premio del P&uacute;blico durante la edici&oacute;n 1997  de la Semana de Cine Iberoamericano de Cuba), la serie tragic&oacute;mica "<em>Amor  por televisi&oacute;n</em>" y la radionovela "<em>Tirando a matar</em>". <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n es autora de: <em>Los artistas de la t&eacute;cnica: Historias  &iacute;ntimas del cine mexicano</em> y <em>Tomo cero del &aacute;lbum de la obscenidad:  Cr&oacute;nicas y relatos sobre la vida y la guerra en Nueva York despu&eacute;s del  11 de septiembre de 2001.</em></p>', '.png'),
(157, 127, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es auxiliar cl&iacute;nico en las ramas sanitaria y de asistencia a discapacitados ps&iacute;quicos y f&iacute;sicos.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Est&aacute; diplomada en <em>salud p&uacute;blica, psicolog&iacute;a transpersonal, cuidados paliativos a enfermos terminales en intervenci&oacute;n psicobiosocial ante la muerte</em>, en la donaci&oacute;n de &oacute;rganos y en acompa&ntilde;amientos de procesos de muerte y duelo, <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n cuenta con <em>estudios en naturopat&iacute;a, hipnosis cl&iacute;nica y P.N.L. </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Colabora regularmente en distintos medios radiof&oacute;nicos e imparte talleres.</p>', ''),
(183, 135, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor bogotano, estudi&oacute; Literatura en la Universidad Javeriana  y es  comentarista de cine de la <em>Revista Semana</em> desde el 2000, y  colaborador de <em>SoHo, Arcadia</em> y<strong> </strong><em>El Tiempo</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 2007 fue elegido por la organizaci&oacute;n del <em>Hay Festival</em> como uno de los 39 escritores menores de 39 a&ntilde;os m&aacute;s destacados de  Latinoam&eacute;rica.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus poemas de <em>R&eacute;quiem</em> obtuvieron, en enero de 2000, el <em>premio  de poes&iacute;a  juvenil del Instituto de Cultura y Turismo</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dos a&ntilde;os despu&eacute;s, la editorial Alfaguara present&oacute;<em> Relato de  Navidad en  La Gran V&iacute;a</em> (esc&uacute;chelo aqu&iacute; en<strong> www.MundoHablado.com</strong>).<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Silva es el autor de: <em>Tic </em>(esc&uacute;chelo aqu&iacute; en<strong> www.MundoHablado.com</strong>), <em>El hombre de los mil nombres</em> y <em>En orden de estatura</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n escribi&oacute; la obra de teatro  <em>Pod&eacute;is ir en paz</em> , el libro de cuentos <em>Sobre la tela de una  ara&ntilde;a</em> y el poemario <em>Terran&iacute;a</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(185, 135, 1, '<p>&nbsp; Autor bogotano, estudi&oacute; Literatura en la Universidad Javeriana y es   comentarista de cine de la <em>Revista Semana</em> desde el 2000, y   colaborador de <em>SoHo, Arcadia</em> y <em>El Tiempo</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 2007  fue elegido por la organizaci&oacute;n del Hay Festival como uno  de los 39  escritores menores de 39 a&ntilde;os m&aacute;s destacados de Latinoam&eacute;rica.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Sus poemas de <em>R&eacute;quiem</em> obtuvieron, en enero de 2000, el  premio de  poes&iacute;a juvenil del <em>Instituto de Cultura y Turismo</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dos  a&ntilde;os despu&eacute;s, la editorial Alfaguara present&oacute; <em>Relato de  Navidad en  La Gran V&iacute;a</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Silva es el autor de: <em>Tic</em> y <em>Parece que va a llover</em>&nbsp;   (esc&uacute;chelos aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>), <em>El hombre de los mil   nombres</em> y <em>En orden de estatura</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n escribi&oacute; la  obra de teatro <em>Pod&eacute;is ir en paz</em> , el  libro de cuentos <em>Sobre  la tela de una ara&ntilde;a</em> y el poemario <em>Terran&iacute;a.</em></p>', '.png'),
(142, 116, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El autor es graduado de la Facultad de Derecho de la <em>Universidad de California </em>en Berkeley y cuenta tambi&eacute;n con una Maestr&iacute;a en Derecho Internacional de la<em> Universidad de Cambridge</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Esto le confiere amplio conocimiento de las leyes que ata&ntilde;en a las grandes empresas a nivel internacional.</p>', '.png'),
(143, 117, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (1933-2006) Estudi&oacute; la licenciatura en Derecho en la Universidad Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico (UNAM), donde tambi&eacute;n curs&oacute; estudios superiores de Historia de M&eacute;xico. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hasta 1959 ejerci&oacute; como abogado postulante y tambi&eacute;n el periodismo profesional.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue Jefe del Departamento de Zona Federal, posteriormente Subdirector de Bienes Inmuebles de la Secretar&iacute;a de Patrimonio Nacional; Director General de Cinematograf&iacute;a de la Secretar&iacute;a de Gobernaci&oacute;n (1964-1968); Pesidente y Director general de PIPSA; Subsecretario de Gobernaci&oacute;n (1969); Secretario de Gobernaci&oacute;n (1970-1976).</p>', '.png'),
(144, 118, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Periodista y escritora espa&ntilde;ola, nacida en Alicante, que se dedica principalmente a la novela hist&oacute;rica y de aventuras.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus libros se han traducido a varios idiomas y se han ubicado en las listas de los m&aacute;s vendidos en Espa&ntilde;a.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estudi&oacute; periodismo en la <em>Universidad Aut&oacute;noma de Barcelona</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Trabaj&oacute; durante tres a&ntilde;os en los informativos de Radio Alicante-SER, despu&eacute;s pas&oacute; a <em>Radio Nacional de Espa&ntilde;a </em>(RNE) como responsable de los informativos locales y provinciales, ejerciendo simult&aacute;neamente como corresponsal de la <em>Agencia EFE</em>, y colaborando en los diarios provinciales <em>La Verdad </em>e <em>Informaci&oacute;n.</em></p>', '.png'),
(146, 119, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lleg&oacute; a Nueva York desde su natal Ecuador junto a su madre puertorrique&ntilde;a, su padre ecuatoriano y cuatro hermanos a la edad de 18 meses. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Se cri&oacute; en El Barrio, la zona puertorrique&ntilde;a de East Harlem, donde se desarrolla <em>El vendedor de sue&ntilde;os</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estudi&oacute; redacci&oacute;n en el City College of New York.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue maestro del programa biling&uuml;e del sistema de escuelas p&uacute;blicas de la ciudad.&nbsp; Actualmente tiene a cargo una c&aacute;tedra en la <em>Universidad de Cornell</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(127, 97, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de reconocimiento internacional, se ha destacado en su  carrera literaria como una autoridad en las escrituras y fue quien  desglos&oacute; las profec&iacute;as b&iacute;blicas en las cuales est&aacute; basada toda la trama  de la serie Dejados atr&aacute;s.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n el autor de numerosos  Bestsellers cuyas ventas se acercan a los 10 millones de ejemplares.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Vive en Washington DC.</p>', '.png'),
(133, 107, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Periodista.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de numerosos libros<em><strong> </strong></em>de crecimiento personal, misterios del mundo y tem&aacute;ticas ins&oacute;litas.</p>', '.png'),
(188, 141, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en Masatepe, Nicaragua en 1942 y ha sido l&iacute;der estudiantil, abogado, vicepresidente, pero ante todo escritor.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es parte de la generaci&oacute;n de escritores latinoamericanos que surgi&oacute; despu&eacute;s del boom, y tras un largo exilio voluntario en Costa Rica y Alemania abandon&oacute; por un tiempo su carrera literaria para incorporarse a la revoluci&oacute;n sandinista que derroc&oacute; a la dictadura del &uacute;ltimo Somoza. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue vicepresidente de su pa&iacute;s en 1984. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reemprendi&oacute; la escritura con la novela <em>Castigo divino</em> (1988), que obtuvo el <em>Premio Dashiel Hammet</em> en Espa&ntilde;a y la siguiente, <em>Un baile de m&aacute;scaras</em>, gan&oacute; el <em>Premio Laure Bataillon</em> a la mejor novela extranjera aparecida en Francia en 1998, a&ntilde;o en que tambi&eacute;n recibi&oacute; el Premio Alfaguara de Novela con<em> Margarita, est&aacute; linda la mar.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Alfaguara ha publicado tambi&eacute;n sus <em>Cuentos completos</em>, con un pr&oacute;logo de Mario Benedetti (1998); <em>Mentiras verdaderas</em> (ensayos sobre la creaci&oacute;n literaria, 2001); los vol&uacute;menes de cuentos <em>Catalina y Catalina</em> (2001) y <em>El reino animal</em> (2007); as&iacute; como las novelas Sombras nada m&aacute;s (2002), <em>Mil y una muertes</em> (2005) y <em>El cielo llora por m&iacute;</em> (2008), y el libro Adi&oacute;s muchachos (2007). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aguilar ha publicado su libro de ensayos <em>Tambor olvidado</em> (2008). <em>Margarita, est&aacute; linda la mar</em> gan&oacute; adem&aacute;s el <em>Premio Latinoamericano de novela Jos&eacute; Mar&iacute;a Arguedas</em>, otorgado por <em>Casa de las Am&eacute;ricas</em> en La Habana.</p>', '.png'),
(168, 132, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en La habana en 1948 y fue eso que suelen llamar un &ldquo;ni&ntilde;o  prodigio,&rdquo; pues empez&oacute; su carrera musical a los seis a&ntilde;os, gracias a la  intuici&oacute;n y ayuda de un padre m&uacute;sico. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha sido reconocido y aclamado, actuando en muchos escenarios del  mundo, junto a grandes figuras del Jazz, la m&uacute;sica pupular y cl&aacute;sica.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganador de m&uacute;ltiples premios GRAMMY en diversas categor&iacute;as. En 2003  la prestigiosa escuela <em>Berklee de Boston</em> le otorga un doctorado <em>Honoris  Causa</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En ese mismo a&ntilde;o gana un premio nacional de periodismo por su  art&iacute;culo &ldquo;<em>Un Premio Nobel para la Mona Chita</em>&rdquo; y en el 2004  publica en Espa&ntilde;a su primera novela <em>"&iexcl;Oh, La Habana!"</em>.<em><br /></em></p>', '.png'),
(149, 121, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El autor colombiano trabaj&oacute; en publicidad, televisi&oacute;n y cine y, finalmente, escribi&oacute; <em>La Lectora</em>, su primera novela. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Publicada por Alfaguara, "<em>La lectora</em>" gan&oacute; el premio <em>Silverio Ca&ntilde;ada</em> en la Semana Negra de Gij&oacute;n, fue vendida a varias lenguas y tiene en curso una versi&oacute;n cinematogr&aacute;fica. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Luego dedic&oacute; diez a&ntilde;os de investigaci&oacute;n, escritura y viajes a la novela que lanz&oacute; en el 2010, "<em>35 Muertos</em>" , en la que a trav&eacute;s de una&nbsp; infinidad de historias y personajes, recrea la historia de Colombia de las &uacute;ltimas d&eacute;cadas.</p>', '.png'),
(150, 103, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Un maestro occidental, nacido en Nueva York el 27 de noviembre de 1936. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha explorado en profundidad el proceso creativo y la comunicaci&oacute;n, y la Medicina del Alma es el fruto de su despertar en el campo del arte a trav&eacute;s de estas especialidades. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha tratado con miles de personas que presentaban toda clase de enfermedades y problemas f&iacute;sicos y a trav&eacute;s de la Medicina del Alma ha sido testigo de curaciones aparentemente &rsquo;milagrosas&rsquo;.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue nominado en el a&ntilde;o 1974 para el Premio Geni junto con Uri Geller. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha colaborado con la <em>NASA, Esson</em> y <em>Telef&oacute;nica Sueca</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>John Lennon, Yoko Ono, Carlos Santana</em> y <em>Paul Simon</em>, se encuentraban entre su destacada lista de personalidades que han solicitado sus consejos.</p>', '.png'),
(162, 139, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reconocida psic&oacute;loga cl&iacute;nica, terapeuta, escritora, conductora de  radio y televisi&oacute;n y conferencista internacional. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La Lic. Elizabeth Rodr&iacute;guez actualmente ejerce como Psicoterapeuta  Cl&iacute;nica en consulta privada, actividad que ha venido desarrollando desde  1991. Su desempe&ntilde;o en diversos cargos le han otorgado un gran prestigio  como l&iacute;der de opini&oacute;n en temas de motivaci&oacute;n y &eacute;xito en los medios m&aacute;s  importantes de comunicaci&oacute;n. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Titular del programa &ldquo;<em>Consultorio del Alma</em>&rdquo; Grupo Acir,  Ciudad de M&eacute;xico. Conductora del programa &ldquo;<em>Sexo Diario</em>&rdquo;, Canal  11. Colaboradora del programa &ldquo;<em>Con Sello De Mujer</em>&rdquo;, TV Azteca,  Canal 13 y conductora de las c&aacute;psulas <em>VIVE MEJOR</em>&nbsp;&nbsp; y el programa &ldquo;<em>&iquest;Por  qu&eacute;?</em>&rdquo; Canal 52 MVS. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Curs&oacute; sus estudios profesionales de Psicolog&iacute;a Cl&iacute;nica en la  Universidad An&aacute;huac del Norte. Los estudios de postgrado en Psicoterapia  Psicoanal&iacute;tica para Adultos, se llevaron a cabo en el Hospital Central  Militar, Secretar&iacute;a de la Defensa Nacional. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Especialidad en Psicoterapia para ni&ntilde;os y adolescentes, Asociaci&oacute;n  Psicoanal&iacute;tica Mexicana. Es Psicoterapeuta Familiar y de Pareja por el  Instituto de la Familia (IFAC) y especialista en Psicoeducaci&oacute;n para  Parejas del Instituto Pairs de Pembrook Pines, Florida.</p>', '.png'),
(152, 122, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor hondure&ntilde;o y desde 1989 reside en Nueva York. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 1986 fund&oacute; y dirigi&oacute; en Honduras&nbsp; la revista literaria SobreVuelo. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n el autor de<em> Big Banana</em>, <em>El humano y la diosa</em>, <em>Nunca entres por Miami</em> y <em>El humano y la diosa que obtuvo</em> el <em>Premio del Instituto Latinoamericano de escritores en Estados Unidos</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La gran parte de su obra abarca distintos aspectos de la tem&aacute;tica de la vida del inmigrante latino en los Estados Unidos.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus cuentos figuran en diversas antolog&iacute;as publicadas en alem&aacute;n, ruso, ingl&eacute;s y espa&ntilde;ol.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Desde 1989 reside en Nueva York.</p>', '.png'),
(153, 123, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; El autor de los libros "<em>Demistificaci&oacute;n de una diva: la verdad sobre La Lupe</em>" y <em>"La reina es la rumba: por siempre Celia"</em> es un periodista puertorrique&ntilde;o que reside en Nueva York donde es el Editor de Entretenimineto de el diario <em>La Prensa</em>, el peri&oacute;dico en espa&ntilde;ol m&aacute;s importante que se publica en la ciudad desde 1913.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Para La Prensa el escribe la columna semana Cuadrando el Cuadrante que se especializa en la radio comercial y la manera en que cubren la comunidad latina.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Especializado en el campo del entretenimiento, particularmente la m&uacute;sica tropical y jazz, recibi&oacute; el Primer Premio por Periodismo Destacado de la Asociaci&oacute;n Nacional de Publicaciones Hispanas en el 2001 por su serie de reportajes sobre La Lupe que sirvi&oacute; de base para la obra teatral La Lupe: mi vida y mi destino.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el 2002 volvi&oacute; a recibir este premio por su reportaje sobre Los Pioneros de la 21, adem&aacute;s del<em> Premio Hispanic Media Top 100.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el 2003 recibi&oacute; el Primer Premio otra vez, pero en la categor&iacute;a de Empresas, por sus reportajes sobre la empresa de mediciones de audiencia televisiva en USA llamada Arbitron.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Graduado del <em>College de University of New York</em> y la <em>Facultad de Estudios de Posgrado de Comunicaciones P&uacute;blicas de Fordham University.</em></p>', '.png'),
(154, 124, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Doctora en filosof&iacute;a en la Universidad Complutense de Madrid.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En la actualidad se la conoce como </em><em>especialista en filosof&iacute;a advaita India.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Como fil&oacute;sofa vocacional, ha </em> (no-dual) de la<em>dedicado su vida al camino de la realizaci&oacute;n humana, lo cual constituye la esencia de todas las tradiciones, por lo que se la considera experta en &laquo;filosof&iacute;a perenne&raquo;. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pero lo que m&aacute;s destaca de su quehacer filos&oacute;fico es la d</em><em>imensi&oacute;n pr&aacute;ctica de sus ense&ntilde;anzas, consecuencia de su vivencia de lucidez, la cual se plasma en la direcci&oacute;n de retiros y seminarios.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La </em><em>Dra. Mart&iacute;n es autora de m&aacute;s de una docena de libros, entre los que recordaremos: El silencio creador (1991), Meditaciones con el Astavakra Samhita (1996), </em><em>La vida como inspiraci&oacute;n (1997), Conciencia y realidad (1998) y Upanisad (2001).<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es, adem&aacute;s, Directora de la revista Viveka, que se viene publicando sin interrupci&oacute;n desde el a&ntilde;o 1977.</em></p>', '.png'),
(155, 125, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Creci&oacute; en Kansas y en Argentina.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Se gradu&oacute; de Williams College y cuenta con una Maestr&iacute;a de la <em>Universidad de California</em> en Berkeley.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Comenz&oacute; su carrera period&iacute;stica trabajando para el <em>Wall Street Journal </em>en sus oficinas de Nueva York, Atlanta, Miami y Los Angeles.&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Durante 20 a&ntilde;os ha escrito y reportado sobre temas sociales en Estados Unidos, m&aacute;s recientemente como reportera para <em>Los Angeles Times</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus informes period&iacute;sticos han puesto de manifiesto la cruel realidad de los problemas m&aacute;s serios en el pa&iacute;s: el hambre, la adicci&oacute;n a las drogas, la inmigraci&oacute;n.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus reportajes sobre el ni&ntilde;o Hondure&ntilde;o que parte en busca de su madre ganaron&nbsp; m&aacute;s de una docena de premios, entre ellos el prestigioso <em>Premio Pulitzer</em>, el <em>Premio George Polk,</em> el <em>Gran Premio Robert F. Kennedy </em>y el<em> Premio de Periodismo Guillermo Mart&iacute;nez-M&aacute;rquez </em>que otorga la<em> Asociaci&oacute;n Nacional de Periodistas Hispanos </em>en Estados Unidos.</p>', '.png'),
(156, 126, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Escritora y editora mexicana. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estudi&oacute; historia del arte en el <em>Instituto de Cultura Superior </em>y posee dos maestr&iacute;as, una en artes y humanidades por la <em>Universidad Anahuac</em> y otra en letras modernas por la <em>Universidad Iberoamericana</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Asimismo, curs&oacute; estudios de filosof&iacute;a y victimolog&iacute;a. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "<em>Agueda: la &uacute;ltima mariposa de papel</em>" es el t&iacute;tulo de su primera novela. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es fundadora y directora de la <em>Editorial Agueda</em> que publica libros de arte y gu&iacute;as tur&iacute;sticas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A trav&eacute;s de Apoyo a las v&iacute;ctimas del delito, fundada por ella, ha impulsado una intensa campa&ntilde;a para brindar atenci&oacute;n m&eacute;dica, psicol&oacute;gica y mental a las v&iacute;ctimas de secuestro y sus familias.</p>', '.png'),
(158, 128, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nacido en Cuba, hijo de padres de ascendencia libanesa, ejerci&oacute; como maestro en las &aacute;reas rurales, posteriormente en la ciudad y en el colegio de Bel&eacute;n de La Habana. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Obtuvo el grado de Doctor en Pedagog&iacute;a en la Universidad de La Habana,en cuya Facultad de Educaci&oacute;n ejerci&oacute; como instructor adscrito y como titular interino. <br /><br />Como exhilado emigr&oacute; a Puerto Rico con su esposa, su suegra y su &uacute;nica hija, dedic&aacute;ndose al comercio y a la escritura con el logro de una serie de novelas.</p>', ''),
(159, 128, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nacido en Cuba, hijo de padres de ascendencia libanesa, ejerci&oacute; como maestro en las &aacute;reas rurales, posteriormente en la ciudad y en el colegio de Bel&eacute;n de La Habana. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Obtuvo el grado de Doctor en Pedagog&iacute;a en la Universidad de La Habana,en cuya Facultad de Educaci&oacute;n ejerci&oacute; como instructor adscrito y como titular interino. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Como exhilado emigr&oacute; a Puerto Rico con su esposa, su suegra y su &uacute;nica hija, dedic&aacute;ndose al comercio y a la escritura con el logro de una serie de novelas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em> "Los cinco nudos" </em>es otra de sus obras que tambi&eacute;n puede escuchar aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>.</p>', ''),
(160, 129, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Acad&eacute;mico, escritor, traductor, activista social, defensor de los pueblos ind&iacute;genas y cantante de &oacute;pera mexicano. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Licenciado en Derecho y maestro en Letras Iberoamericanas por la Facultad de Filosof&iacute;a y Letras de la UNAM.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue Miembro de la Academia Mexicana de la Lengua , la Real Academia Espa&ntilde;ola y la Asociaci&oacute;n de Escritores en Lenguas Ind&iacute;genas.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La Universidad Aut&oacute;noma Metropolitana le confiri&oacute; el grado de Doctor Honoris Causa por sus contribuciones en el campo de las ciencias sociales y las humanidades; la Universidad Aut&oacute;noma de Ciudad Ju&aacute;rez lo nombr&oacute; Profesor Em&eacute;rito.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Por sus distintas obras se le confiri&oacute; el Premio Nacional de Ciencias y Artes, as&iacute; como el Premio Internacional Juan Rulfo de Radio Francia Internacional, el Xavier Vilaurrutia, el Jos&eacute; Fuentes Mares y el Colima de Narrativa.</p>', '.png'),
(161, 130, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em>Autor y&nbsp; novelista, naci&oacute; en San Jos&eacute; de Ocoa, Rep&uacute;blica Dominicana, en 1941. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estudi&oacute; Ciencias Pol&iacute;ticas&nbsp; en el Instituto de Educaci&oacute;n de Coronado, en Costa Rica y Literatura en The City University of New York (Lehman College). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Varios de sus cuentos han aparecido en la revista<em> Punto 7</em> y en la antolog&iacute;a &ldquo;<em>Historias de Washington Heights y otros rincones del mundo</em>&rdquo;. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha publicado art&iacute;culos en varios peri&oacute;dicos y revistas nacionales y fue columnista del peri&oacute;dico <em>La Naci&oacute;n</em>, de New York.</p>', '.png'),
(163, 58, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Santiago, Chile, in 1953, he grew up in Chile and Mexico City, where he was a founder of the <em>Infrarealism Poetry Movement</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2666 is his posthumous work. His first full-length novel, <em>The Savage Detectives</em>, received the <em>Herralde Prize</em> and the <em>R&oacute;mulo Gallegos Prize</em> when it was published in 1998.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Roberto Bola&ntilde;o died in Blanes, Spain, at the age of fifty.</p>', '.png'),
(2, 19, 1, '<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: " lang="EN-US">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in 1959, Greenwood is a Canadian writer and editor who created the <strong><em><span style="font-family: ">Forgotten Realms Dungeons &amp; Dragons</span></em></strong> campaign setting. <br /></span><span style="font-family: " lang="EN-US">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He retains certain rights of his setting, but is essentially a freelance author. He lives in Colborne, Ontario, and works full-time as a librarian.<br /></span><span style="font-family: " lang="EN-US">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is an active freelance game designer and has written several best-selling novels in the <strong><em><span style="font-family: ">Forgotten Realms</span></em></strong> fantasy setting he created.</span></p>', '.png'),
(128, 103, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Un maestro occidental, nacido en<strong> </strong><em>Nueva York</em><em> </em>el 27 de noviembre de 1936. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha explorado en profundidad el proceso creativo y la comunicaci&oacute;n, y La <em>medicina del alma</em> es el fruto de su despertar en el campo del arte a trav&eacute;s de estas especialidades. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha tratado con miles de personas que presentaban toda clase de enfermedades y problemas f&iacute;sicos y a trav&eacute;s de La<em> medicina del alma </em>ha sido testigo de curaciones aparentemente &rsquo;<em>milagrosas</em>&rsquo;.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue nominado en el a&ntilde;o 1974 para el<strong> </strong><em>Premio Geni</em> junto con <em>Uri Geller</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha colaborado con la <em>NASA, Esson y Telef&oacute;nica Sueca</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>John Lennon, Yoko Ono, Carlos Santana y Paul Simon</em>, se encuentraban entre su destacada lista de personalidades que han solicitado sus consejos.</p>', '.png'),
(110, 86, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en Santiago, Chile.&nbsp; Se gradu&oacute; de la Universidad Cat&oacute;lica en Chile y recibi&oacute; su Maestr&iacute;a y Doctorado en Econom&iacute;a de la Universidad de Chicago.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reconocido economista y acad&eacute;mico chileno. Profesor Henry Ford II de Econom&iacute;a Empresarial Internacional en la Facultad de Postgrado de la Administraci&oacute;n Empresarial de la Uinversidad de California en Los Angeles.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de varios libros de an&aacute;lisis econ&oacute;mico tales como<em> &ldquo;El deterioro de las econom&iacute;as latinoamericanas&rdquo;,&nbsp; &ldquo;Flujos de capitales&rdquo; </em>y<em> &ldquo;Econom&iacute;as emergentes&rdquo;</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha sido<em> Presidente de LACEA (Latin American and Caribbean Economic Association)</em> y miembro del <em>Consejo de Asesores Econ&oacute;micos del Gobernador de California, Arnold Schawarzenegger.<br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus puntos de vista y opiniones a menudo son citadas en el<strong> </strong><em>New York Times, the Financial Tiems, Los Angeles Times, Wall Street Journal</em> y el <em>Economist</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(24, 70, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Richard Horatio Edgar Wallace (1875-1932) was a prolific British crime writer, journalist and playwright, who wrote 175 novels, 24 plays, and countless articles in newspapers and journals. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Over 160 films have been made of his novels, more than any other author. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the 1920s, one of <em>Wallace&rsquo;s </em>publishers claimed that a quarter of all books read in England were written by him. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is most famous today as the co-creator of "<em>King Kong</em>", writing the early screenplay and story for the movie, as well as a short story "<em>King Kong</em>" (1933) credited to him and Draycott Dell. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He was known for the J. G. Reeder detective stories, <em>The Four Just Men, the Ringer,</em> and for creating the <em>Green Archer</em> character during his lifetime.</p>', '.png'),
(29, 55, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New York Times </em>best-selling author of<em> I Am Legend, Hell House, Somewhere in Time, The Incredible Shrinking Man, A Stir of Echoes, The Beardless Warriors, The Path, Seven Steps to Midnight, Now You See It</em> ... , and<em> What Dreams May Come</em>. (Also available here in <em>MundoHablado.com</em>) <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A <em>Grand Master of Horror </em>and past winner of the <em>Bram Stoker Award for Lifetime Achievement</em>, he has also won the <em>Edgar</em>, the <em>Hugo</em>, the <em>Spur</em>, and the <em>Writer&rsquo;s Guild awards.</em></p>', '.png'),
(30, 52, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grew up on the Grant-Kohrs Ranch at Deer Lodge, Montana. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A lover of journeys, she has traveled widely, lived in Missouri, New York state, California, and Europe, and speaks five languages.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 22 years as a <em>Reader&rsquo;s Digest</em> Editor, she also had an independent career as a writer and has published 11 books. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She lives in Los Angeles.</p>', '.png'),
(31, 46, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A contemporary legend, a frequent contributor to <em>The New Yorker</em> for close to fifty years, and undisputed master of the short story whose peerless prose captures the range of human experience while evoking time and place with unequaled skill.</p>', '.png'),
(32, 49, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>New York Times</em> best-selling author of <em>Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several <em>Hugo</em> and <em>Nebula Awards</em> for his works of speculative fiction. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(33, 51, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A best-selling author of mysteries, romances, westerns, and fantasies. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A former English teacher, an Oregonian by birth and inclination, <em>Patricia Lucas White</em> lives in the Cascade Mountains, contemplates a sleeping volcano, deer, quail, and encroaching street lights, and writes whatever strikes her fancy. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her fancy is wide-ranging and curious, but it is especially attracted to fantasy.</p>', ''),
(34, 18, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; British writer, journalist, and spy, who gained enduring fame mostly for his novels <em>Robinson Crusoe</em> and<em><strong> </strong>Moll Flanders</em> (1660 - 1731). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Defoe is notable for being one of the earliest practitioners of the novel and helped popularize the genre in Britain. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In some texts he is even referred to as one of the founders, if not the founder, of the English novel. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A prolific and versatile writer, he wrote over 500 books, pamphlets and journals on various topics (including politics, crime, religion, marriage, psychology and the supernatural). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He was also the first author of ghost stories in English literature and a pioneer of economic journalism.</p>', '.png');
INSERT INTO `audiobooks_authors` (`audiobook_id`, `author_id`, `main`, `bio`, `image`) VALUES
(37, 53, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Was born in 1875 in Italy, the son of two opera singers. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Schooled in England and Switzerland, he would learn many languages. His first job was as a translator, and he would later translate for <em>British Intelligence</em> during World War I. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He began writing historical romances for fun, and after publishing his first story in the mid 1890s, produced a new book every year for the next twenty five years.</p>', '.png'),
(44, 35, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An American writer and adventurer (1876-1916) was born into poverty and largely self-educated but led an extraordinarily eventful life. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He traveled extensively and was at various times a war correspondent, oyster pirate, seaman, horticulturalist, sealer, hobo, and politician.</p>', '.png'),
(47, 21, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A German-born psychoanalyst and social philosopher who explored the interaction between psychology and society.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An internationally renowned social psychologist, psychoanalyst, humanistic philosopher and democratic socialist. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 1950 he relocated to Mexico and a post at the National Autonomous University, Mexico City, where he taught until 1965. He was invited to found the Mexican Institute of Psychoanalysis in Mexico City, which he directed till 1976. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He died in the United States in 1980.</p>', '.png'),
(48, 50, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Was born in Dublin and died in Paris (1854-1900). In between he lived flamboyantly, writing poems, short stories, plays, and one novel that were both critically successful and socially criticized for their radical ideas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A socialist libertarian pacifist anarchist, he was an actively bisexual man-about-town. He was tried for "<em>immoral acts</em>", and sentenced to hard labor in prison. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Three years after his release he died in obscurity.</p>', '.png'),
(49, 4, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; French novelist and playwright (1802-1870) was born in France, the son of an innkeeper&rsquo;s daughter and one of Napoleon&rsquo;s generals. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He moved to Paris in 1823 to make his fortune in the theater, and at twenty-eight he was one of the leading literary figures of his day. <br />His complete works were eventually to fill over <em><strong>300 volumes</strong>,</em> and his stories made him the best-known Frenchman of his age.</p>', '.png'),
(52, 66, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A poet, novelist, dramatist, and leader of the Romantic movement in France (1802-1885). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He also played an active part in political life. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His literary works best known in English include <em>Les Mis&eacute;rables, The Hunchback of Notre Dame </em>and <em>Ninety-Three</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(53, 29, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Bromley, Kent, England (1866-1946), was apprenticed to a drygoodsman and a druggist before he made his way to the <em>Royal College of Science</em> where he studied biology. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The first great writer of Science Fiction, he was also a prophet, journalist, and spokesman for progress. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aerial warfare and the atomic bomb, which he "invented" in <em>The War in the Air </em>(1908) and <em>The World Set Free </em>(1914), have proved as apocalyptically destructive as he prophesied.</p>', '.png'),
(54, 49, 1, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New York Times</em> best-selling author of<strong><em> </em></strong><em>Ender&rsquo;s Game</em>, has won several <em>HugoNebula</em> and <strong> </strong>Awards for his works of speculative fiction.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.</p>', '.png'),
(57, 13, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Won the <em>World Fantasy Award </em>and the <strong>J</strong><em>ames Tait Black Memorial Prize</em> and in 2001 was awarded the <em>Prix Utopia </em>for lifetime achievement in fantastic literature. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is married to the writer Leigh Kennedy. They live in Hastings, England, with their two children.</p>', '.png'),
(58, 58, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Santiago, Chile, in 1953. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He grew up in Chile and Mexico City, where he was a founder of the Infrarealism poetry movement. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His first full-length novel, <em>The Savage Detectives</em>, received the <em>Herralde Prize</em> and the <em>R&oacute;mulo Gallegos Prize</em> when it appeared in 1998. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Roberto Bola&ntilde;o died in Blanes, Spain, at the age of fifty.</p>', '.png'),
(59, 59, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Of Irish parentage in Edinburgh, Scotland (1859-1930). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He studied medicine at Edinburgh, but initial poverty as a young practitioner led him into authorship. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His first book introduced that prototype of the modern detective in fiction,<em> Sherlock Holmes. <br /></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He also wrote historical romances and two essays in pseudo-scientific fantasy, <em>The Lost World</em> (1912) and <em>The Poison Belt </em>(1913).</p>', '.png'),
(60, 15, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Oxford, Massachusetts (1821-1912), and attended the <em>Liberal Institute of Clinton,</em> New York. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She organized a system of free public schools in Bordentown, New Jersey in 1851. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While working for the <em>U.S. Patent Office in Washington, D.C</em>., Clara Barton launched her philanthropic career when the <em>Civil War</em> began. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She used her own money to get supplies for needy soldiers, eventually becoming supervisor of nursing for the<em> Army of the James</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her names "<em>Angel of the Battlefield</em>" and "<em>America&rsquo;s Florence Nightingale</em>" came from her work on behalf of the wounded on the battlefield regardless of risk to herself. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During the Franco-Prussian War she became associated with the <em>International Red Cross</em>, and founded the <em>American Red Cross</em> in 1873. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Largely through her efforts, the U.S. Senate confirmed the <em>Geneva Convention in 1882</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Upon her death in 1912, the <strong>Detroit Free Press</strong> wrote: "<em>She was perhaps the most perfect incarnation of mercy the modern world has known</em>."</p>', '.png'),
(62, 4, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; French novelist and playwright (1802-1870), was born in France, the son of an innkeeper&rsquo;s daughter and one of Napoleon&rsquo;s generals.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He moved to Paris in 1823 to make his fortune in the theater, and at twenty-eight he was one of the leading literary figures of his day. <br />His complete works were eventually to fill over 300 volumes, and his stories made him the best-known Frenchman of his age.</p>', '.png'),
(169, 57, 1, '<p>Called "<em>the dean of Canadian Science Fiction</em>" by the <em>Ottwa  Citizen</em> and ""just about the best Science-Fiction writer out there""  by the <em>Denver Rocky Muntain News&nbsp;</em>-- is one of&nbsp;7 authors in  history to win all three of the Science-Fiction field&rsquo;s highest honors  for best novel of the year: the  <em>Hugo Award </em>(which he won for <em>Hominids</em>),  the <em>Nebula Award </em>(which he won for<em> The Terminal Experiment</em>);  and the <em>John W. Campbell Memorial Award</em> (which he won for <em>Mindscan</em>).  <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He has written 18 novels and his short fiction has been  published in numerous magazines and anthologies. He has won 41 national  and international awards. <br /><em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; Sawyer</em> is the President  of the <em>Science Fiction Writers of America.</em></p>', '.png'),
(170, 36, 1, '<p>A newspaper reporter, magazine writer, and daily columnist for the <em>Los  Angeles Times</em> (1916-1996). <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For 37 years he chronicled or  poked fun at Los Angeles, his family and himself in a witty style that  became a defining voice for the booming city. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His columns were  distributed to almost 600 newspapers worldwide by the <em>Los Angeles  Times-Washington Post News Service</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He published 10 books,  many of them based on his columns, and won the Los Angeles chapter of  the <em>Society of Professional Journalists&rsquo; Distinguished Journalist  Award.</em></p>', '.png'),
(171, 63, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The <em>Macavity Award</em>-winning author of <em>Stealing the Dragon</em>.<br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Tim Maleeny</em> was born in New Jersey, and graduated from <em>Dartmouth  College</em> with a Computer Science degree. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Afterwards  attended <em>Columbia Business School</em> and spent several years  pursuing a career in advertising. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His on-going series with  detective <em>Cape Weathers</em> and his deadly Asian sidekick, Sally, are  eagerly awaited by his growing audience worldwide. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After a lot  of traveling around the world, he now lives in San Francisco.</p>', '.png'),
(172, 32, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A retired <em>United States Foreign Service</em> officer and a  professional historian. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is the author of <em>The Vision of  Anglo-America </em>(1987) as well as numerous articles and studies  concerning diplomatic history and government affairs.</p>', '.png'),
(175, 7, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Was born in Russia (1905-1982), graduated from the University of  Leningrad, and in 1926 came to the United States where she was  naturalized. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Her first novel, We the Living, was published in  1936. With the publication of <em>The Fountainhead</em> in 1943, she  achieved a spectacular and enduring success and her unique philosophy,  objectivism, gained a worldwide following.</p>', '.png'),
(176, 58, 1, '<p>&nbsp; Born in Santiago, Chile, in 1953, he grew up in Chile and Mexico City, where he was a founder of the <em>Infrarealism</em> poetry movement.<br /><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2666</em> is his posthumous work. His first full-length novel,<em> The Savage Detectives</em>, received the <em>Herralde Prize </em>and the<strong> </strong><em>R&oacute;mulo Gallegos Prize</em> when it was published in 1998.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Roberto Bola&ntilde;o died in Blanes, Spain, at the age of fifty.</p>', '.png'),
(177, 76, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; For 18 years was the first and only Latino writer ever to win a <em>Pulitzer  Prize for Literature.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hijuelos was born in New York City,  in Morningside Heights, Manhattan, to Cuban immigrant parents. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  His first novel, "<em>Our House in the Last World</em>", was published in  1983 and received the 1985 Rome Prize, awarded by the American Academy  in Rome. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His second novel, "<em>The Mambo Kings Play Songs of  Love</em>", received the 1990 Pulitzer Prize for Fiction. It was adapted  for the film "<em>The Mambo Kings</em>" in 1992 and as a Broadway musical  in 2005. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; His five previous novels have been translated into  twenty-five languages. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Hijuelos has taught at Hofstra  University and is currently affiliated with Duke University, where he is  a member of the faculty of the Department of English.</p>', '.png'),
(178, 77, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Widely acknowledged as one of the world&rsquo;s most skilled  practitioners of jazz piano. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; She has hosted <em>Marian  McPartland&rsquo;s Piano Jazz </em>on <em>National Public Radio </em>since 1979  and has many recordings to her credit and continues to perform in the  United States.</p>', '.png'),
(179, 50, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Born in Dublin in 1854, he won scholarships to both <em>Trinity  College</em> (Dublin) and <em>Magdalen College</em> (Oxford), where he was  heavily influenced by the radical aesthetics of Walter Pater. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Flamboyant wit and man-about-town, Wilde had a reputation that preceded  him, especially in his early career. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After publishing two  volumes of short stories between 1887 and 1891, his social-comedy plays  such as <em>Lady Windermere&rsquo;s Fan </em>and<em> The Importance of Being  Earnest </em>established his critical and commercial success.</p>', '.png'),
(173, 13, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Won the <em>World Fantasy Award </em>and the <strong>J</strong><em>ames Tait Black  Memorial Prize</em> and in 2001 was awarded the <em>Prix Utopia </em>for  lifetime achievement in fantastic literature. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He is married to  the writer Leigh Kennedy. They live in Hastings, England, with their two  children.</p>', '.png'),
(192, 90, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Toda su vida ha sido una asidua estudiante de metaf&iacute;sica.&nbsp; A pesar de nunca haberse afiilado a ning&uacute;n l&iacute;der u organizaci&oacute;n espec&iacute;fica sus exploraciones en el campo han abarcado las ense&ntilde;anzas de muchos de los m&aacute;s prominentes exponentes en los Estados Unidos.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su principal af&aacute;n es trasmitir estas ense&ntilde;anzas a la generaci&oacute;n de su hija y todos los que puedan valerse de sus revelaciones a cualquier edad.</p>', '.png'),
(134, 97, 1, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de reconocimiento internacional, se ha destacado en su carrera literaria como una autoridad en las escrituras y fue quien desglos&oacute; las profec&iacute;as b&iacute;blicas en las cuales est&aacute; basada toda la trama de la serie Dejados atr&aacute;s.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n el autor de numerosos Bestsellers cuyas ventas se acercan a los 10 millones de ejemplares.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Vive en Washington DC.</p>', '.png'),
(134, 96, 0, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Novelista y bi&oacute;grafo estadounidense.&nbsp; Ha escrito m&aacute;s de 150 libros, pero es m&aacute;s conocido por su co-autor&iacute;am con Tim LaHaye, en la serie Dejados atr&aacute;s.&nbsp; Debido a esta serie en el 2005, ambos autores se ubicaron en la&nbsp; novena posici&oacute;n de los 10 autores con&nbsp; mayor n&uacute;mero de libros vendidos en Amazon desde 1995. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 16 de sus obras se han ubicado entre los Bestsellers del New York Times (7 en la posici&oacute;n #1).&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n han registrado las m&aacute;s altas ventas en las listas de USA Today, Wall Street Journal y Publisher&rsquo;s Weekly.</p>', '.png'),
