(186, 71, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Actor y narrador hondure&ntilde;o que trabaja tanto en ingl&eacute;s como en  espa&ntilde;ol.&nbsp; <em><strong><br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong></em>Reside en Nueva York donde se ha desempe&ntilde;ado en papeles en  obras de teatro y pel&iacute;culas.&nbsp; <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganador del <em>Premio de Arte Dram&aacute;tico Franklin Furnace </em>y  fondos del <em>Manhattan Decentralization Grant. </em>&nbsp;<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entre sus cr&eacute;ditos como narrador est&aacute;n programas documentales en  espa&ntilde;ol para<em> HBO, ABC, CBS</em> y <em>CNN</em>. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Narrador de audiolibros para <em>Recorded Books</em> en Nueva York.</p>', '.png'),
(187, 65, '<p>Actriz y Narradora, fue una de las integrantes de la compa&ntilde;&iacute;a de teatro  &ldquo;<em>Repertorio espa&ntilde;ol</em>&rdquo; en la ciudad de Nueva York durante 10 a&ntilde;os.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Ganadora del <em>Premio Audie </em>2010 en la categor&iacute;a de Audiolibros en  espa&ntilde;ol por su narraci&oacute;n de &ldquo;<em>La traves&iacute;a de Enrique</em>&rdquo; de Sonia  Nazario, producido por <em>Recorded Books</em>. (tambi&eacute;n aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Tambi&eacute;n recibi&oacute; una beca de la <em>Fundaci&oacute;n Princess Grace</em>; el  premio como la Mejor Artista en el Festival de Chamizal, El Paso, por su  actuaci&oacute;n en &ldquo;<em>El burlador de Sevilla</em>&rdquo;; y el premio<em> ACE</em> por su actuaci&oacute;n en &ldquo;<em>Revoltillo</em>&rdquo; de Eduardo Machado.</p>', '.png'),
(145, 66, '<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Actor, Director, Narrador y Locutor</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cuenta con una<em><strong> </strong>Maestr&iacute;a en Comunicaciones</em> y un t&iacute;tulo universitario en <em>Arte Dram&aacute;tico</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En Nueva York complet&oacute; otra <em>Maestr&iacute;a en Teatro Educativo de la Universidad de Nueva York.&nbsp; </em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el 2010 fue<strong> </strong>nominado al prestigioso <em>Premio Audie</em> en la catagor&iacute;a de audiolibro en espa&ntilde;ol por su narraci&oacute;n en dos producciones de Recorded Books:&nbsp; <em>&ldquo;El juego del angel&rdquo; de Carlos Ruiz Zaf&oacute;n</em>" y<em> &ldquo;&iquest;Por qu&eacute; ese idiota es rico y yo no?" </em>de Robert Shemin.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus cr&eacute;ditos teatrales incluyen muchas producciones del <em>S</em><em>panish Repertory Theatre</em><strong> </strong>en Nueva York y otros teatros hispanos.&nbsp; Ha actuado en obras teatrales tales como <strong><em>&ldquo;</em></strong><em>A Man&rsquo;s a Man</em><strong><em>&rdquo; </em></strong>de Brecht.&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En televisi&oacute;n ha tenido apariciones en <strong><em>&ldquo;</em></strong><em>The Cosby Show</em><strong><em>&rdquo; </em></strong>y varias telenovelas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha grabado decenas de audiolibros para Recorded Books y la <em>American Foundation for the Blind</em></p>\r\n<p><em>.</em></p>', '.png'),
(146, 69, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Graduado de<strong> </strong>Tisch School of the Arts de New York University en la ciudad de Nueva York y ha estado trabajando <em>en y fuera de la pantalla en el cine independiente, la televisi&oacute;n, el teatro y la publicidad</em> por casi 30 a&ntilde;os. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adem&aacute;s de actor es <em>locutor en la televisi&oacute;n nacional</em> en Estados Unidos y en <em>campa&ntilde;as de radio locales</em> en la ciudad de Nueva York.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Como miembro de<em> Repertorio Espa&ntilde;ol</em>, viaj&oacute; a nivel nacional e internacional con obras contempor&aacute;neas adem&aacute;s de <em>obras cl&aacute;sicas del Siglo de Oro Espa&ntilde;ol</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Para la pantalla grande ha trabaj&oacute; en&nbsp;<strong><em> </em></strong><em>El Cantante</em>, con <em>Jennifer L&oacute;pez</em><strong> </strong>y<strong> </strong><em>Marc Anthony</em>. <br /><br />En la televisi&oacute;n todav&iacute;a pueden ver sus actuaciones en la repetici&oacute;n de los programas, <strong>Los Sopranos</strong> y <strong>Ley y orden</strong>, series ganadoras de los Premios <strong>Emmy&reg;</strong>. <br /><em><strong><br />Pupo</strong></em> tambi&eacute;n ha creado voces para el programa de variedades, <strong>The Late Show with David Letterman</strong> y <strong>Coraje, el perro cobarde</strong>, donde cre&oacute; la voz del <strong>Rey del flan</strong>.<br /><br />Ha<em> grabado cursos de espa&ntilde;ol</em> a nivel universitario, <em>doblajes</em> de pel&iacute;culas educativas, religiosas, t&eacute;cnicas y m&eacute;dicas.</p>', '.png'),
(188, 66, '<p>Actor, Director, Narrador y Locutor.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cuenta con una Maestr&iacute;a  en Comunicaciones y un t&iacute;tulo universitario en Arte Dram&aacute;tico.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  En Nueva York complet&oacute; otra <em>Maestr&iacute;a en Teatro Educativo</em> de la <em>Universidad  de Nueva York</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el 2010 fue nominado al prestigioso <em>Premio  Audie </em>en la catagor&iacute;a de audiolibro en espa&ntilde;ol por su narraci&oacute;n en  dos producciones de Recorded Books:&nbsp; &ldquo;<em>El juego del angel</em>&rdquo; de  Carlos Ruiz Zaf&oacute;n, y &ldquo;<em>&iquest;Por qu&eacute; ese idiota es rico y yo&nbsp; no?</em>" de  Robert Shemin.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus cr&eacute;ditos teatrales incluyen muchas  producciones del <em>Spanish Repertory Theatre</em> en Nueva York y otros  teatros hispanos.&nbsp; Ha actuado en obras teatrales tales como &ldquo;<em>A Man&rsquo;s a  Man</em>&rdquo; de Brecht.&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En televisi&oacute;n ha tenido apariciones en &ldquo;<em>The  Cosby Show</em>&rdquo; y varias telenovelas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha grabado decenas de  audiolibros para <em>Recorded Books </em>y la <em>American Foundation for  the Blind.</em></p>', '.png'),
(168, 81, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Con gran emotividad en su voz relata c&oacute;mo su instintiva rebeli&oacute;n, gran sentido del humor e intolerancia ante toda interferencia en el &aacute;mbito art&iacute;stico, lo llev&oacute; a salir de Cuba y exilarse en los Estados Unidos en 1980. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Esa misma rebeli&oacute;n distingue su estilo musical que busca extender los l&iacute;mites de la fusi&oacute;n de lo cl&aacute;sico, con los ritmos latinos y el jazz. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; D&rsquo;Rivera narra su obra con pasi&oacute;n y entusiasmo al hablar sobre las ra&iacute;ces afro-cubanas de sus composiciones y formaci&oacute;n musical, o cuando se expresa con humor y ah&iacute;nco sobre su vida codeandose con las grandes figuras musicales a nivel internacional.<em><br /></em></p>', '.png'),
(189, 65, '<p>Actriz y Narradora, fue una de las integrantes de la compa&ntilde;&iacute;a de teatro &ldquo;<em>Repertorio espa&ntilde;ol</em>&rdquo; en la ciudad de Nueva York durante 10 a&ntilde;os.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganadora del <em>Premio Audie </em>2010 en la categor&iacute;a de Audiolibros en espa&ntilde;ol por su narraci&oacute;n de &ldquo;<em>La traves&iacute;a de Enrique</em>&rdquo; de Sonia Nazario, producido por <em>Recorded Books</em>. (tambi&eacute;n aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n recibi&oacute; una beca de la <em>Fundaci&oacute;n Princess Grace</em>; el premio como la Mejor Artista en el Festival de Chamizal, El Paso, por su actuaci&oacute;n en &ldquo;<em>El burlador de Sevilla</em>&rdquo;; y el premio<em> ACE</em> por su actuaci&oacute;n en &ldquo;<em>Revoltillo</em>&rdquo; de Eduardo Machado.</p>', '.png'),
(189, 66, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; Actor, Director, Narrador y Locutor.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cuenta con una Maestr&iacute;a en Comunicaciones y un t&iacute;tulo universitario en Arte Dram&aacute;tico.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En Nueva York complet&oacute; otra <em>Maestr&iacute;a en Teatro Educativo</em> de la <em>Universidad de Nueva York</em>.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En el 2010 fue nominado al prestigioso <em>Premio Audie </em>en la catagor&iacute;a de audiolibro en espa&ntilde;ol por su narraci&oacute;n en dos producciones de Recorded Books:&nbsp; &ldquo;<em>El juego del angel</em>&rdquo; de Carlos Ruiz Zaf&oacute;n, y &ldquo;<em>&iquest;Por qu&eacute; ese idiota es rico y yo&nbsp; no?</em>" de Robert Shemin.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus cr&eacute;ditos teatrales incluyen muchas producciones del <em>Spanish Repertory Theatre</em> en Nueva York y otros teatros hispanos.&nbsp; Ha actuado en obras teatrales tales como &ldquo;<em>A Man&rsquo;s a Man</em>&rdquo; de Brecht.&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En televisi&oacute;n ha tenido apariciones en &ldquo;<em>The Cosby Show</em>&rdquo; y varias telenovelas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha grabado decenas de audiolibros para <em>Recorded Books </em>y la <em>American Foundation for the Blind.</em></p>', '.png'),
(192, 58, '<p>Puertorrique&ntilde;a<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Para el mercado internacional latinoamericano trabaj&oacute; durante d&eacute;cadas como productora/animadora/narradora de <em>Worldnet TV</em> y la<em> Voz de Am&eacute;rica.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;</em> &nbsp; A trav&eacute;s de los a&ntilde;os ha grabado para, entre otros, <em>National Geographic, Discovery Channel, Biblioteca del Congreso de los Estados Unidos, Banco Mundial, Departamento de Educaci&oacute;n de los Estados Unidos, Oficina del Censo de los Estados Unidos, Cruz Roja Internacional, Simon &amp; Schuster, Santillana Publishing &ndash; USA, UNESCO, Random House, Recorded Books</em> y <em>National Institutes of Health.</em><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En calidad de productora y animadora, trabaj&oacute; para los canales de TV en Washington, D.C. afiliados a la <em>ABC, CBS</em> y <em>NBC</em>. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue la creadora/productora y animadora de la co-producci&oacute;n con <em>NBC</em> de un programa de televisi&oacute;n nacional sobre temas hispanos, en ingl&eacute;s, llamado<em> LATIN TEMPO</em>.</p>', '.png'),
(195, 71, '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Actor y narrador hondure&ntilde;o que trabaja tanto en ingl&eacute;s como en espa&ntilde;ol. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reside en Nueva York donde se ha desempe&ntilde;ado en papeles en obras de teatro y pel&iacute;culas. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganador del Premio de Arte Dram&aacute;tico Franklin Furnace y fondos del Manhattan Decentralization Grant.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entre sus cr&eacute;ditos como narrador est&aacute;n programas documentales en espa&ntilde;ol para HBO, ABC, CBS y CNN.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Narrador de audiolibros para Recorded Books en Nueva York.</p>', '.png');
INSERT INTO `authors` (`id`, `name`, `bio`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1, 'Gayle Lynds', '<p>"The New York Times best-selling author of four international thrillers, including Masquerade and The Coil. She also coauthored three bestselling novels in the Covert-One series with Robert Ludlum, including The Hades Factor, which was a CBS miniseries in 2006. She has been a newspaper reporter, a magazine editor, and a think-tank editor with top-secret clearance before turning to fiction. She lives in Santa Barbara with her husband, writer Dennis Lynds. "</p>', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(2, 'A. A. Milne', '"The son of a Scottish schoolmaster(1882-1956), Milne won a scholarship to Westminster School and later read mathematics at Cambridge. \r\nHis real interest was in light-hearted writing; he edited the undergraduate magazine Granta and at 24 he became assistant editor of Punch. \r\nAfter serving as a signals officer in World War I he won additional acclaim as a playwright. His great success, however, came as a writer of childrens literature after publishing a series of verses about his young son Christopher Robin (When We Were Very Young and Now We Are Six). \r\nFollowing the acclaim received for the Winnie-the-Pooh books, Milne published several novels as well as an autobiography, Its Too Late Now (1939). His last triumph was a stage adaptation of Kenneth Grahames The Wind in the Willows called Toad of Toad Hall.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(3, 'Aaron J. Klein', '"Time magazines military and intelligence affairs correspondent in the Jerusalem Bureau. \r\nHe received the 2002 <b>Henry Luce Award</b> and has been a consultant for <b>CNN</b>. Klein was the military-security correspondent and analyst for <b>Hadashot</b> and <b>Al-Hamishmar</b>, two of Israels leading national newspapers. \r\nHe teaches at <b>Hebrew University</b> and is a Captain in the <b>Israeli Defense Forces Intelligence</b>.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(4, 'Alexander Dumas', '"French novelist and playwright (18021870), was born in France, the son of an innkeeper''s daughter and one of Napoleon''s generals. He moved to Paris in 1823 to make his fortune in the theater, and at twenty-eight he was one of the leading literary figures of his day. \r\nHis complete works were eventually to fill over 300 volumes, and his stories made him the best-known Frenchman of his age.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(5, 'Allen Shawn', 'Grew up in New York. He currently lives in Vermont and teaches at Bennington College. As a composer, he has produced a large catalog of orchestral, chamber, and piano works, as well as scores for ballet, theater, and film. He performs frequently as a pianist, and he has written for the Atlantic Monthly, the Times Literary Supplement, the New York Times Magazine, and other publications.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(6, 'Apsley Cherry-Garrard', NULL, '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(7, 'Ayn Rand', '"Was born in Russia (19051982), graduated from the University of Leningrad, and in 1926 came to the United States where she was naturalized. \r\nHer first novel, We the Living, was published in 1936. \r\nWith the publication of The Fountainhead in 1943, she achieved a spectacular and enduring success and her unique philosophy, objectivism, gained a worldwide following.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(8, 'Barbara Ehrenreich', 'BARBARA EHRENREICH is the author of several books, including the <b>New York Times</b> best-seller <i>Nickel and Dimed</i>. A frequent contributor to the <b>New York Times, Progressive</b>, and <b>Harpers</b>, and a contributing writer to <b>Time</b> magazine. She lives in Florida.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(9, 'Ben Bova', 'A six-time winner of science fictions <b>Hugo Award</b>, is the author of over 100 works of science fact and fiction. A former editor of <b>Analog</b> and former fiction editor of<b> Omni</b>, he is also a past President of the <b>National Space Society</b> and the <b>Science-Fiction Writers of America</b>. He lives in Naples, Florida.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(10, 'Bob Madgic', '"An Amherst College graduate in 1960, moved to California to attend Stanford and obtain a teaching degree.  Taught American History in the Bay Area High Schools in the 60s and later returned to Stanford for a PhD in Education.  Became principal of Los Altos High School in 1976 and later Assistant Superintendent for the District.   He retired in the early 90s.\r\nAuthor of  two books about fly fishing: <i>Pursuing Wild Trout</i> and A Guide to Californias Freshwater Fishes</i>.   Also a contributing Editor at <i> California Fly Fisher </i>magazine.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(11, 'Cash Peters', 'CASH PETERS is an award-winning British writer and broadcaster. Previously a writer and host for <b>BBC TV</b> and <b>BBC Radio</b>,. He is also a frequent contributor to <b>National Public Radio</b>''s shows <i>Marketplace</i> and <i>The Savvy Traveler</i>, where his <i>Bad Taste Tours</i> have been heard regularly since 2000, as well as a regular panelist on the <b>KUOW</b> talk show <i>Rewind</i>.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(12, 'Charles Elton', '"worked as a designer and editor in publishing before becoming a director of the literary agency Curtis Brown. \r\nSince 1991 he has worked in television and has been executive producer in drama at ITV since 2000. \r\nAmong his productions are The Railway Children, the Oscar-nominated short Syrup, Andrew Davies adaptation of Northanger Abbey, and the recent series Time of Your Life.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(13, 'Christopher Priest', '"Won the <b>World Fantasy Award</b> and the <b>James Tait Black Memorial Prize</b> and in 2001 was awarded the <b>Prix Utopia</b> for lifetime achievement in fantastic literature. \r\nHe is married to the writer <b>Leigh Kennedy</b>. They live in Hastings, England, with their two children.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(14, 'Claire Dederer', '"She writes essays and reviews for the New York Times, Vogue, Nation, and other major publications. \r\nShe lives on an island near Seattle.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(15, 'Clara Barton', '"CLARISSA HARLOWE BARTON (18211912) was born in Oxford, Massachusetts, and attended the Liberal Institute of Clinton, New York. She organized a system of free public schools in Bordentown, New Jersey in 1851. \r\nWhile working for the U.S. Patent Office in Washington, D.C., Clara Barton launched her philanthropic career when the Civil War began. She used her own money to get supplies for needy soldiers, eventually becoming supervisor of nursing for the Army of the James. \r\nHer names Angel of the Battlefield, and Americas Florence Nightingale, came from her work on behalf of the wounded on the battlefield regardless of risk to herself. During the Franco-Prussian War. \r\nShe became associated with the International Red Cross, and founded the American Red Cross in 1873. Largely through her efforts, the U.S. Senate confirmed the Geneva Convention in 1882. \r\nUpon her death in 1912, the Detroit Free Press wrote: She was perhaps the most perfect incarnation of mercy the modern world has known.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(16, 'Colonel Archibald Gracie', NULL, '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(17, 'Cornelia Read', 'CORNELIA READ was born in New York and raised in Big Sur, California. Her childhood mentors included Sufis, surfers, single moms, Black Panthers, Ansel Adams, draft dodgers, and striking farm workers. Today she lives in Berkeley, California, with her husband and two daughters.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(18, 'Daniel Defoe', '"Daniel Defoe (1660  1731) was a British writer, journalist, and spy, who gained enduring fame mostly for his novels <i>Robinson Crusoe</i> and <i>Moll Flanders</i>. \r\nDefoe is notable for being one of the earliest practitioners of the novel and helped popularize the genre in Britain. In some texts he is even referred to as one of the founders, if not the founder, of the English novel. \r\nA prolific and versatile writer, he wrote over 500 books, pamphlets and journals on various topics (including politics, crime, religion, marriage, psychology and the supernatural). He was also the first author of ghost stories in English literature and a pioneer of economic journalism.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(19, 'Ed Greenwood', '"Born in 1959, Greenwood is a Canadian writer and editor who created the <i>Forgotten Realms Dungeons & Dragons</i> campaign setting. He retains certain rights of his setting, but is essentially a freelance author. \r\nHe lives in Colborne, Ontario, and works full-time as a librarian. He is an active freelance game designer and has written several best-selling novels in the <i>Forgotten Realms</i> fantasy setting he created.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(20, 'Edith Wharton', '"Edith Wharton(18621937) was an American novelist,short story writer anddesigner. . In 1921 she was awared the Pulitzer Price for Literature for her novel The Age of Innocence,<8>making her the first woman ever to win the prestigious award.\r\nShe combined her insider''s view of America''s privileged classes with a brilliant, natural wit to write humorous and incisive novels and short stories\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(21, 'Erich Fromm', '"ERICH FROMM was a German-born psychoanalyst and social philosopher who explored the interaction between psychology and society.an internationally renowned social psychologist, psychoanalyst, humanistic philosopher and democratic socialist. \r\nIn 1950 he relocated to Mexico and a post at the National Autonomous University, Mexico City, where he taught until 1965. He was invited to found the Mexican Institute of Psychoanalysis in Mexico City, which he directed till 1976. He died in the United States in 1980.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(22, 'Ernest Shackleton', '"SIR ERNEST HENRY SHACKLETON (1874-1922) was a British explorer born in Ireland. He made his first expedition to Antarctica under Robert F. Scott. \r\nIn 1907 he commanded a south polar expedition in which the south magnetic pole was located, with vast scientific results. The journey of the Endurance was his final expedition.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(23, 'Fred Burton', 'Fred Burton was a key figure in international counterterrorism and domestic spycraft. As a member of the State Departments Diplomatic Security Service in the mid 1980s, he was on the front lines of Americas first campaign against terror. ', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(24, 'Fyodor Dostoevsky', '"Born in Moscow  (1821-1881),  the son of a surgeon. Leaving the study of engineering for literature, he published Poor Folk in 1846. \r\nAs a member of revolutionary circles in St. Petersburg, he was condemned to death in 1849. A last-minute reprieve sent him to Siberia for hard labor. Returning to St. Petersburg in 1859, he worked as a journalist and completed his masterpiece, Crime and Punishment, as well as other works, including The Idiot and The Brothers Karamazov.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(25, 'Gaston Leroux', '"French novelist (1868-1927), was born in Paris. He earned a law degree in 1889 but turned to journalism in his mid twenties and later sailed the world as a correspondent, reporting on the Russian Revolution of 1905. \r\nIn the early 1900s, he began writing novels and became best known for The Phantom of the Opera (1910). His novel The Mystery in the Yellow Room sparked the development of detective fiction as a genre.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(26, 'Greg Campbell', 'GREG CAMPBELL is an award-winning freelance journalist and editor of the <b>Fort Collins Weekly</b>. His work has appeared in the <b>Christian Science Monitor, San Francisco Chronicle</b>, and the fifth edition of <b>Lonely Planets West Africa</b> guidebook. Received the <b>American Library Association''s Notable Book of the Year</b> award. He was consultant to the film, <b>Blood Diamonds</b>.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(27, 'Greg Lawrence', 'The author or coauthor of seven previous books, including Colored Lights, Dance with Demons, Time Steps, The Shape of Love, The Little Ballerina and Her Dancing Horse, and the New York Times bestselling Dancing on My Gravethe last three edited by Jackie Onassis.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(28, 'Gustave Flaubert', '"French novelist and one of the masters of nineteenth-century fiction, was born in Rouen (1821-1880), the second son of a noted physician. Beset by ill health and personal misfortune, he led a solitary life of rigid discipline, which was reflected in his writing by his obsession with finding le mot juste (exactly the right word). \r\nHis first published novel was Madame Bovary (1857). When certain passages in Madame Bovary were judged to be offensive to public morals, Flaubert, his publisher, and his printer were tried, but acquitted.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(29, 'H. G. Wells', '"HERBERT GEORGE WELLS (1866-1946), born in Bromley, Kent, England, was apprenticed to a drygoodsman and a druggist before he made his way to the Royal College of Science where he studied biology. \r\nThe first great writer of science fiction, he was also a prophet, journalist, and spokesman for progress. Aerial warfare and the atomic bomb, which he invented in The War in the Air (1908) and The World Set Free (1914), have proved as apocalyptically destructive as he prophesied.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(30, 'H. Rider Haggard', '"Born in Norfolk, England(1856-1925). After failing the Army entrance exam, he went to Natal in 1875, as secretary to Sir Henry Bulwer, and the next year went to the Transvaal. He returned to England in 1881, married, and settled down to a literary life. \r\nHis first novel, King Solomon''s Mines, was published in 1885. He published thirty-four adventure novels during his lifetime. He was knighted in 1912.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(31, 'Heather Sellers', ' A professor of English at Hope College in Michigan, where she teaches fiction, poetry, and creative nonfiction.                                                                                                     A recipient of a National Endowment for the Arts Fellowship for Fiction and a Barnes & Noble New Discovery Writers Award, she has published widely in a variety of genres. Her books include Georgia Under Water, a collection of linked stories; Drinking Girls and Their Dresses: Poems; Page After Page, a memoir of the writing life; and Spike and Cubbys Ice Cream Island Adventure, a childrens book.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(32, 'Henry Butterfield Ryan', 'A retired United States Foreign Service officer and a professional historian. He is the author of The Vision of Anglo-America (1987) as well as numerous articles and studies concerning diplomatic history and government affairs.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(33, 'J. Campbell Bruce', '(19061996) He was a noted feature writer for the San Francisco Chronicle, a lecturer, and a regular contributor to national magazines. In addition to Escape from Alcatraz (1963), he also authored The Golden Door: The Irony of Our Immigration Policy (1954). ', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(34, 'J. Maarten Troost', 'Author of three travel books about his experiences in the Pacific Islands in <i>The Sex Lives of Cannibals</i> and <i>Getting Stoned with Savages</i>, and a 3-month trip to China in<i>Lost on Planet China</i>. His travel essays have appeared in the <b>Atlantic Monthly</b>, <b>Washington Post</b>, and other publications.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(35, 'Jack London', 'JACK LONDON (1876-1916), an American writer and adventurer, was born into poverty and largely self-educated but led an extraordinarily eventful life. He traveled extensively and was at various times a war correspondent, oyster pirate, seaman, horticulturalist, sealer, hobo, and politician. ', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(36, 'Jack Smith', 'JACK SMITH (1916-1996) was a newspaper reporter, magazine writer, and daily columnist for the <b>Los Angeles Times</b>. For 37 years he chronicled or poked fun at Los Angeles, his family and himself in a witty style that became a defining voice for the booming city. His columns were distributed to almost 600 newspapers worldwide by the Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service. He published 10 books, many of them based on his columns, and won the Los Angeles chapter of the Society of Professional Journalists'' <b>Distinguished Journalist Award</b>.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(37, 'Jeaniene Frost', '"Lives with her husband and their very spoiled dog in Florida. Although not a vampire herself, she confesses to having pale skin, wearing a lot of black, and sleeping in late whenever possible. \r\nAnd while she cant see ghosts, she loves to walk through old cemeteries. She also loves poetry and animals, but fears children and hates to cook.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(38, 'Jon Lee Anderson', 'He began working as a reporter in 1979 for the Lima Times in Peru. During the 1980s he covered Central America first for the syndicated columnist Jack Anderson and later for Time magazine. He has also written for the New York Times, Nation, Harpers, Life, and the Nation  and is the author of Guerillas: Journeys in the Insurgent World.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(39, 'Jules Verne', 'JULES VERNE (1828-1905) is considered by many the father of science fiction. Born in Nantes, France, he studied law but turned to writing opera libretti until the 1863 publication of his first Voyages extraordinairesCinq Semaines en ballon (Five Weeks in a Balloon). Its success encouraged him to produce a number of classic and prophetic science-fiction novels, including A Journey to the Center of the Earth and Twenty Thousand Leagues under the Sea.                                     Vernes stories foresaw many scientific and technological developments, including the submarine, television, and space travel.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(40, 'Karl Marlantes', 'A cum-laude graduate of Yale University and Rhodes Scholar at Oxford University, was a Marine in Vietnam, where he was awarded the Navy Cross, the Bronze Star, two Navy Commendation Medals for valor, two Purple Hearts, and ten air medals.                                                                                                                                                   He has lived and traveled all over the world and now writes full time. He and his wife, Anne, have five children and live on a small lake in Washington state.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(41, 'Kirk Douglas', '"Kirk Douglas is a born storyteller, and in this engrossing memoir, he offers wonderful tales, favorite jokes, and hard-won insights.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(42, 'Lois McMaster Bujold', '"One of the most honored writers in the fields of science fiction and fantasy, having won five Hugo Awards and three Nebula Awards. \r\nHer second novel, The Warriors Apprentice, introduced young Miles Vorkosigan, one of the most popular characters in science fiction. The mother of two, she lives in Minneapolis.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(43, 'Mark Jacobson', '"MARK JACOBSON is a writer and journalist based in Brooklyn, New York. He is known for his explorations of the seamy side of urban life, both here and abroad, and for his offbeat and witty take on popular culture. He is a Contributing Editor at New York Magazine and Rolling Stone. \r\nAlso a frequent contributor to The Village Voice, National Geographic, Natural History Magazine, Men''s Journal, Esquire and other publications. Jacobsons articles have been adapted into the classic TV series, <b>Taxi</b> and the feature film <b>AMERICAN GANGSTER</b>.Jacobson was awarded the 2001 <b>Humanitas Prize</b>.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(44, 'Mark Twain', 'MARK TWAIN, pseudonym of Samuel L. Clemens (18351910), was born in Florida, Missouri.                                                                                                                                                             A printer and later a Mississippi riverboat pilot, he adopted his pen name from riverboat lingo meaning water two fathoms deep. His masterpieces, The Adventures of Tom Sawyer (1876) and The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn (1884), are not only classics of humorous writing but also a graphic picture of nineteenth-century America.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(45, 'Matthew Goodman', 'Received an M.F.A. from Vermont College. His writing has appeared in the Harvard Review, Georgia Review, New England Review, American Scholar, and Utne Reader. A former fellow at the MacDowall and Yaddo colonies, he lives in New York City with his wife and children.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(46, 'Mavis Gallant', 'Mavis Gallant is a contemporary legend, a frequent contributor to the New Yorker for close to fifty years, and undisputed master of the short story whose peerless prose captures the range of human experience while evoking time and place with unequaled skill. ', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(47, 'Michael Codella        Bruce Bennett', '"MICHAEL CODELLA was a New York City cop for twenty years. He worked and supervised in the DEA, Secret Service Task Force, Special Frauds Squad, Missing Persons Squad, Operation 8, and several other outstanding and prestigious units throughout the city. He retired from the NYPD in 2003 as a detective sergeant. He now divides his time between television and film work, being a professional fight trainer, and running his Renzo Gracie Brazilian Jiu Jitsu academy with his family.\r\nBRUCE BENNETT is a writer whose work has appeared in the Wall Street Journal and the erstwhile New York Sun, among other publications; a guitar player who has performed and recorded with the A-Bones, Hasil Adkins, Action Swingers, Yo La Tengo, and Andre Williams, to name a few; and the writer and director of two award-winning short films, both aired on the Independent Film Channel. A Manhattan native and resident of the Lower East Side for twenty yearsincluding the period covered in Alphavillehe now lives and works in Brooklyn.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(48, 'Neil deGrasse Tyson', '"NEIL DEGRASSE TYSON is an astrophysicist with the <b>American Museum of Natural History</b>, where he serves as Director of its world-famous <b>Hayden Planetarium</b> at the <b>American Museum of Natural History</b> in Manhattan. \r\nHe is an award-winning author and a columnist for <b>Natural History</b>. \r\nA charismatic television personality, he has, since 2006, hosted <b>PBS</b>''s educational television show <b>NOVA</b> and <b>NOVA scienceNOW</b>. He has been a frequent guest on <b>The Daily Show, The Colbert Report</b>, and <b>Jeopardy</b>. \r\nAwarded the <b>NASA</b> <i>Distinguished Public Service Medal</i>, the highest civilian honor bestowed by <b>NASA</b>.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(49, 'Orson Scott Card', '<b>New York Times</b> best-selling author of <i>Enders Game</i>, has won several <b>Hugo</b> and <b>Nebula Awards</b> for his works of speculative fiction. He lives with his family in Greensboro, North Carolina.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(50, 'Oscar Wilde', '"Born in Dublin in 1854, he won scholarships to both <b>Trinity College</b> (Dublin) and <b>Magdalen College</b> (Oxford), where he was heavily influenced by the radical aesthetics of Walter Pater. \r\nFlamboyant wit and man-about-town, Wilde had a reputation that preceded him, especially in his early career. After publishing two volumes of short stories between 1887 and 1891, his social-comedy plays such as <i>Lady Windermere''s Fan</i> and <i>The Importance of Being Earnest</b> established his critical and commercial success.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(51, 'Patricia Lucas White', '"a best-selling author of mysteries, romances, westerns, and fantasies. \r\nA former English teacher, an Oregonian by birth and inclination, Patricia Lucas White lives in the Cascade Mountains, contemplates a sleeping volcano, deer, quail, and encroaching street lights, and writes whatever strikes her fancy. \r\nHer fancy is wide-ranging and curious, but it is especially attracted to fantasy.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(52, 'Patricia Nell Warren', '"PATRICIA NELL WARREN grew up on the Grant-Kohrs Ranch at Deer Lodge, Montana. A lover of journeys, she has traveled widely, lived in Missouri, New York state, California, and Europe, and speaks five languages. \r\nDuring twenty-two years as a <b>Readers Digest</b> editor, she also had an independent career as a writer and has published 11 books. She lives in Los Angeles.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(53, 'Rafael Sabatini', '"Was born in 1875 in Italy, the son of two opera singers. Schooled in England and Switzerland, he would learn many languages. His first job was as a translator, and he would later translate for British Intelligence during World War I. \r\nHe began writing historical romances for fun, and after publishing his first story in the mid 1890s, produced a new book every year for the next twenty five years.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(54, 'Richard Adams', '"Grew up in Berkshire, England, the son of a country doctor. After an education at Oxford, he spent six years in the army and then went into the Civil Service. \r\nHe has written many novels and short stories, including Shardik and The Plague Dogs.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(55, 'Richard Matheson', 'The <b>New York Times</b> best-selling author of such novels as <i>I Am Legend, Hell House, Somewhere in Time, The Incredible Shrinking Man</i>, and <i>A Stir of Echoes</i>. Named a <b>Grand Master of Horror</b> and winner of the <b>Bram Stoker Award</b> for Lifetime Achievement, he has also won the <b>Edgar</b>, the <b>Hugo</b>, the <b>Spur</b>, and the <b>Writer''s Guild</b> awards. He lives in Calabasas, California.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(56, 'Robert Falcon Scott', '"ROBERT FALCON SCOTT (6 June 186829 March 1912) was a British Royal Naval officer and explorer who led two expeditions to the Antarctic regions: the Discovery Expedition, 190104, and the ill-fated Terra Nova Expedition, 191013. \r\nDuring this second venture, Scott led a party of five to the South Pole on 17 January 1912, only to find that they had been preceded by Roald Amundsen''s Norwegian party in an unsought ""race for the Pole"". \r\nOn their return journey, Scott and his four comrades all perished because of a combination of exhaustion, hunger, and extreme cold.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(57, 'Robert J. Sawyer', '"ROBERT J. SAWYER Robert J. Sawyer -- called ""the dean of Canadian science fiction"" by the OTTAWA CITIZEN and ""just about the best science-fiction writer out there"" by the Denver ROCKY MOUNTAIN NEWS -- is one of seven authors in history to win all three of the science-fiction field''s highest honors for best novel of the year: the Hugo Award (which he won for HOMINIDS), the Nebula Award (which he won for THE TERMINAL EXPERIMENT); and the John W. Campbell Memorial Award (which he won for MINDSCAN).\r\nHe has written 18 novels and his short fiction has been published in numerous magazines and anthologies. He has won 41 national and international awards.\r\nSawyer is the President of the <b>Science Fiction Writers of America</b>.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(58, 'Roberto Bolaño', '<p>ROBERTO BOLA&Ntilde;O Bola&ntilde;o was born in Santiago, Chile, in 1953. He grew up in Chile and Mexico City, where he was a founder of the <strong>Infrarealis</strong> poetry movement. <strong>2666</strong> is his posthumous work. His first full-length novel, <em>The Savage Detectives</em>, received the <strong>Herralde Prize</strong> and the <strong>R&oacute;mulo Gallegos Prize</strong> when it appeared in 1998. Roberto Bola&ntilde;o died in Blanes, Spain, at the age of fifty.</p>', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(59, 'Sir Arthur Conan Doyle', '"Was born (1859-1930) of Irish parentage in Edinburgh, Scotland. He studied medicine at Edinburgh, but initial poverty as a young practitioner led him into authorship. \r\nHis first book introduced that prototype of the modern detective in fiction, <i>Sherlock Holmes</i>. He also wrote historical romances and two essays in pseudo-scientific fantasy, <i>The Lost World</i> (1912) and <i>The Poison Belt</i> (1913). \r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(60, 'Slavomir Rawicz', '"He lived in England for many years after the war. \r\nHe married an Englishwoman and lived in the countryside until his death in 2004. \r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(61, 'Spider Robinson', '"SPIDER ROBINSON is renowned for his <i>Callahans Place>/i> series of best-selling novels. With his wife, Jeanne, he has written the Hugo- and Nebula-winning <i>Stardance</i> series. \r\nWinner of three <b>Hugo Awards</b>, a <b>John W. Campbell Award</b> and a <b>Nebula Award</b>, he currently resides on an island near Vancouver, British Columbia, and writes a regular editorial column, <i>Future Tense,</i> for the <b>Globe/</b> and <b>Mail</b>. He is a favorite guest at sci-fi conventions across the United States and Canada.).\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(62, 'T.C. Boyle', '"Received his Ph.D in English literature from the University of Iowa and has taught creative writing at the University of Southern California since 1977. \r\nHis novels include <i>World''s End<i> -- winner of the <b>PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction</b>), and <i>Water Music<i>. \r\nHis short fiction regularly appears in such major magazines as <b>Harper''s</b> and the <b>New Yorker</b>. \r\nMuch of the appeal of Boyle''s novels and stories is his creation of outrageous characters, bizarre situations and deliberately inflated comparisons.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(63, 'Tim Maleeny', '"TIM MALEENY is the <b>Macavity Award</b>-winning author of <i>Stealing the Dragon</i>.Tim Maleeny was born in New Jersey, and graduated from <b>Dartmouth College</b>with a Computer Science. Afterwards attended Columbia Business School and spent several years pursuing a career in advertising. \r\nHis on-going series with detective Cape Weathers and his deadly Asian sidekick, Sally, are eagerly awaited by his growing audience worldwide. After a lot of traveling around the world, he now lives in San Francisco.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(64, 'Timothy Ferriss', 'His diverse background experience includes acting, holding a world record in tango, and being a national Chinese kickboxing champion.                                                He has written for Maxim and the Philadelphia Inquirer and has appeared on MTV and CBS radio. ', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(65, 'Trevanian', '"Rodney William Whitaker (June 12, 1931  Dec 14, 2005) was an American film scholar and writer who wrote several successful novels under the pen name Trevanian. Whitaker also published works as Nicholas Seare, Beñat Le Cagot and Edoard Moran. He published the non-fiction The Language of Film under his own name.\r\nWhitaker wrote in a wide variety of genres, achieved best-seller status, and published under several names, but was best known as Trevanian. Between 1972 to 1983, five of his novels sold more than a million copies each.<1> He was described as ""the only writer of airport paperbacks to be compared to Zola, Ian Fleming, Poe and Chaucer."" He revealed his real name in an interview with the New York Times in 1979.<2>\r\nHis books have been translated into more than fourteen languages.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(66, 'Victor Hugo', 'VICTOR HUGO (18021885) was a poet, novelist, dramatist, and leader of the Romantic movement in France. He also played an active part in political life. His literary works best known in English include Les Misérables, The Hunchback of Notre Dame, and Ninety-Three.', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(67, 'William L. Shirer', '"He has had a distinguished career as foreign correspondent, news commentator, and historian of the contemporary world. \r\nHe was a War Correspondent reporting from Berlin on the rise of the Nazis for the Universal News Service and for CBS. Out of these reports grew his best-sellers, Berlin Diary and The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich, which has sold more copies for the Book-of-the-Month Club than any other book in the club''s history.\r\n"', '.png', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(68, 'Walter T. Shaw', 'Started his crime career as a bagman for the Mafia and graduated to master jewel thief. He is now reformed and has written this book about his father as an act of redemption. ', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(69, 'John and Jean Silverwood', 'The Silverwoods live in California with their four children.', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(70, 'Edgar Wallace', '"Richard Horatio Edgar Wallace (1875-1932) was a prolific British crime writer, journalist and playwright, who wrote 175 novels, 24 plays, and countless articles in newspapers and journals. \r\n\r\nOver 160 films have been made of his novels, more than any other author. \r\n\r\nIn the 1920s, one of Wallace''s publishers claimed that a quarter of all books read in England were written by him. \r\n\r\nHe is most famous today as the co-creator of ""King Kong"", writing the early screenplay and story for the movie, as well as a short story ""King Kong"" (1933) credited to him and Draycott Dell. He was known for the J. G. Reeder detective stories, The Four Just Men, the Ringer, and for creating the Green Archer character during his lifetime.\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(72, 'Mark Twain', '"\r\n(18351910) was born Samuel L. Clemens in the town of Florida, Missouri.\r\n\r\nOne of the most popular and influential authors our nation has ever produced, his keen wit and incisive satire earned him praise from both critics and peers. \r\n\r\nHe has been called not only the greatest humorist of his age but the Father of American Literature.\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(74, 'Michael Codella', '"Was a New York City cop for twenty years. He worked and supervised in the DEA, Secret Service Task Force, Special Frauds Squad, Missing Persons Squad, Operation 8, and several other outstanding and prestigious units throughout the city. \r\n\r\nHe retired from the NYPD in 2003 as a detective sergeant. \r\n\r\nHe now divides his time between television and film work, being a professional fight trainer, and running his Renzo Gracie Brazilian Jiu Jitsu academy with his family.\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(75, 'Susan Richards', '"The author has a B.A. in English from the University of Colorado and a master''s degree in social work from Adelphi University. She lives in Olivebridge, New York, and teaches writing at SUNY Ulster and Marist College.\r\n\r\nShe is also the author of Saddled and Chosen Forever.\r\n\r\n[b]Authors Comments:[/b][i] Horses have enriched my life immeasurably, not the least of which was to show me how better to love people.[/i]\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(76, 'Oscar Hijuelos', '"For 18 years was the first and only Latino writer ever to win a [b]Pulitzer Prize for Literature[/b].\r\n\r\nHijuelos was born in New York City, in Morningside Heights, Manhattan, to Cuban immigrant parents.  \r\n\r\nHis first novel, [i]Our House in the Last World[/i], was published in 1983 and received the 1985 Rome Prize, awarded by the American Academy in Rome. His second novel, [i] The Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love[/i], received the 1990 ]b]Pulitzer Prize for Fiction[/b]. \r\n\r\nIt was adapted for the film [i]The Mambo Kings[/i] in 1992 and as a Broadway musical in 2005. \r\n\r\nHis five previous novels have been translated into twenty-five languages. \r\nHijuelos has taught at Hofstra University and is currently affiliated with Duke University, where he is a member of the faculty of the Department of English.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(77, 'Marian McPartland', '"Widely acknowledged as one of the worlds most skilled practitioners of jazz piano. \r\n\r\nShe has hosted Marian McPartlands Piano Jazz on National Public Radio since 1979 and  has many recordings to her credit and continues to perform in the United States."', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(78, 'A. E. W. Mason', '" (18651948) was born at Dulwich, England. \r\n\r\nA graduate of [b]Oxford[/b], he was first a professional actor before becoming a playwright. When he turned to writing fiction, he proved to be a versatile and prolific author, excelling at historical fiction, adventure fiction, social melodrama, and crime fiction. \r\n\r\nHe is perhaps best remembered today for his tales of adventure and detection, often set in exotic locales.\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(79, 'Mary Jane Robinson', 'Founder of [i]Story Books[/i], a business committed to helping others preserve their life stories. She has composed more than seventy-five personal histories in the past twenty years. She lives with her family in Naples, Florida', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(80, 'Malcolm McConnell', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(81, 'Aaron Johnston', '', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(82, 'Merian C. Cooper', '"(1893-1973) was a Director, Screenwriter and Producer. \r\n\r\nCooper started his film career with documentaries for [b]Paramount Pictures[/b] and afterwards led movie production for RKO Radio Pictures before and after World War II. \r\n\r\nThe now classic 1933 [i]King Kong[/i] film, which he co-wrote, co-directed, and appeared in, was a breakthrough in technical innovations. Cooper helped pave the way for such ground-breaking technologies as Technicolor and the widescreen process Cinerama.\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(83, 'Bruce Bennett', '"A writer whose work has appeared in the Wall Street Journal and the erstwhile New York Sun, among other publications; a guitar player who has performed and recorded with the A-Bones, Hasil Adkins, Action Swingers, Yo La Tengo, and Andre Williams, to name a few; and the writer and director of two award-winning short films, both aired on the Independent Film Channel. \r\n\r\nA Manhattan native and resident of the Lower East Side for twenty yearsincluding the period covered in Alphavillehe now lives and works in Brooklyn.\r\n"', NULL, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(84, 'Luis L&oacute;pez Nieves', '<p>Doctor en <em>literatura comparada</em>, titulado de la <strong>Universidad de Nueva York</strong>.<br /><br />Autor de "<em><strong>El coraz&oacute;n de Voltaire</strong></em>", novela aclamada por la cr&iacute;tica literaria internacional como una de las m&aacute;s originales del siglo XXI, y de <strong><em>Seva</em></strong>, uno de los mayores &eacute;xitos de la literatura caribe&ntilde;a.<br /><br />L&oacute;pez Nieves ha ganado el <strong>Premio Nacional de Literatura de Puerto Rico</strong> en dos ocasiones. Fund&oacute; el primer programa de <strong>Maestr&iacute;a</strong> <strong>en Creaci&oacute;n Literaria de Am&eacute;rica Latina en la Universidad del Sagrado Coraz&oacute;n </strong>en Puerto Rico, del cual es actualmente su regente y <em>Escritor Residente</em>. <br /><br />Tambi&eacute;n es el creador y director de la <strong>Biblioteca Digital Ciudad Seva (CiudadSeva.com)</strong>, uno de los portales ciberliterarios m&aacute;s visitados del mundo.&nbsp;<br /><br />Sus obras han sido traducidas al <em>alem&aacute;n, ingl&eacute;s, island&eacute;s, neerland&eacute;s, polaco </em>e <em>italiano. <br /></em></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(85, 'Jeffrey Siger', '<p>Naci&oacute; y se cri&oacute; en Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.&nbsp; <br /><br />Se gradu&oacute; de la <strong>Facultad de Derecho de Boston College</strong> y practicaba en una de las principales firmas de Wall Street.&nbsp; <br /><br />Dej&oacute; su vida como abogado en la ciudad de Nueva York para escribir <em>libros de intriga y misterio</em> en su querida isla paradis&iacute;aca griega de <strong>Mykonos</strong>, como s&oacute;lo alguien local pod&iacute;a hacerlo.&nbsp; <br /><br />Su obra es ahora todo un <em>fen&oacute;meno en ventas</em> en Grecia, tanto entre los turistas como la poblaci&oacute;n nativa.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(86, 'Sebastian Edwards', '<p>Naci&oacute; en Santiago, Chile.&nbsp; Se gradu&oacute; de la Universidad Cat&oacute;lica en Chile y recibi&oacute; su Maestr&iacute;a y Doctorado en Econom&iacute;a de la Universidad de Chicago.<br /><br />Reconocido economista y acad&eacute;mico chileno. Profesor Henry Ford II de Econom&iacute;a Empresarial Internacional en la Facultad de Postgrado de la Administraci&oacute;n Empresarial de la Uinversidad de California en Los Angeles.<br />&nbsp; <br />Autor de varios libros de an&aacute;lisis econ&oacute;mico tales como<em> &ldquo;El deterioro de las econom&iacute;as latinoamericanas&rdquo;,&nbsp; &ldquo;Flujos de capitales&rdquo; </em>y<em> &ldquo;Econom&iacute;as emergentes&rdquo;</em>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Ha sido<strong> Presidente de LACEA (Latin American and Caribbean Economic Association)</strong> y miembro del <strong>Consejo de Asesores Econ&oacute;micos del Gobernador de California, Arnold Schawarzenegger</strong>.<br /><br />Sus puntos de vista y opiniones a menudo son citadas en el<strong> New York Times, the Financial Tiems, Los Angeles Times, Wall Street Journal</strong> y el <strong>Economist</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(87, 'Pablo de Santis', '<p><em><strong>Pablo De Santis </strong></em>es licenciado en<strong> Letras, escritor,  periodista y guionista de c&oacute;mics</strong>. <br /><br />Su obra ha sido muy bien  recibida por el p&uacute;blico lector as&iacute; como por la cr&iacute;tica literaria  argentina y la de pa&iacute;ses como <strong>Espa&ntilde;a </strong>y <strong>Francia</strong>. <br /><br />Autor  de <strong>cinco novelas internacionalmente aclamadas</strong>, recibi&oacute; el premio  Pl<strong>aneta / Casa de Am&eacute;rica</strong> por su obra <strong><em>&ldquo;El enigma de  Par&iacute;s&rdquo;.</em></strong><br />Vive en Buenos Aires.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(88, 'Jaime Collyer', '<p>Chileno.<br /><br />Sic&oacute;logo de formaci&oacute;n, ha trabajado como <em>editor, acad&eacute;mico, traductor y columnista de prensa en Chile</em> y <em>Espa&ntilde;a</em>.<br /><br /><em><strong>Jaime Collyer</strong></em> fue uno de los protagonistas del boom editorial de los a&ntilde;os noventa conocido como la <strong>"Nueva narrativa chilena"</strong>.&nbsp;<em><strong> Collye</strong><strong>r</strong></em> se destaca y reconoce en su narrativa por el <em>erotismo, la  especulaci&oacute;n bibli&oacute;fila, el escepticismo y la insurrecci&oacute;n.</em><br /><br />Desde entonces ha seguido publicando novelas y libros de cuentos con muy buena recepci&oacute;n cr&iacute;tica y resonancia internacional.<br /><br />Entre 1981 y 1990 residi&oacute; en <em>Espa&ntilde;a</em>, donde obtuvo el <em><strong>Premio Jauja de Cuentos</strong></em> y una distinci&oacute;n de la revista <strong><em>Playboy</em></strong> en su concurso de narraciones er&oacute;ticas.<br /><br />El infiltrado, de 1989, fue galardonada como <em>la mejor novela Latinoamericana traducida al franc&eacute;s</em> y le signific&oacute; un s&oacute;lido comienzo en su trayectoria literaria.<br /><br />En 1993,<em><strong> Gente al acecho</strong></em> (<em>Premio Municipal de Literatura y Premio del Consejo Nacional del Libro y la Lectura</em>; a&ntilde;os m&aacute;s tarde el volumen fue publicado en Estados Unidos como <em><strong>People on the Prowl,</strong></em> con muy buena cr&iacute;tica) fue celebrado un&aacute;nimemente como uno de los vol&uacute;menes de cuentos mejor logrados en muchos a&ntilde;os.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(89, 'Mauricio Electorat', '<p>Escritor chileno.<br /><br /> En 1981, tras cursar dos a&ntilde;os de <strong>Periodismo y Literatura en la Universidad de Chile</strong>, se traslad&oacute; a <strong>Barcelona</strong>, donde se licenci&oacute; en <strong>Filolog&iacute;a Hisp&aacute;nica</strong> por la <strong>Universidad Central</strong>. <br /><br /><em>Considerado una de las voces narrativas m&aacute;s personales de la nuevas generaciones de escritores latinoamericanos</em>. <br /><br />En 1995 apareci&oacute; su primera novela, <strong><em>El Para&iacute;so tres veces al d&iacute;a</em></strong>, ganadora del <strong>Premio del Consejo Nacional del Libro y la Lectura y del Premio Municipal de Literatura </strong>que concede la ciudad de Santiago.<br /><br />El volumen de relatos <strong><em>"Nunca fui a Tijuana y otros cuentos"</em></strong>, publicado en Santiago en 1999, obtuvo los mismos reconocimientos en la categor&iacute;a de cuento. <br /><br />Su segunda novela, <strong><em>"La burla del tiempo"</em></strong>, gan&oacute; en <strong>Espa&ntilde;a</strong> el prestigioso <strong>Premio Biblioteca Breve </strong>en 2004 y el <strong>Premio del Consejo Nacional del Libro y la Lectura</strong> a la mejor novela chilena publicada en 2004.<br /><br />Su tercera novela "<strong><em>Las islas que van quedando"</em></strong> (Alfaguara, 2009), le vali&oacute; otra vez el<strong> Premio del Consejo Nacional del Libro y la Lectura</strong> a la mejor novela chilena in&eacute;dita de 2008. Sus tres primeras novelas han sido traducidas al franc&eacute;s.<br /><br />Desde 1987 hasta 2005 residi&oacute; en Par&iacute;s; actualmente vive en Santiago de Chile donde es <strong>profesor de literatura en la Universidad Diego Portales</strong> y<strong> columista de la Revista de Libros de El Mercurio</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(90, 'Maria C. Siccardi', '<p>Se desempe&ntilde;&oacute; durante d&eacute;cadas en los medios de comunicaci&oacute;n desde su base en la ciudad de Wahsington, D.C. para radio y televisi&oacute;n en los Estados Unidos a nivel local y nacional, y para Am&eacute;rica Latina a trav&eacute;s de los medios internacionales.</p>\r\n<p>Toda su vida ha sido una asidua estudiante de metaf&iacute;sica.&nbsp; A pesar de nunca haberse afiilado a ning&uacute;n l&iacute;der o organizaci&oacute;n espec&iacute;fica sus exploraciones en el campo han abarcado las ense&ntilde;anzas de muchos de los m&aacute;s prominentes exponentes en los Estados Unidos.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Su principal af&aacute;n siempre ha sido encontrar la forma de traducir ese conocimiento en su vida para valerse de esas ense&ntilde;anzas a pesar de haber pasado gran parte de su vida en &aacute;reas del quehacer humano donde no se reconocen.</p>\r\n<p>Ahora comparte con la generaci&oacute;n de su hija, y todos los que puedan valerse de sus revelaciones a cualquier edad, lo que ha aprendido y c&oacute;mo le han ayudado en su vida.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(91, 'Mary Summer Rain', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(92, 'Lisette Larkins', '<p>En el 2000 <em><strong>Lisette</strong></em> comenz&oacute; a trabajar como la asistente personal de <strong><em>Neale Donald Walsch</em></strong>, autor de la exitosa serie de libros de <strong><em>&ldquo;Conversaciones con Dios&rdquo;</em></strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Con su apoyo y &aacute;nimo <strong><em>Lisette</em></strong> accedi&oacute; a comenzar a revelar sus comunicaciones personales con seres cuyo prop&oacute;sito es ayudar a la evoluci&oacute;n del planeta y continuar ampliando el contacto con la poblaci&oacute;n terrestre.<br /><br />En sus libros sobre este tema: <strong><em>&ldquo;Talking to Extraterrestrials&rdquo; </em></strong>y&nbsp; <em><strong>&ldquo;Calling on Extraterrestrials"</strong></em> en que explica c&oacute;mo estos contactos son parte de la expansi&oacute;n espiritual de humanos que comienzan a aprender a caminar entre mundos y percibir otras dimensiones que nos rodean.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(93, 'Ana Martos', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
INSERT INTO `authors` (`id`, `name`, `bio`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(94, 'Ignacio Padilla', '<p>Autor mexicano contempor&aacute;neo, ejerce actualmente como <strong><em>Profesor de la Universidad Iberoamericana</em></strong> y est&aacute; considerado como uno de los m&aacute;ximos exponentes de la llamada<strong><em> Generaci&oacute;n del Crack</em></strong> y en 1996 fue uno de los impulsores de su Manifiesto. <br /><br />Ha sido galardonado con <em>media docena de permios nacionale</em>s, como el <strong>Premio Alfonso Reyes</strong>, <strong>Premio Juan de la Cabada</strong> y <strong>Premio Primavera de Novela.</strong><br /><br />Ganador del <strong>Premio Iberoamericano de Ensayo y Debate- Case de Am&eacute;rica en el 2010</strong> con su obra<strong><em> "</em><em>La isla de las tribus perdidas"</em></strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(95, 'Luis Dario Bernal Pinilla', '<p>Naci&oacute; en <strong>Bogot&aacute; </strong>(Colombia) en 1950. <br /><br />Abogado con un posgrado en <strong><em>Econom&iacute;a y Ciencias Pol&iacute;ticas</em></strong>. <br /><br />Se dedica a la literatura desde 1979, a&ntilde;o en que obtuvo el <strong>Premio<br />Nacional de Novela Infantil</strong> con su obra <strong><em>"</em><em>Catalino Bocachica"</em></strong>. <br /><br />Su quehacer como escritor est&aacute; ligado a una constante preocupaci&oacute;n<br />por incentivar y promover la lectura en ni&ntilde;os y j&oacute;venes. En este<br />campo ha colaborado como consultor con organismos de fomento<br />a la lectura y con diversos peri&oacute;dicos y revistas de <strong>Am&eacute;rica Latina </strong>y<strong><br />Espa&ntilde;a.</strong></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(96, 'Jerry B. Jenkins', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Novelista y bi&oacute;grafo estadounidense.&nbsp; Ha escrito m&aacute;s de 150 libros, pero es m&aacute;s conocido por su co-autor&iacute;am con Tim LaHaye, en la serie Dejados atr&aacute;s.&nbsp; Debido a esta serie en el 2005, ambos autores se ubicaron en la&nbsp; novena posici&oacute;n de los 10 autores con&nbsp; mayor n&uacute;mero de libros vendidos en Amazon desde 1995. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 16 de sus obras se han ubicado entre los Bestsellers del New York Times (7 en la posici&oacute;n #1).&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n han registrado las m&aacute;s altas ventas en las listas de USA Today, Wall Street Journal y Publisher&rsquo;s Weekly.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(97, 'Tim LaHaye', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor de reconocimiento internacional, se ha destacado en su carrera literaria como una autoridad en las escrituras y fue quien desglos&oacute; las profec&iacute;as b&iacute;blicas en las cuales est&aacute; basada toda la trama de la serie Dejados atr&aacute;s.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n el autor de numerosos Bestsellers cuyas ventas se acercan a los 10 millones de ejemplares.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Vive en Washington DC.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(98, 'Olafur Olafsson', '<p>Nacido en<strong> Islandia </strong>(1962) estudi&oacute; <strong>F&iacute;sica</strong> en la <strong>Universidad de Brandeis</strong>. <br /><br />Fue uno de los <strong>fundadores y Presidente de Sony Interactive Entertainment</strong>, donde supervis&oacute; el lanzamiento de la conocida consola de juegos <strong>Playstation</strong>. <br /><br />Desde 1999 es<strong> Vicepresidente de Time Warner Digital Media</strong> en Nueva York, ciudad donde reside habitualmente.<br /><br /> Es autor de varias novelas, entre ellas <strong><em>Absolution</em></strong> publicada en 1994.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(99, 'Da&iacute;na Chaviano', '<p>Naci&oacute; en <strong>La Havana</strong> en 1960 y se considera como <em>una de las tres autoras de habla hispana de fantas&iacute;a y ciencia ficci&oacute;n m&aacute;s importantes</em>&mdash;la argentina <strong><em>Ang&eacute;lica Gorodischer</em></strong> y la espa&ntilde;oal <em><strong>Elia Barcel&oacute;</strong></em> completan esa trinidad femenina.<br /><br />En 1991 abandona Cuba y se establece en los <strong>Estados Unidos</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />En 1998 logra <strong>reconocimiento internacional con el Premio Azor&iacute;n</strong> en <strong>Espa&ntilde;a</strong> por la <strong><em>mejor novela</em></strong>&nbsp; con su obra <strong><em>&ldquo;El hombre, la hembra y el hambre&rdquo;</em></strong>. &nbsp;<br /><br />En el 2004 fue la invitada de honor en la <strong>Vigesimoquinta Conferencia Internacional de lo Fant&aacute;stico en las Artes</strong>, en EE. UU.&nbsp; <em>Esta fue la primera vez que se le confiere ese honor a un autor de habla hispana</em>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(100, 'David Mart&iacute;n del Campo', '<p>Nacido en la Ciudad de <strong>M&eacute;xico </strong>el a&ntilde;o de 1952,<strong><em> David Mart&iacute;n del Campo </em></strong>se forj&oacute; inicialmente en el periodismo, carrera que estudi&oacute; en la <strong>UNAM</strong>; de hecho, fue corresponsal en <strong>Madrid </strong>y ha incursionado en todos los g&eacute;neros asociados a la labor informativa: art&iacute;culos, ensayos, cr&oacute;nicas y entrevistas publicados en medios de circulaci&oacute;n nacional como <strong>La Jornada, Unom&aacute;sUno</strong> y <strong>Reforma</strong>.<br /><br />En 1973 publica su primera novela, <strong><em>&ldquo;Las rojas son las carretas&rdquo;</em></strong>, y a la fecha cuenta con m&aacute;s de una veintena de t&iacute;tulos de elegancia estil&iacute;stica con historias ins&oacute;litas y cuativantes.&nbsp; <br /><br />Entre sus obras est&aacute;n las cr&oacute;nicas de <strong><em>Los mares de M&eacute;xico</em></strong>, <em><strong>Isla de lobos</strong></em> (<strong>Premio nacional de Novela Jos&eacute; Rub&eacute;n Romero 1987</strong>), <strong><em>Dama de noche, Alas de &aacute;ngel</em></strong> (<strong>Premio Internacional de Novela Diana-Novedades 1990</strong>),el<strong><em> A&ntilde;o del fuego,&nbsp; Las viudas de blanco, Cielito lindo</em></strong> y los cuentos infantiles de <strong><em>El tlacuache lun&aacute;tico. </em></strong></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(101, 'Dulce Chac&oacute;n', '<p>Espa&ntilde;ola {1954-2003 }, escritora galardonada con el<strong> Permio de Poes&iacute;a Ciudad de Ir&uacute;n</strong> 1995 y del <strong>Premio Azor&iacute;n</strong> 2000 con su obra<strong><em> &ldquo;Cielos de barro&rdquo;</em></strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /><br />Muri&oacute; de c&aacute;ncer a sus 49 a&ntilde;os y dej&oacute; varias novelas y una obra de teatro. <br /><br />Su &uacute;ltima novela publicada fue <strong><em>"La voz dormida"</em></strong>, premiada en la<strong> Feria del Libro de Madrid por el Gremio de Libreros de Madrid</strong> como <strong>Libro del A&ntilde;o</strong> 2003. <br /><br />Ese mismo a&ntilde;o se convoca en el <strong>Ayuntamiento de Brunete</strong>, el<strong> I Premio Literario de Novela Corta Dulce Chac&oacute;n</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(102, 'Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (1547-1616) Un novelista, poeta y dramaturgo espa&ntilde;ol. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su obra cumbre fue el immortal Don Quijote de la Mancha, a menudo designada como la primara novela moderna y uno de los grandes cl&aacute;sicos de la literatura occidental.&nbsp; Se considera una de las mejores obras de ficci&oacute;n jam&aacute;s escritas. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Toda su obra tambi&eacute;n se considera una de las m&aacute;s importantes en la literatura occidental.&nbsp; Su influencia en la lengua hispana ha sido tan fuerte que a menudo se la llama la <em>lengua de Cervantes. </em></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(103, 'Eric Rolf', '<p>Un maestro occidental, nacido en<strong> Nueva York</strong> el 27 de noviembre de 1936. <br /><br />Ha explorado en profundidad el proceso creativo y la comunicaci&oacute;n, y la <strong><em>Medicina del Alma</em></strong> es el fruto de su despertar en el campo del arte a trav&eacute;s de estas especialidades. <br /><br />Ha tratado con miles de personas que presentaban toda clase de enfermedades y problemas f&iacute;sicos y a trav&eacute;s de la <strong><em>Medicina del Alma </em></strong>ha sido testigo de curaciones aparentemente &rsquo;<em>milagrosas</em>&rsquo;.<br /><br />Fue nominado en el a&ntilde;o 1974 para el<strong> Premio Geni</strong> junto con <strong><em>Uri Geller</em></strong>. <br /><br />Ha colaborado con la <strong>NASA</strong>, <strong>Esson</strong> y <strong>Telef&oacute;nica Sueca</strong>. <br /><br /><strong><em>John Lennon, Yoko Ono, Carlos Santana</em></strong> y<strong><em> Paul Simon</em></strong>, se encuentraban entre su destacada lista de personalidades que han solicitado sus consejos.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(104, 'Carlos Cort&eacute;s', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Narrador, poeta y ensayista.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Estudi&oacute; periodismo en Costa Rica y hoy es jefe de redacci&oacute;n del diario La Naci&oacute;n. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fue finalista del premio Jaime Sabines de M&eacute;xico con su poemario "<em>Canciones del prodigioso citarista del r&iacute;o</em>".</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(105, 'Rosario G&oacute;mez', '<p>Naci&oacute; en <strong>Chile</strong>, en 1958, y se halla comprometida con el despertar de lo m&aacute;s profundo en cada uno de nosotros. <br /><br />Ha publicado <em>cuatro vol&uacute;menes</em> de <strong><em>"Cuentos con alma"</em></strong>&nbsp; que, por su gran acogida, cuenta ya con numerosas ediciones.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(106, 'Omar Kurdi', '<p>Periodista. <br /> <br />Seguidor del movimiento <strong>Sufi</strong> desde hace m&aacute;s de 20 a&ntilde;os.&nbsp; <br /><br />Ha impartido <em><strong>numerosos talleres y seminarios</strong></em> sobre la magia de los cuentos y sus ense&ntilde;anzas secretas.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(107, 'Pedro Palao Pons', '<p>Periodista.&nbsp; <br /><br />Autor de <em><strong>numerosos libros </strong></em>de c<em>recimiento personal, misterios del mundo y tem&aacute;ticas ins&oacute;litas</em>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(108, 'Yosano Sim', '<p><em>Periodista, escritora e investigadora</em> de las <em>tradiciones m&iacute;sticas</em> orientales. <br /><br />Es <em>colaboradora</em> habitual de revistas especializadas en crecimiento personal y vida alternativa.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(109, 'Alejandro Rosas', '<p>Nacido en la Ciudad de <strong>M&eacute;xico</strong> en 1969. <br /><br />Es licenciado en <em>Relaciones Internacionales </em>por la<strong> UNAM</strong>, donde obtuvo su t&iacute;tulo profesional con la tesis hist&oacute;rica: El financiamiento de particulares norteamericanos a la revoluci&oacute;n 1910-1914.<br /><br /><strong>Catedr&aacute;tico en la Facultad de Ciencias Pol&iacute;ticas y Sociales</strong>. Actualmente <strong>colabora</strong> en las revistas DF Traves&iacute;as y Estilo M&eacute;xico. <br /><br />Es colaborador del programa de noticias <strong>Monitor</strong>. <br /><br />Desde 1999 es titular de la columna<strong> Relicario</strong> en la secci&oacute;n <strong>Cultura del peri&oacute;dico</strong> <strong>Reforma</strong>.<br /><br /> Es asesor de los contenidos <em>hist&oacute;ricos de la p&aacute;gina de Internet</em> de la <em>Presidencia de la Rep&uacute;blica</em>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(110, 'Jos&eacute; Manuel Villalpando', '<p><em>Locutor de radio y pol&iacute;tico mexicano</em>, que se dio a conocer como divulgador de la historia. <br /><br />Naci&oacute; en la <strong>Ciudad de M&eacute;xico</strong>. Estudi&oacute; en la <strong>Escuela Libre de Derecho</strong> obteniendo su t&iacute;tulo profesional de <strong>abogado</strong> en 1981 con la tesis:<em> El Sistema Jur&iacute;dico del Segundo Imperio Mexicano. </em><br /><br />Desde 1986 es <strong><em>catedr&aacute;tico de la Libre de Derecho</em></strong> con la materia de Historia del Derecho Patrio as&iacute; como desde 1998 <strong>Prosecretario de la Instituci&oacute;n Educativa.</strong></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(111, 'Silvia Molina', '<p>La <em><strong>destacada escritora</strong></em>, es tambi&eacute;n <em><strong>narradora, ensayista y editora</strong></em>; realiz&oacute; estudios en la <strong>Escuela Nacional de Antropolog&iacute;a e Historia y la licenciatura en Letras Hisp&aacute;nicas en la Universidad Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico</strong>.<br /><br />Parte de su obra ha sido <strong><em>traducida al ingl&eacute;s, al franc&eacute;s y al alem&aacute;n.</em></strong> Entres sus textos destacan las novelas: <strong><em>Ascensi&oacute;n Tun</em></strong> (1981), <em><strong>La familia vino del norte</strong></em> (1988), <em><strong>Imagen de H&eacute;ctor </strong></em>(1990), <em>El amor me juraste</em> (1998); los libros de cuentos: <em>Lides de esta&ntilde;o</em> (1984), <em><strong>Dicen que me case yo</strong></em> (1989) y <em><strong>Un hombre cerca</strong></em> (1992). <br /><br />Tambi&eacute;n ha escrito ensayos y literatura infantil.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(112, 'Mario Satz', '<p><strong><em>Poeta, narrador, ensayista y traductor</em></strong>, naci&oacute; en Coronel Pringles, <strong>Buenos Aires</strong>, en el seno de una familia de origen hebreo. <br /><br />En 1970 se traslad&oacute; a <strong>Jerusal&eacute;n</strong> para estudiar <strong>Kabbalah </strong>y en 1978 se estableci&oacute; en<strong> Barcelona</strong>, donde se licenci&oacute; en<strong> Filolog&iacute;a Hisp&aacute;nica</strong>. <br /><br />Hoy combina la realizaci&oacute;n de <strong><em>seminarios sobre Kabbalah</em></strong> con su profesi&oacute;n de escritor. <br /><br />Incansable viajero, ha recorrido <strong>Estados Unidos</strong>, buena parte de <strong>Sudam&eacute;rica</strong>, <strong>Europa </strong>e<strong> Israel</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(113, 'Walter Mosley', '<p>Uno de los <em><strong>autores m&aacute;s vers&aacute;tiles y admirados en Estados Unido</strong></em>s.&nbsp; <br /><br />Ha escrito <em><strong>m&aacute;s de 35 libros</strong></em>, incluyendo la<em><strong> serie de misterio</strong></em> que protagoniza el personaje principal de este libro, <em><strong>Easy Rawlin</strong></em>. <br /><br /> Sus obras se han traducido a 21 idiomas .<br />Sus escritos de<em> no-ficci&oacute;n </em>a menudo se publican en <em><strong>The New York Times Magazine y The Nation,</strong></em> entre otros.&nbsp; <br /><br />Ganador de un sinn&uacute;mero de premios entre los que se cuentan el O.Henry Award, un <strong>Grammy y PEN America&rsquo;s Lifetime Achievement Award</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(114, 'Jose Luis Nuag', '<p><strong><em>Investigador y escrito</em></strong>r, experto en <strong><em>tradiciones m&aacute;gicas</em></strong>. <br /> <br />Autor de <em><strong>numerosos libros</strong></em> de tem&aacute;ticas ins&oacute;litas.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(115, 'Enrique Serna', '<p>&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico y estudi&oacute; Letras Hisp&aacute;nicas en la UNAM. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Se ha desempe&ntilde;ado como ensayista, narrador y guionista. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Considerado como uno de los autores contempor&aacute;neos m&aacute;s importantes  actualmente en M&eacute;xico, en el a&ntilde;o 2000 obtuvo el <em>Premio Mazatl&aacute;n de  Literatura </em>por su novela hist&oacute;rica<em> El seductor de la patria</em>.  (esc&uacute;chela aqu<em>&iacute; en </em><strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong><em>)</em><br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entre sus obras destacan las novelas U<em>no so&ntilde;aba que era rey,  Se&ntilde;orita M&eacute;xico, El miedo a los animales </em>y <em>&Aacute;ngeles del abismo</em>;  la colecci&oacute;n de ensayos, <em>Da mano</em> y <em>El orgasm&oacute;grafo</em>,&nbsp; que  permite apreciar su visi&oacute;n cr&iacute;tica de la literatura y la sociedad.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(116, 'Ovdio Diaz Espino', '<p>El autor es graduado de la <strong>Facultad de Derecho de la Universidad de California en Berkeley</strong> y cuenta tambi&eacute;n con una <strong>Maestr&iacute;a en Derecho Internacional de la Universidad de Cambridge</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Esto le confiere amplio conocimiento de las leyes que ata&ntilde;en a las grandes empresas a nivel internacional.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(117, 'Mario Moya Palencia', '<p>(1933-2006) Estudi&oacute; la licenciatura en <strong>Derecho en la Universidad Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico (UNAM)</strong>, donde tambi&eacute;n curs&oacute; estudios superiores de <strong>Historia de M&eacute;xico</strong>. <br /><br />Hasta 1959 ejerci&oacute; como abogado postulante y tambi&eacute;n el <strong>periodismo </strong>profesional.<br /><br />Fue <strong>Jefe del Departamento de Zona Federal</strong>, posteriormente <strong>Subdirector de Bienes Inmuebles de la Secretar&iacute;a de Patrimonio Nacional</strong>; <strong>Director General de Cinematograf&iacute;a de la Secretar&iacute;a de Gobernaci&oacute;n</strong> (1964-1968); <strong>Pesidente y Director general de PIPSA</strong>; <strong>Subsecretario de Gobernaci&oacute;n</strong> (1969); <strong>Secretario de Gobernaci&oacute;n</strong> (1970-1976).</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(118, 'Matilde Asensi', '<p><strong><em>Periodista y escritora espa&ntilde;ola</em></strong>, nacida en Alicante, que se dedica principalmente a la <strong><em>novela hist&oacute;rica y de aventuras</em></strong>.<br /><br />Sus libros se han <strong><em>traducido a varios idiomas</em></strong> y se han ubicado en <em><strong>las listas de los m&aacute;s vendidos en Espa&ntilde;a.<br /></strong></em><br />Estudi&oacute; <strong>periodismo </strong>en la <strong>Universidad Aut&oacute;noma de Barcelona</strong>. <br /><br />Trabaj&oacute; durante tres a&ntilde;os en los informativos de <strong>Radio Alicante-SER</strong>, despu&eacute;s pas&oacute; a <strong>Radio Nacional de Espa&ntilde;a</strong> (RNE) como responsable de los informativos locales y provinciales, ejerciendo simult&aacute;neamente como corresponsal de la <strong>Agencia EFE,</strong> y colaborando en los diarios provinciales <strong>La Verdad</strong> e<strong> Informaci&oacute;n</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(119, 'Ernesto Quiñ&oacute;nez', '<p>Lleg&oacute; a <strong>Nueva York</strong> desde su natal <strong>Ecuador</strong> junto a su <strong><em>madre puertorrique&ntilde;a</em></strong>, su <strong><em>padre ecuatoriano</em></strong> y cuatro hermanos a la edad de 18 meses. <br /><br />Se cri&oacute; en <strong>El Barrio</strong>, la zona puertorrique&ntilde;a de <strong>East Harlem</strong>, donde se desarrolla <em><strong>El vendedor de sue&ntilde;os</strong></em>. <br /><br />Estudi&oacute; redacci&oacute;n en el <strong>City College of New York</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Fue <em><strong>maestro del programa biling&uuml;e</strong></em> del sistema de escuelas p&uacute;blicas de la ciudad&nbsp; Actualmente tiene a cargo una <strong><em>c&aacute;tedra en la Universidad de Cornell.</em></strong></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(120, 'Malu Huacuja del Toro', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en M&eacute;xico, D.F., el 25 de mayo de 1961.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A los 23 a&ntilde;os escribi&oacute; y estren&oacute; en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico su primera obra teatral, "Historia de amor, en s&iacute;ntesis".<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Su libro "Crimen sin faltas de ortograf&iacute;a" fue finalista en el Primer Concurso Internacional de Novela Policial Plaza &amp; Jan&eacute;s 1986.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n autora de las novelas "<em>Un cad&aacute;ver llamado Sara</em>"&nbsp; y "<em>Un Dios para Cordelia</em>".<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Como guionista, ha escrito "<em>El amor de tu vida S.A</em>." , dirigida por Leticia Venzor (Premio del P&uacute;blico durante la edici&oacute;n 1997 de la Semana de Cine Iberoamericano de Cuba), la serie tragic&oacute;mica "<em>Amor por televisi&oacute;n</em>" y la radionovela "<em>Tirando a matar</em>". <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n es autora de: <em>Los artistas de la t&eacute;cnica: Historias &iacute;ntimas del cine mexicano</em> y <em>Tomo cero del &aacute;lbum de la obscenidad: Cr&oacute;nicas y relatos sobre la vida y la guerra en Nueva York despu&eacute;s del 11 de septiembre de 2001.</em></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(121, 'Sergio Alvarez', '<p>El autor colombiano trabaj&oacute; en <strong><em>publicidad, televisi&oacute;n y cine</em></strong> y, finalmente, escribi&oacute; La Lectora, su primera novela. <br /><br />Publicada por Alfaguara, <strong><em>"La lectora"</em></strong> gan&oacute; el premio <strong>Silverio Ca&ntilde;ada en la Semana Negra de Gij&oacute;n</strong>, fue vendida a <em>varias lengua</em>s y tiene en curso una <em>versi&oacute;n cinematogr&aacute;fica</em>. <br /><br />Luego dedic&oacute; <em>diez a&ntilde;os de investigaci&oacute;n, escritura y viajes</em> a la novela que lanz&oacute; en el 2010, <strong><em>"35 Muertos</em></strong>" , en la que a trav&eacute;s de una&nbsp; infinidad de historias y personajes, <strong>recrea la historia de Colombia</strong> de las &uacute;ltimas d&eacute;cadas.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(122, 'Roberto Quesada', '<p>Autor <em><strong>hondure&ntilde;o</strong></em> y desde 1989 reside en <strong>Nueva York</strong>. &nbsp;<br /><br />En 1986 fund&oacute; y dirigi&oacute; en Honduras&nbsp; la revista literaria <em><strong>SobreVuelo</strong></em>. <br /><br />Es tambi&eacute;n el autor de <strong><em>Big Banana, El humano y la diosa, Nunca entres por Miami</em></strong> y <strong><em>El humano y la diosa</em></strong> que obtuvo el <strong>Premio del Instituto Latinoamericano de escritores</strong> en Estados Unidos.&nbsp; <br /><br />La gran parte de su obra abarca distintos aspectos de la tem&aacute;tica de la <strong><em>vida del inmigrante latino en los Estados Unidos</em></strong>.<br /><br />Sus cuentos figuran en diversas antolog&iacute;as publicadas en <em><strong>alem&aacute;n, ruso, ingl&eacute;s y espa&ntilde;o</strong></em>l.<br /><br />Desde 1989 reside en <strong>Nueva York</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(123, 'Juan Moreno-Vel&aacute;zquez', '<p>El autor de los libros y <strong><em>"Desmitificaci&oacute;n de una diva: la verdad sobre La Lupe"</em><em>"La reina es la rumba: por siempre Celia"</em></strong> es un <strong>periodista puertorrique&ntilde;o</strong> que reside en<strong> Nueva York</strong> donde es el <strong>Editor de Entretenimineto</strong> de el diario<strong> La Prensa</strong>, el peri&oacute;dico en espa&ntilde;ol m&aacute;s importante que se publica en la ciudad desde 1913.&nbsp; <br /><br />Para <strong>La Prensa</strong> el escribe la columna semana <strong><em>Cuadrando el Cuadrante </em></strong>que se especializa en la radio comercial y la manera en que cubren la comunidad latina.<br /><br />Especializado en el campo del entretenimiento, particularmente la <em><strong>m&uacute;sica tropical y jazz</strong></em>, recibi&oacute; el <strong>Primer Premio por Periodismo Destacado de la Asociaci&oacute;n Nacional de Publicaciones Hispanas</strong> en el 2001 por su serie de reportajes sobre <strong><em>La Lupe</em></strong> que sirvi&oacute; de base para la obra teatral <strong><em>La Lupe: mi vida y mi destino</em></strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />En el 2002 volvi&oacute; a recibir este premio por su reportaje sobre <em><strong>Los Pioneros de la 21</strong></em>, adem&aacute;s del <strong>Premio Hispanic Media Top 100</strong>.<br /><br />En el 2003 recibi&oacute; el <strong>Primer Premio </strong>otra vez, pero en la categor&iacute;a de Empresas, por sus reportajes sobre la empresa de mediciones de audiencia televisiva en USA llamada <strong>Arbitron</strong>.<br /><br /><strong>Graduado del College de University of New York</strong> y la <strong>Facultad de Estudios de Posgrado de Comunicaciones P&uacute;blicas de Fordham University.</strong></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(124, 'Consuelo Mart&iacute;n', '<p><em><strong>Doctora en filosof&iacute;a</strong></em> en la <strong>Universidad Complutense de Madrid</strong>.<br /><br />En la actualidad se la conoce como <em><strong>especialista en filosof&iacute;a advaita</strong></em> (no-dual) de la<strong> India</strong>.<br /><br />Como <strong><em>fil&oacute;sofa vocacional</em></strong>, ha <em>dedicado su vida al camino de la realizaci&oacute;n humana</em>, lo cual constituye la esencia de todas las tradiciones, por lo que se la considera experta en &laquo;<strong><em>filosof&iacute;a perenne</em></strong>&raquo;. <br /><br /> Pero lo que m&aacute;s destaca de su quehacer filos&oacute;fico es la d<em>imensi&oacute;n pr&aacute;ctica de sus ense&ntilde;anzas,</em> consecuencia de su vivencia de lucidez, la cual se plasma en la direcci&oacute;n de retiros y seminarios.<br /><br />La <em><strong>Dra. Mart&iacute;n</strong></em> es <strong><em>autora de m&aacute;s de una docena de libros</em></strong>, entre los que recordaremos: <strong><em>El silencio creador</em></strong> (1991), <strong><em>Meditaciones con el Astavakra Samhita </em></strong>(1996), <em><strong>La vida como inspiraci&oacute;n</strong></em> (1997), <strong><em>Conciencia y realidad </em></strong>(1998) y <strong><em>Upanisad</em></strong> (2001).<br />&nbsp;<br />Es, adem&aacute;s,<strong><em> Directora</em></strong> de la revista <strong>Viveka</strong>, que se viene publicando sin interrupci&oacute;n desde el a&ntilde;o 1977.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(125, 'Sonia Nazario', '<p>Creci&oacute; en <strong>Kansas </strong>y en<strong> Argentina</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Se gradu&oacute; de <strong>Williams College </strong>y cuenta con una <strong>Maestr&iacute;a</strong> de la <strong>Universidad de California en Berkeley</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Comenz&oacute; su carrera period&iacute;stica trabajando para el <strong>Wall Street Journal </strong>en sus oficinas de <strong>Nueva York, Atlanta, Miami </strong>y <strong>Los Angeles</strong>.&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /><br />Durante <strong>20 a&ntilde;os</strong> ha escrito y <strong>reportado</strong> sobre temas sociales en <strong>Estados Unidos</strong>, m&aacute;s recientemente como reportera para <strong>Los Angeles Times</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Sus informes period&iacute;sticos han puesto de manifiesto la cruel realidad de los problemas m&aacute;s serios en el pa&iacute;s:<em> el hambre, la adicci&oacute;n a las drogas, la inmigraci&oacute;n</em>.<br /><br />Sus reportajes sobre el ni&ntilde;o Hondure&ntilde;o que parte en busca de su madre ganaron&nbsp; <strong><em>m&aacute;s de una docena de premios</em></strong>, entre ellos el prestigioso <strong>Premio Pulitze</strong>r, el<strong> Premio George Polk</strong>, el <strong>Gran Premio Robert F. Kennedy</strong> y el <strong>Premio de Periodismo Guillermo Mart&iacute;nez-M&aacute;rquez</strong> que otorga la A<strong>sociaci&oacute;n Nacional de Periodistas Hispanos en Estados Unidos.</strong></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(126, 'Ernestina Sodi', '<p><em><strong>Escritora y editora mexicana</strong></em>. <br /><br />Estudi&oacute; <em>historia del arte </em>en el <strong>Instituto de Cultura Superior</strong> y posee dos <em>maestr&iacute;as</em>, una en artes y humanidades por la <strong>Universidad Anahuac </strong>y otra en letras modernas por la <strong>Universidad Iberoamericana</strong>. <br /><br />Asimismo, curs&oacute; estudios de filosof&iacute;a y victimolog&iacute;a. <br /><br /><strong>"Agueda: la &uacute;ltima mariposa de papel"</strong> es el t&iacute;tulo de su primera novela. <br /><br />Es <em><strong>fundadora y directora</strong></em> de la <strong>Editorial Agueda</strong> que publica libros de arte y gu&iacute;as tur&iacute;sticas. <br /><br />A trav&eacute;s de <strong>Apoyo</strong> a las v&iacute;ctimas del delito, fundada por ella, ha impulsado una intensa campa&ntilde;a para <em>brindar atenci&oacute;n m&eacute;dica, psicol&oacute;gica y mental a las v&iacute;ctimas de secuestro y sus familias</em>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(127, 'Bibiana Balboa', '<p>Es auxiliar cl&iacute;nico en las ramas sanitaria y de asistencia a discapacitados ps&iacute;quicos y f&iacute;sicos.&nbsp; <br /><br />Est&aacute; diplomada en <em>salud p&uacute;blica, psicolog&iacute;a transpersonal, cuidados paliativos a enfermos terminales en intervenci&oacute;n psicobiosocial ante la muerte</em>, en la donaci&oacute;n de &oacute;rganos y en acompa&ntilde;amientos de procesos de muerte y duelo, <br /><br />Tambi&eacute;n cuenta con <em>estudios en naturopat&iacute;a, hipnosis cl&iacute;nica y P.N.L. </em><br /><br />Colabora regularmente en distintos medios radiof&oacute;nicos e imparte talleres.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(128, 'Juan Jacobo-Doger', '<p>Nacido en <strong>Cuba</strong>, hijo de <em>padres de ascendencia libanesa</em>, ejerci&oacute; como maestro en las &aacute;reas rurales, posteriormente en la ciudad y en el colegio de <strong>Bel&eacute;n de La Habana</strong>. <br /><br />Obtuvo el grado de <strong>Doctor en Pedagog&iacute;a en la Universidad de La Habana</strong>,en cuya Facultad de Educaci&oacute;n ejerci&oacute; como instructor adscrito y como titular interino. <br /><br />Como exhilado emigr&oacute; a <strong>Puerto Rico</strong> con su esposa, su suegra y su &uacute;nica hija, dedic&aacute;ndose al comercio y a la escritura con el logro de una serie de novelas. <br /><br /><strong><em>"Los cinco nudos" </em></strong>es otra de sus obras que tambi&eacute;n puede escuchar aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(129, 'Carlos Montemayor', '<p><em>Acad&eacute;mico, escritor, traductor, activista social, defensor de los pueblos ind&iacute;genas y cantante de &oacute;pera mexicano</em>.&nbsp; <br /><br /><strong>Licenciado en Derecho </strong>y <strong>maestro en Letras Iberoamericanas</strong> por la <strong>Facultad de Filosof&iacute;a y Letras de la UNAM</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br />Fue Miembro de la<strong> Academia Mexicana de la Lengua</strong> , la <strong>Real Academia Espa&ntilde;ola</strong> y la <strong>Asociaci&oacute;n de Escritores en Lenguas Ind&iacute;genas</strong>.<br /><br />La Universidad Aut&oacute;noma Metropolitana le confiri&oacute; el grado de <strong>Doctor Honoris Causa </strong>por sus contribuciones en el campo de las ciencias sociales y las humanidades; la <strong>Universidad Aut&oacute;noma de Ciudad Ju&aacute;rez</strong> lo nombr&oacute; <strong>Profesor Em&eacute;rito</strong>.<br /><br />Por sus distintas obras se le confiri&oacute; el <strong>Premio Nacional de Ciencias y Arte</strong>s, as&iacute; como el <strong>Premio Internacional Juan Rulfo de Radio Francia Internacional</strong>, el <strong>Xavier Vilaurrutia</strong>, el <strong>Jos&eacute; Fuentes Mares</strong> y el <strong>Colima de Narrativa</strong>.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(130, 'Viriato Senci&oacute;n', '<p><em>Autor y&nbsp; novelista</em>, naci&oacute; en San Jos&eacute; de Ocoa, <strong>Rep&uacute;blica Dominicana</strong>, en 1941. <br /><br />Estudi&oacute; <strong>Ciencias Pol&iacute;ticas&nbsp; en el Instituto de Educaci&oacute;n de Coronado</strong>, en <strong>Costa Rica</strong> y <strong>Literatura en The City University of New York</strong> (Lehman College). <br /><br />Varios de sus <em>cuentos</em> han aparecido en la revista Punto 7 y en la antolog&iacute;a <strong><em>&ldquo;Historias de Washington Heights y otros rincones del mundo&rdquo;. </em></strong><br /><br />Ha publicado art&iacute;culos en varios peri&oacute;dicos y revistas nacionales y fue <em>columnista del peri&oacute;dico</em> <strong>La Naci&oacute;n, de New York.</strong></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(132, 'Paquito DRivera', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en La habana en 1948 y fue eso que suelen llamar un &ldquo;ni&ntilde;o prodigio,&rdquo; pues empez&oacute; su carrera musical a los seis a&ntilde;os, gracias a la intuici&oacute;n y ayuda de un padre m&uacute;sico. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ha sido reconocido y aclamado, actuando en muchos escenarios del mundo, junto a grandes figuras del Jazz, la m&uacute;sica pupular y cl&aacute;sica.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ganador de m&uacute;ltiples premios GRAMMY en diversas categor&iacute;as. En 2003 la prestigiosa escuela <em>Berklee de Boston</em> le otorga un doctorado <em>Honoris Causa</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En ese mismo a&ntilde;o gana un premio nacional de periodismo por su art&iacute;culo &ldquo;<em>Un Premio Nobel para la Mona Chita</em>&rdquo; y en el 2004 publica en Espa&ntilde;a su primera novela <em>"&iexcl;Oh, La Habana!"</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Mi vida saxual,</em> escrito con un estilo ameno, humor&iacute;stico, &aacute;gil, lleno de an&eacute;cdotas y opiniones personales. Es la cr&oacute;nica de una &eacute;poca, de una ciudad, de una generaci&oacute;n.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(133, 'Barry Long', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (1926-2003) fue un maestro espiritual australiano y autor de libros sobre meditaci&oacute;n, auto-conocimiento y la naturaleza espiritual del hombre y del universo.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(134, 'Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Considerada &ldquo;<em>una de las escritoras j&oacute;venes m&aacute;s interesantes de la  literatura mexicana&rdquo;</em> naci&oacute; en la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Contribuye a revistas y suplementos culturales, estudi&oacute; letras francesas y teatro en la Universidad Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico y en sus obras a menudo y aborda conflictos en las vidas de las mujeres, as&iacute; como temas de la muerte, pero siempre con gran humor.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Proviene de  una familia con experiencia en la literatura. Su padre, Emilio Garc&iacute;a  Riera, era un cr&iacute;tico de cine. Su hermano, Jordi Garc&iacute;a Bergua, fue un galardonado  escritor y Alicia Garc&iacute;a Bergua, su hermana, es una poeta con  varios t&iacute;tulos publicados<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ana Garc&iacute;a Bergua est&aacute; incluida en la colecci&oacute;n llamada Los Mejores Cuentos Mexicanos compilado por Joaqu&iacute;n Motriz.&nbsp;</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(135, 'Ricardo Silva Romero', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; Autor bogotano, estudi&oacute; Literatura en la Universidad Javeriana y es  comentarista de cine de la <em>Revista Semana</em> desde el 2000, y  colaborador de <em>SoHo, Arcadia</em> y <em>El Tiempo</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; En 2007 fue elegido por la organizaci&oacute;n del Hay Festival como uno  de los 39 escritores menores de 39 a&ntilde;os m&aacute;s destacados de Latinoam&eacute;rica.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sus poemas de <em>R&eacute;quiem</em> obtuvieron, en enero de 2000, el  premio de poes&iacute;a juvenil del <em>Instituto de Cultura y Turismo</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dos a&ntilde;os despu&eacute;s, la editorial Alfaguara present&oacute; <em>Relato de  Navidad en La Gran V&iacute;a</em> (esc&uacute;chelo aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>).<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Silva es el autor de: <em>Tic</em>, <em>Parece que va a llover</em>&nbsp;  (esc&uacute;chelo aqu&iacute; en <strong>www.MundoHablado.com</strong>), <em>El hombre de los mil  nombres</em> y <em>En orden de estatura</em>.<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tambi&eacute;n escribi&oacute; la obra de teatro <em>Pod&eacute;is ir en paz</em> , el  libro de cuentos <em>Sobre la tela de una ara&ntilde;a</em> y el poemario <em>Terran&iacute;a.<br /> </em></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(136, 'David Unger', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en Guatemala y en la actualidad reside en la ciudad de Nueva York.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unger se gradu&oacute; de la <em>Universidad de Massachusetts, en Amherst, </em>con un BA y recibi&oacute; un MFA de <em>La Universidad de Columbia</em>. En la actualidad es profesor en la <em>City College de Nueva York </em>y es el representante de Estados Unidos para la <em>Feria Internacional del Libro de Guadalajara</em>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es el autor de <em>Ni chicha, ni limonada</em>, La vida en el tr&oacute;pico (esc&uacute;chelos aqu&iacute; en <em>www.MundoHablado.com</em>), que ha sido publicado en espa&ntilde;ol (Plaza y Jan&eacute;s, 2004),&nbsp; <em>China</em> y <em>Ni Caterpillar, ni tampoco Butterfly</em> <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Es tambi&eacute;n traductor del espa&ntilde;ol al ingl&eacute;s, incluyendo obras de Nicanor <em>Parra, Silvia Molina, Elera Garro, Barbara Jacobs, Mario Benedetti </em>y<em> Rigoberta Mench&uacute;.</em></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(137, 'Marilyn Graman', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(138, 'Maureen Walsh', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(139, 'Lizi RodrIquez', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reconocida psic&oacute;loga cl&iacute;nica, terapeuta, escritora, conductora de radio y televisi&oacute;n y conferencista internacional. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; La Lic. Elizabeth Rodr&iacute;guez actualmente ejerce como Psicoterapeuta Cl&iacute;nica en consulta privada, actividad que ha venido desarrollando desde 1991. Su desempe&ntilde;o en diversos cargos le han otorgado un gran prestigio como l&iacute;der de opini&oacute;n en temas de motivaci&oacute;n y &eacute;xito en los medios m&aacute;s importantes de comunicaci&oacute;n. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Titular del programa &ldquo;<em>Consultorio del Alma</em>&rdquo; Grupo Acir, Ciudad de M&eacute;xico. Conductora del programa &ldquo;<em>Sexo Diario</em>&rdquo;, Canal 11. Colaboradora del programa &ldquo;<em>Con Sello De Mujer</em>&rdquo;, TV Azteca, Canal 13 y conductora de las c&aacute;psulas <em>VIVE MEJOR</em>&nbsp;&nbsp; y el programa &ldquo;<em>&iquest;Por qu&eacute;?</em>&rdquo; Canal 52 MVS. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Curs&oacute; sus estudios profesionales de Psicolog&iacute;a Cl&iacute;nica en la Universidad An&aacute;huac del Norte. Los estudios de postgrado en Psicoterapia Psicoanal&iacute;tica para Adultos, se llevaron a cabo en el Hospital Central Militar, Secretar&iacute;a de la Defensa Nacional. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Especialidad en Psicoterapia para ni&ntilde;os y adolescentes, Asociaci&oacute;n Psicoanal&iacute;tica Mexicana. Es Psicoterapeuta Familiar y de Pareja por el Instituto de la Familia (IFAC) y especialista en Psicoeducaci&oacute;n para Parejas del Instituto Pairs de Pembrook Pines, Florida.</p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(140, 'Horacio Quiroga', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Naci&oacute; en Uruguay, en 1878, y muri&oacute; en Buenos Aires, Argentina, en 1937.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Inici&oacute; su obra con el g&eacute;nero de poes&iacute;a, pero se hizo conocido por sus magn&iacute;ficos cuentos. Los t&iacute;tulos que m&aacute;s repercusi&oacute;n literaria alcanzaron fueron <em>Anaconda</em>, <em>Cuentos de amor, locura y muerte</em> y <em>Cuentos de la selva.</em><br /></p>', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(141, 'Sergio Ram&iacute;rez', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(143, 'Yves Patak, MD', 'Yves, born in 1968 from a Hungarian-Swiss background, works as a general practitioner, acupuncturist (ASA), and hypnosis therapist in Zurich, Switzerland. But writing is his passion, and two of his novels have been published. During his medical studies Yves spent three months in Jamaica, where he experienced uncanny phenomena which he partly incorporated into his first novel The Healer and his current project, the thriller The Screener. Various stays in the Far East, India, Sri Lanka, and the West Indies brought him into contact with miscellaneous cultures, rites, tribal medicine, and superstition. All those experiences have strongly inspired Yves both in his work as a physician and writer.', '.jpg', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
